name: 't Kerkje op de Heuvel
description:
't Kerkje op de Heuvel, located in the Gelderse village of Heelsum, Renkum municipality, was built in the 16th century and is a Dutch national monument, also known as the Reformed Church. The church has a single nave, with a large transept added in 1859.

Built in 1517, it stands on a hill near the Heelsumse Beek valley. The church was originally commissioned as a Catholic place of worship by the Lord of Doorwerth, owner and resident of Doorwerth Castle. The location, stained glass windows, monumental Van Rossum organ, and the Van Brakell family crypt are special details. Since July 2021, Geldersch Landschap en Kasteelen owns it.

name: (Voormalige) Doopsgezinde Kerk
description: The former Mennonite Church in Middelburg, located at Hoogstraat 20, is a national monument and a former church building. Constructed in 1592, it was converted into a church in 1629 for Mennonite worship. In 1889, a new church building was put into use, and this building was sold to the Salvation Army. The Salvation Army used the building until 2009, when they moved to a new location. In the same year, the property on Hoogstraat was sold to Theaterproductiehuis Zeelandia, which was founded in 2005. The building features a simple facade with church windows, brickwork, and stone corner blocks, with the year 1592 marked on the facade. It's believed to have originally been a dwelling house converted into a church.

name: Adelaarkerk
description:
The Adelaarkerk was a church building located in Leeuwarden, Friesland. It was built in 1971-72, designed by architect Gerrit Steen. The church featured three stained glass windows by Aquino van Dijck, representing the Trinity.

The Adelaarkerk served as the third church for the Reformed Parish Leeuwarden-West. The first service was held on January 30, 1972. An organ made by Van den Berg & Wendt was installed in 1976. The last service took place on May 20, 2012. After years of vacancy, the church building was demolished in June 2024. A care complex with 67 care apartments is now located at the site.

name: Adelbertuskerk
description:
The Adelbertuskerk in Haarlem is a Roman Catholic church with an attached rectory. It is located on the corner of the Zaanenstraat and the Rijksstraatweg, in the Indischewijk district of Haarlem-Noord. The church was designed by architect Jos Margry and built in a sober neo-Gothic style between 1920 and 1929.

The church is dedicated to Saint Adelbert of Egmond. The interior features brick ribbed vaults with stuccoed panels and stained glass windows. Since 2011, the church has its own brewery run by a brewers guild. The church and its rectory are municipal monuments.

name: Adullamkerk
description:
The Adullamkerk is a church building of the Gereformeerde Gemeenten (Reformed Congregations) located on the Ds. Fransenlaan in Barneveld. It was built in 2008, designed by architectural firm Van Beijnum from Amerongen. Initially, the brick hall church had 1,376 seats, but after an expansion in 2021, it now has 1,936 seats.

Besides the main church hall, the building also includes a wedding hall and three other halls that can be converted into one large hall using a flexible wall. A parking lot with 355 spaces and an underground bicycle parking for 360 bicycles are available at the church. The church was put into use in December 2008. The highest point of the building is 34.6 meters.

name: Adventkerk
description: The Adventkerk in Leeuwarden is a church building of the Seventh-day Adventist Church, located in the Bilgaard district of the city. The church was built in 1980. The Adventkerk is a vibrant community that focuses on spiritual connection and personal growth. They aim to create a welcoming environment where members and visitors can deepen their faith. The church has been rooted in the heart of Leeuwarden since its establishment, with the mission of offering a place of peace and hope for the local population. In 2015, the Adventkerk in Friesland celebrated its 100th anniversary.

name: Adventkerk
description: The Adventkerk in Amersfoort is a church building that belongs to a congregation of the Protestant Church in the Netherlands (PKN). It is an active church community within the Protestant Municipality of Amersfoort (PGA), situated on the border between Kruiskamp and Liendert. The church has existed since 1962, and underwent renovation in the 2010s with architectural reconstruction between 2012 and 2013. The architect of the church is Teus van Hoogevest. The church also features stained glass windows and an organ. It aims to be a church that does justice to the Bible and at the same time has a message for the people of today, described as "contemporary orthodox".

name: Adventkerk
description:
The Adventkerk in Utrecht was formerly located in a residential house on Hamburgerstraat dating back to the 18th century. The building's basement has medieval origins. In 1948, the Seventh-day Adventist Church acquired the property and extensively renovated it. A large, open baptismal font was added, as adult baptism by immersion is practiced in Adventist congregations worldwide.

The building, also called "Adventkerk," was used for worship services and gatherings from 1949. After the sale of the property, which became a national monument in 1967 and was converted into an office, the baptismal font disappeared. Since 2015, the services of ZDA-Utrecht have been held on Saturday mornings in the Triumfatorkerk on Marco Pololaan in Kanaleneiland-Zuid, which the Adventists purchased and now also call "Adventkerk".

name: Adventkerk
description:
The Adventkerk, formerly known as the Sint Martinuskerk until 2006, is a church building located in West-Souburg, a district in Vlissingen. It was built in 1938 as a Roman Catholic auxiliary church for the parish of Vlissingen. During World War II, the Germans used the building as a military hospital. After the war, it was returned to the Roman Catholics and expanded in 1966, having become an independent parish church in 1964.

Weekly services ceased in 1999, and in 2005, the building was sold to the Seventh-day Adventists. In 2023, the church was updated with amenities like floor heating. The church community consists of about 70 baptized members and welcomes many visitors of various nationalities, especially during the tourist season. An amateur organ builder constructed a pipe organ for the Roman Catholic Parish, which remains in the church after its sale.

name: Agnietenkapel
description:
The Agnietenkapel, or Chapel of the Convent of Saint Agnes, is a 15th-century Gothic chapel in Amsterdam. Built in 1470, it replaced an earlier chapel that burned down. The chapel is known as the birthplace of the University of Amsterdam. In 1632, the Athenaeum Illustre, the forerunner of the UvA, was founded there.

The building served various purposes over time, including an arsenal and a city library. Today, the Agnietenkapel is used for doctoral dissertations, university ceremonies, lectures, and academic events. The gate in front of the chapel originally came from the city carpenter's yard. It has been a recognized national monument since 1970.

name: Alexanderkerk
description:
The Alexanderkerk, also known as the Oude Kerk or Sint-Alexanderkerk, is the oldest church building in Bennekom. Originally a Romanesque building from the 12th century, it was expanded over time. A tower was added, and in the 16th century, a Gothic nave with side aisles was constructed. A large transept was added in the 19th century.

The side aisles, which had been closed off since 1857, were reincorporated into the church. The pews were spaced more generously, and the stone floor was restored. The church tower is an early Gothic brick structure from the early 14th century, decorated with lesenes and friezes of brick arches containing trefoils. It features a late-Gothic bell storey and a constricted spire. The church also has a Leichel organ made in 1878.

name: Allemanskerk
description:
The Allemanskerk, also known as the Oude Sint Maartenskerk, is a church located at Dorpsstraat 878 in Oudkarspel. It was originally dedicated to Saint Martin of Tours. In the 11th century, the church was known as Aldenkercha. During the Middle Ages, it became known as the St. Maartenskerk.

In 1621, the tower's spire was destroyed by lightning. The church was restored in 1706. In 1862, both the church and the tower underwent a major restoration. In 1969, a fire largely destroyed the church, including its inventory and tower. The church was rebuilt in 1970 and has been named 'Allemanskerk' since then. The church tower's spire was deliberately omitted during the last restoration. The church has been a registered national monument since 1972.

name: Allerheiligst Hart van Jezuskerk
description: The Allerheiligst Hart van Jezuskerk, or Sacred Heart of Jesus Church, is a Roman Catholic church located in De Noord near Heerhugowaard. It was built in 1910 after the number of Catholic believers in the area increased significantly around the turn of the century. Architect C.P.W. Dessing designed it as a three-aisled basilica in Neo-Romanesque style, featuring a bell tower with a dome-shaped roof next to the entrance. Inside, the church is covered with a wooden barrel vault. Initially, the church stood alone amidst meadows, but soon after its opening, houses, shops, and a café were constructed nearby, forming the heart of the present-day village.

name: Amstel(veld)kerk
description:
The Amstelkerk is a Reformed church in central Amsterdam, located in the Grachtengordel neighborhood. Designed by Daniël Stalpaert, it was intended as a temporary wooden structure in 1668-1670. It was meant to provide church services during the fourth extension of Amsterdam in the Golden Age. However, it was never replaced by a permanent building.

Initially, the church's interior was modest, but Hendrik Springer redesigned it in a neo-Gothic style in 1842. In the late 1980s, Stadsherstel Amsterdam acquired the church and renovated it by 1990. Today, it is no longer used for regular church services but functions as a venue for concerts and events, with some parts converted into office spaces.

name: Amstelkerk
description:
The Amstelkerk in Ouderkerk aan de Amstel is a Protestant church in the Dutch province of North Holland. It is located on the west side of Ouderkerk, on the Amstel River, near the Kerkbrug (Church Bridge) over the Bullewijk.

The Amstelkerk was built in 1775 in neoclassical style. This is the fourth church on that location. The previous church was demolished because it was dilapidated. The design comes from Jacob Eduard de Witte, city architect of Amsterdam. The church has a Greek cross-shaped floor plan, a style that was more common in the 18th century. The interior is simple and austere, with hardly any decoration.

name: Andrieskerk
description:
The Andrieskerk is a church of The Christian Community, a movement for religious renewal, located in the Buitenveldert neighborhood of Amsterdam. The church is named after the apostle Andrew, who is linked to the city of Amsterdam through the three St. Andrew's crosses in the city's coat of arms.

Designed by architect H. Hupkes, the church was built in 1971 in an organic architectural style. Hupkes moved away from straight lines and rectangular windows, drawing inspiration from crystals to bring back the human scale. The roof is finished with copper plates that turn green over time. Inside, a large 200 m² mural behind the altar depicts death and resurrection as its central theme. The windows were created by the German glass artist Udo Zembok.

name: Annunciatenkerk
description: The Annunciatenklooster in Maastricht featured a spacious double chapel, consisting of an upper choir and a lower church. The chapel's construction was largely funded by provost Boonen, who had his family coat of arms displayed in various places within it. Inside the chapel, a replica of the statue of Our Lady of Scherpenheuvel was present. In 1798, the chapel was demolished.

name: Antonietenkerk
description: The Antonieten monastery in Maastricht was a commandery of the Order of Saint Anthony. Founded in the early thirteenth century, this monastic complex was dissolved in 1783. The once imposing building complex on the Maas river no longer exists. In 1848, the buildings were demolished for the construction of the Maastricht-Liège canal and the associated lock connection to the Bassin. The Maastrichtse Antonieten had the patronage of several churches in the Maastricht area, such as the Sint-Martinuskerk in Meeuwen.

name: Antonius Abtkerk
description:
The Antonius Abtkerk is a Roman Catholic church building in Nijmegen, dedicated to Antonius Abt. It is located on the Dennenstraat in Neerbosch-Oost/Hees and is used by the Hees parish. The church was designed in 1874 by P.J.H. Cuypers, and the building itself dates from 1879-1880.

It is a neo-Gothic three-aisled hall church. The church is a reinterpretation of the Hague hall type, where the side aisles are covered with pointed vaults. The stained-glass windows were made by glass studio F. Nicolas and Sons in Roermond and were installed between 1880 and 1925. The Stations of the Cross are by the Nijmegen painter Dorus Arts. Inside the church is a 16th-century crucifix from Kalkar. The Antonius Abtkerk is a national monument.

name: Antonius Abtkerk
description:
The Antonius Abtkerk in Bergen op Zoom is a former Roman Catholic church. The third church with this name was built in 1951, designed by J. de Lint. It is a three-aisled basilica with a narthex, flanked by a baptismal and devotion chapel, and an apse at the rear, flanked by two square towers with tent roofs.

The design shows influence from early Christian and early Romanesque church architecture in Italy. In 2000, the church was deconsecrated. It was saved from demolition due to protests from local residents. Since August 2002, it has housed the Franke daycare center and, since October 2003, also the Het Hoofdkwartier neighborhood center.

name: Antonius Abtkerk
description: The Antonius Abtkerk is a Roman Catholic church in Volkel, Netherlands, dedicated to Saint Anthony the Great. In 1455, the first chapel was erected in Volkel, dedicated to Antonius Abt and Barbara of Nicomedia, made possible by a legacy. The current church was built in 1938 in a Gothicizing, traditionalist style, designed by J. van Halteren. It is a three-aisled cruciform church built of imitation hand-molded brick with a western tower. The tower has angled, recessed buttresses and four sections separated by brick lists. The first section has a pointed arch niche with a portal below with a profiled frame in tuff and above it a three-part window with brick fork tracing.

name: Antonius van Paduakerk
description:
The Antonius van Paduakerk was a Roman Catholic church building in the Nazareth neighborhood of Maastricht. Built from 1959 to 1961, it served as a parish church for the Parish of St. Anthony of Padua. In 2007, the Diocese of Roermond decommissioned the church. It was demolished in 2011, though the bell tower and former baptistery were preserved.

The church was a rectangular hall church with a northwest-southeast orientation. Its concrete skeleton was left exposed and filled with prefabricated concrete facade panels featuring window openings and brickwork. The window openings appeared randomly placed. The church had a flat roof covered with bitumen roofing. In the middle of the west facade, within a risalit, was the main entrance with double doors and two lower side entrances.

name: Antonius van Paduakerk
description:
The Antonius van Paduakerk is a church building in the Scharn neighborhood in Maastricht. It serves as the parish church of the Roman Catholic parish of Saint Anthony of Padua in the former village of Scharn, east of Maastricht. The traditional-looking church from 1938 is a municipal monument and possesses a number of valuable art treasures.

The church is a spacious three-aisled cruciform basilica with a transept and a chancel. It has a wide central nave that connects to a more or less square chancel, which is separated from the semicircular apse by a parabolic arch opening. The church has a high, square church tower, which is narrower than the nave. The two-part tower ends in a four-sided tent roof on which a tower cross and a weather vane are placed. The church is built in Limburg marl and Kunrader limestone and covered with slate.

name: Antonius van Paduakerk
description:
The Antonius van Paduakerk is a Roman Catholic church located on the Groesbeekseweg in Nijmegen. This neo-Gothic building was constructed between 1916 and 1917, designed by Rotterdam architect Jos Margry. It is dedicated to Saint Anthony of Padua.

The church is a brick-built, three-aisled cruciform basilica. The transept has two aisles, and above the crossing is a hexagonal dome topped with a small bell tower. The stained-glass windows are the work of Nijmegen artist Piet Gerrits and Lambert Simon. Inside the church is a Verschueren organ.

Next to the church is the rectory, also designed by J. Margry in 1917. Besides liturgical services, the church is frequently used for concerts, especially by choirs. In 2008, the church was designated as a municipal monument. A planned 50-meter high tower was never realized, though the connection points and large pointed archway intended as the entrance are still visible.

name: Antonius van Paduakerk
description: The Antonius van Paduakerk, also known as the Antoniuskerk, is a Roman Catholic church in Ulft, Netherlands. This Neo-Romanesque church was built in 1914, designed by Herman Kroes. The church was consecrated on October 28, 1914, by the Archbishop of Utrecht, Henricus van de Wetering, and dedicated to Antonius van Padua as its patron saint. A reliquary was placed during the consecration. The church was located north of Ulft, near the footbridge over the Oude IJssel to Silvolde. In 2016, the church was sold and now functions as a funeral center. As of 2025, it is for sale again.

name: Antoniuskapel
description:
The Antoniuskapel is a small hall church located in Sinderen, in the Dutch municipality of Oude IJsselstreek. The chapel, dating from 1150, was part of the Sinderen Castle, which disappeared around 1876. This prayer chapel of the lords of Sinderen was dedicated to Saint Antonius Abbot, the patron saint against pig diseases.

The white-plastered building is a hall church with pointed arch windows. It has a wooden bell cage on the roof with a bell from the early 17th century, with a diameter of 36 cm. Inside, there are visible gravestones, under which the burial vaults are located. The balcony and the current church organ date from 1950.

name: Antoniuskerk
description:
The Antoniuskerk in Rekken is a Protestant church. The current church was built in 1889 after the original chapel burned down due to lightning. The original chapel was built in the 14th century and expanded around 1655 with a brick tower.

The brick tower did not burn down in 1889 and now forms a whole with the new building from 1889. The church is a hall church with a single-aisle nave. The windows consist of cast-iron arched windows. The entrance is in the tower, which is crowned with a tent roof. Inside the church is an organ made by Van Dam.

Both the church and the tower are national monuments. It also functions as a meeting place with multifunctional rooms.

name: Antoniuskerk
description:
The Sint-Antoniuskathedraal, or St. Anthony of Padua Cathedral, is located in Breda and serves as the Roman Catholic cathedral of the Diocese of Breda. Constructed in 1837 by architect Peter Huijsers, it exemplifies neoclassical style. The facade showcases Doric, Ionic, and Corinthian elements, topped by a pediment resembling a Greek temple.

Initially elevated to cathedral status in 1853, it later lost this designation in 1876 but regained it on January 1, 2001, at the request of Bishop Muskens. The church is also known as a "waterstaatskerk" because the government largely financed its construction and civil engineers supervised it. The cathedral is known as 'white church' and is seen as an oasis of peace.

name: Apostolische Kerk
description:
The Apostolische Kerk in Haarlem is a church of the Hersteld Apostolische Zendinggemeente, located on Jacobijnestraat. The building dates back to the second half of the 19th century, with a cornerstone indicating the year 1868.

It was originally built as a school but has been used as a church since 1925. Before acquiring this building, the Hersteld Apostolische Zendinggemeente, founded in 1879, had no permanent home and held services in various rented spaces. The building is made of brick with plasterwork and has a protruding central section and windows with truncated corners.

name: Appèlkerk
description: The Appèlkerk is a church building in Amersfoort, Netherlands, built in 1927. It is located on the corner of Appelweg and Wouter van Bloklandlaan. The church was designed by Gijs van Hoogevest. The church is known for its tower with a wooden section topped by a tented roof with a cross. The entrance is at the base of the tower, featuring brickwork and a narrow, tall stained glass window above it. The side facades have rectangular windows that partially break through the roofline, and buttresses support the side walls. The complex also has a stone boundary wall with pillars made of the same brick as the church. An extension was added to the south facade and rear of the building at some point.

name: Augustanakerk
description:
The Augustanakerk, also known as Augustanahof due to its current mixed use, is a Lutheran church building in the Bos en Lommer neighborhood of Amsterdam. Designed by architect Ferdinand B. Jantzen and built in 1956, it's located near the Erasmusgracht, opposite the Erasmus Park. The church is named after the Augsburg Confession (Confessio Augustana) of 1530.

The church was closed in January 2015, with the last service held on January 4, 2015. In 2017, the major part of the complex was transformed into apartments. Besides the religious spaces, it also had a meeting hall, canteen, liturgical center, rooms for church work, a parsonage and caretaker's house. Since 2011 there is a "silent garden" between the church and the canal.

name: Augustijnenkerk
description:
The Augustijnenkerk, known locally as "Awwestiene", is a baroque church in the center of Maastricht, situated on the Kesselskade along the Maas River. It was constructed in the 17th century as a monastery church for the Augustinian order. However, the monastery was dissolved at the end of the 18th century.

Since then, the church has served various functions, including a theatre, a school, an exhibition hall, and a parish church dedicated to St. Joseph from 1920-1968, after which a new chancel was added. The church is a national monument since 1966. The coats of arms of Hendrik Huyn van Geleen and the city of Maastricht are displayed on the facade.

name: Bakenesserkerk
description:
The Bakenesserkerk is a former church in Haarlem, Netherlands, located on the Vrouwestraat. It is now used as exhibition space for the Archeologisch Museum Haarlem's workgroup. The church is known for its characteristic white tower, visible in Haarlem cityscapes.

Founded in the 13th century by William II of Holland as "Onze Lieve Vrouwenkapel", the white sandstone tower was added in 1520. The current building dates back to the fifteenth century. The oldest mention dates from 1486 and concerns the northern ship of the church and the lower part of the tower. The upper part of the tower dates from the beginning of the sixteenth century. Inside, in the choir closure, there are still late Gothic images from around 1470 of Mary, the Three Kings and the Evangelist.

name: Bantsiliek
description:
The Bantsiliek is a former Roman Catholic church in Bant, Noordoostpolder, that now functions as a multi-purpose center owned by the Protestant community. Designed by architect A. Vosman in 1955, its architecture reflects the traditionalist Delft School style, characterized by simple brickwork and limited ornamentation. The building has three naves with walls, arches, and vaults in clean masonry.

Due to its cultural-historical, urban planning, and architectural significance, the Bantsiliek is listed as a municipal monument. Today, it hosts concerts, exhibitions, meetings, workshops, and other events.

name: Baptistenkerk
description:
The Baptistenkerk in Leeuwarden is a former church building located in the city of Leeuwarden, Netherlands. Around 1900, the Baptist community in Leeuwarden held services in a building on the Bagijnestraat. In 1913, they moved to a building on Vliet 11. In 1934, a church was built on the grounds at the rear, designed by architect R. Wijbenga. The entrance was on the Hoogpad (later changed to M.H. Trompstraat).

The first stone, inscribed 19/5/1934, was laid by Ds. Huizinga. The church hall, featuring stained glass windows, had 360 seats. The new church building was first used on September 16, 1934. In 1996, the Baptist Church Leeuwarden bought the Parkkerk. The Baptistenkerk was sold, and since 2013, the TrompTheater has been located in the building. The building is an interesting hall church without a tower.

name: Barnabaskerk
description:
The Barnabaskerk in Apeldoorn is a cross-shaped church building constructed in 1919-1920. It was designed by J.A. Heuvelink, an architect from Apeldoorn, and is located in the De Parken neighborhood. The church is owned by the Christian Reformed Church Apeldoorn-Centrum.

The building has several symbols, including its cross-shaped structure, representing an important symbol in the life of Christ. In front of the pulpit, there is a table with a bowl, a jug, and a cup, symbolizing the Holy Communion. The church organ, located in the front of the church above the pulpit, was built by the Van Vulpen brothers in Utrecht.

name: Bartholomeuskerk
description:
The Bartholomeuskerk in Stedum is a Romanesque-Gothic church built around 1250-1275, with the lower part of the tower being slightly older. Tuff stone can still be seen in the base of the tower. The tower, initially separate, was later raised and equipped with an inner tower and bell chair. It houses a Maria bell from 1300, the oldest dated bell in the province of Groningen.

Monks from the Cistercian Abbey in Aduard led the construction between 1250 and 1275. Restorations were carried out in 1877-1878 by architect P.J.H. Cuypers and in 1937-1939 by architect A.R. Wittop Koning. Inside the church is a marble tomb from Rombout Verhulst's workshop, commemorating Adriaan Clant. The interior features rich wood carvings from the second half of the seventeenth century and the current organ was made in 1791.

name: Bartholomeüskerk
description:
The Bartholomeüskerk in Noordlaren is a church originally dedicated to Saint Bartholomew. Its oldest parts date back to the 12th century when a wooden church was first erected. During the 13th century, the current stone building was constructed in several phases. The church largely acquired its present appearance in the 15th century.

The church is known for its unique paintings and a 16th-century alms box. In 1876, Petrus van Oeckelen and his sons built the current organ. The church is used by the Protestant congregation of Noordlaren-Glimmen and is owned by the Stichting Oude Groninger Kerken since 2021. It serves as a wedding location for the municipality of Groningen and is used for funeral and wedding services. Concerts are occasionally held there.

name: Basiliek van Onze Lieve Vrouwe Tenhemelopneming
description:
The Basiliek van Onze Lieve Vrouwe Tenhemelopneming in Zwolle is a medieval cross church. The building was constructed in four phases. The first phase took place between 1394 and 1417. The second phase occurred between 1452 and 1454 when the nave was completed with a west facade. The third phase included the construction of a tower between 1463 and 1483, finalized with the installation of six bells.

In 1999, the church received the honorary title of basilica on its 600th anniversary. During the Reformation, it fell into disuse but was later returned to the Roman Catholics during the French era. The basilica is still used for Catholic services and musical performances, often featuring choirs accompanied by the Maarschalkerweerd organ. The church's tower, called "Peperbus", is a landmark of Zwolle.

name: Basiliek van Onze-Lieve-Vrouw van het Heilig Hart
description:
The Basilica of Our Lady of the Sacred Heart is a Catholic church and pilgrimage site in the historic center of Sittard. It's a striking example of Neo-Gothic architecture in Limburg, built between 1875-1879. The basilica has a cruciform shape and includes side aisles with galleries, an ambulatory with radiating chapels, and a high crossing tower. The tower is adorned with openwork, polygonal turrets at its corners.

Inside, the church features a richly decorated interior. The high vaults and galleries reduce the amount of light, creating a rather dark atmosphere. Stained glass windows depict various biblical figures and scenes. The basilica also houses an organ built in 1954. The church's spiritual significance is emphasized by a statue of Our Lady above the altar, symbolizing the distribution of God's grace.

name: Basiliek van de H.H. Agatha en Barbara
description:
The Basilica of the Saints Agatha and Barbara is a Roman Catholic church in Oudenbosch, in the province of Noord-Brabant, Netherlands. It was built between 1867 and 1880 and elevated to a basilica minor in 1912.

The church is a smaller replica of St. Peter's Basilica in Rome, with the facade of the St. John Lateran. The architects were P.J.H. Cuypers and later G.J. van Swaay. The basilica is 81 meters long and 55 meters wide, and the highest point of the dome is 63 meters. There is a large dome, 20 meters in diameter and 51 meters high, and several smaller domes. The inside of the dome can be viewed up close via a narrow staircase.

name: Basiliek van de H.H. Wiro, Plechelmus en Otgerus
description: The Basilica of the Saints Wiro, Plechelmus and Otgerus, located in Sint Odiliënberg, is a parish church elevated to a basilica in 1957. It stands on a church hill by the Roer river. The Romanesque-style church has been almost completely rebuilt twice. The first time was between 1880 and 1883. After being heavily damaged by the towers being blown up in early 1945, it was rebuilt between 1949 and 1951 according to the plans of architect Alphons Boosten and consecrated on May 6, 1951. The stained glass windows were designed by Joep Nicolas, and the Stations of the Cross were designed by his wife, Suzanne Nijs. Unique 12th-century apostle statues of Jacobus and Johannes can be admired in the basilica since May 17, 2021.

name: Basiliek van de Heilige Kruisverheffing
description:
The Basilica of the Holy Cross in Raalte is a Roman Catholic basilica in neo-Gothic style. It was built in 1891-1892, designed by Alfred Tepe. The church was consecrated on October 19, 1892. In addition to the patronage of the Holy Cross, it also received the patronage of Saint Anthony of Padua.

The church soon got the nickname "The Cathedral of Salland". The dials above the sound holes were installed in 1955, and a fourth dial was added to the side of the church nave. To prevent leaks, the dormers disappeared in 1966 by placing a flat roof over them. The church was placed on the list of monuments in 1974. In 1992, the honorary title of basilica minor was granted to the church building by the Roman Congregation for Divine Worship. Also in that year, the carillon in the 79-meter-high tower of the church was put into use.

name: Basiliek van het H. Sacrament
description:
The Basilica of the Holy Sacrament, also known as the Basilica of Meerssen, is a Roman Catholic church in Meerssen, Netherlands. It is dedicated to the Holy Sacrament and the apostle Bartholomew and was elevated to basilica minor by Pope Pius XI in 1938. The basilica exemplifies mature Maas Gothic style and is considered the pinnacle of this style in the Netherlands.

The basilica consists of a nave of three Gothic and three neo-Gothic bays, a 14th-century transept and an equally old choir. The neo-Gothic sacristy, built against the south side of the choir, dates from 1878. The neo-Gothic burial chapel of the Maastricht manufacturer family Regout from 1869 is located on the northeast side of the church. The church has a sacrament tower and stained glass windows.

name: Begijnekerk
description: The Begijnekerk, located in Breedstraat, Utrecht, is a former church with historical roots in the Beguinage. The Beguinage was an enclosed site dating back to the 13th century, encompassing a chapel, a "big house", a communal garden, and small houses for individual Beguines. After the Reformation, the Beguinage lost independence, and by 1675, it effectively ceased to exist. Following this, new streets and houses were built on the site. The Begijnekerk was named after the previous Beguinage, with some streets also taking their names from it. Very little of the original Beguinage buildings remain today.

name: Begijnhofkapel
description: The Begijnhof Chapel, dedicated to Saint John and Saint Ursula, is a Roman Catholic chapel run by the Congregation of the Blessed Sacrament. Located in the Begijnhof, it stands across from its original location. The chapel's current form includes a gallery with left and right sections, supported by six wooden columns. The main altar showcases a painting depicting the Miracle of Amsterdam, while side altars feature paintings by Claes Corneliszoon Moeyaert. The facade, adorned with gothic-style leaded ogive windows, dates back to the 19th century. Built as a hidden church in 1672, it replaced the original church that was lost to the Reformed Protestants. Inside the chapel, one can see a nine-pane painting and stained glass windows that narrate the story of the Miracle of Amsterdam.

name: Bergeijk; de Sint-Petrus Bandenkerk of Hofkerk
description:
The Sint-Petrus' Bandenkerk, also known as Hofkerk, is located in Bergeijk in the province of Noord-Brabant. It's a Gothic cruciform church built in a pseudo-basilical style. Notably, it lacks a tower but has a small ridge turret. The original tower collapsed in 1650 and was never rebuilt. The chancel dates back to 1422, while the late-Gothic transept and nave were constructed in the early 16th century.

The nave and transept feature a five-rib barrel vault, and the chancel has a ribbed vault. The interior has a simple design. From 1648 to 1798, the church was used for Protestant services. Between 1888 and 1893, it was restored and expanded by Caspar Franssen. After WWII, a new, larger church was built. The Hofkerk stood empty from 1965 to 1994. It was declared a national monument and restored in the 1970s. The interior includes sculptures of Saint John and Saint Lucy from 1490.

name: Bergkerk
description:
The Bergkerk is a church building in the Dutch city of Amersfoort, located at Dr. A. Kuyperlaan 2. The church community that uses the building is part of the Protestant Church of Amersfoort.

The north-south non-oriented church building consists of a two-aisled nave with six bays, a straight closed choir of one bay on the south side, and on the north side of the aisle a square tower topped with a lantern. North of the nave and east of the tower is a portal.

The organ in the Bergkerk was built in 1956 by the Van Vulpen brothers. It was put into use on February 8, 1956. The instrument was restored in 1979 by Van Vulpen, whereby the disposition was also changed.

name: Best Life Church
description: The Sint-Jacobuskerk in Zuilen, Utrecht, is a former Roman Catholic church, now known as the Best Life Church. It was built in the 1950s as a three-aisled cruciform basilica due to the increasing number of Catholics in the area. The church is considered a characteristic work by architects H.W. Valk and his son G.H.F. Valk. A low, compact tower emphasizes the sanctuary. In 2017, the church was sold to the Best Life Church and deconsecrated as a Catholic church.

name: Beth-elkerk
description: The Beth-elkerk in Maastricht is a church building of the Moluccan Evangelical Church, located on Godefridus van Heerstraat in Heer. It was built in 1961, designed by architect Frans Dingemans, and significantly renovated in 1991-1992. It is a brick hall church under a relatively flat gable roof. The concrete bell tower has an open bell cage and a large steel cross in a niche. The church is largely painted grey, except for the brick entrance, which has a striking pink canopy. The bell tower is painted white to match the white houses in the neighborhood. The original church tower, also designed by Dingemans, is a municipal monument together with the surrounding buildings.

name: Bethelkerk
description: The Bethelkerk in Assen is a church located on the Groningerstraat. It formerly served as the Synagogue of Assen. The name of the church refers to the biblical place Bethel. In 1947, the Reformed Church took the church building into use, and a few years later in 1951, they bought the building. In 1970, the Reformed Church moved to the Noorderkerk, and the Bethelkerk was offered for sale. The building stood empty for years and was used as a storage place for furniture. In 1980, the church was eventually bought by the Christian Reformed Church, which still holds services there.

name: Bethelkerk
description:
The Bethelkerk in Ede, Gelderland, is owned by the Reformed Church of Ede and is used for church services on Sundays and Christian holidays. The current Bethelkerk was opened on Wednesday, February 24, 1965. The building is located on the corner of Diedenweg and Jan Th. Tooroplaan. The architects are Geenen and Oskam from Eindhoven.

The architectural style is reminiscent of the New Building style. Characteristic features include the recurring patterns in the brickwork, the transparent style of the bell tower, and the enormous space of the church hall. At the front of the church hall is a pulpit made mainly of stone and steel with a large sounding board above it. At the back of the church is a window by glass artist Lex van Voorst, a glass application with stained glass, depicting the story of Jacob in Bethel. Above this is a balcony on which the organ is placed. The building is a municipal monument.

name: Bethelkerk
description: The Bethelkerk in Sint-Annaland is a church building of the Restored Reformed Church, located at F.M. Boogaardweg 17a. Designed by W.M. van Beijnum, it offers 385 seats. The building is constructed with red bricks and features a built-in tower. The church has a high pitched roof, and the tower consists of two parallel brick walls. An electronic Johannus organ of the Monarke type is used for musical accompaniment. The first service was held in 2007 after the community used the church of the Reformed Church from 2004-2007.

name: Bethelkerk
description: The Bethelkerk in Westkapelle is a former barrack that was transformed into a Reformed church building. It is located on the Noordstraat in the Zeeland town of Westkapelle. The church was closed in 2011. During the German occupation, it was also used as a school building, but later German soldiers were stationed there, so the services were held in the Reformed Church.

name: Bethelkerk
description:
The Bethelkerk in Geldermalsen is a church belonging to the Reformed Congregations. It is located in the southern part of Geldermalsen and was opened on February 6, 2003. The name of the church refers to the biblical place Bethel, meaning "House of God".

The church was built to replace a smaller building. The design is by Architectenbureau RoosRos. It originally accommodated 1224 worshipers, but can be expanded to 1600 seats if needed. The church has an organ with 46 registers, built by I. Boogaard. The two largest bells originate from the St. Thomas van Aquino Church in Amsterdam.

name: Bethelkerk
description:
The Bethelkerk in Goes is a church building located at Beatrixlaan 9A, with entrances on Violenstraat 1 and Tulpstraat 2. The church is named after the biblical place Bethel and is used by the Free Evangelical Church of Goes.

The Bethelkerk was built in 1952-1953 by order of the Reformed Church of Goes and was put into use on December 23, 1953. In 1966, the Bethelkerk was renovated and reopened on February 23, 1967. After the Reformed Church moved to the Sion Church in 1979, the Bethelkerk was sold to the Free Evangelical Church of Goes.

The Bethelkerk houses an organ with electro-pneumatic action. In 1966, the organ was modified by organ builder M.K. Koppejan from Ederveen. The number of registers has been expanded to 20, divided over two manuals and a free pedal. The organ was then moved and the console was placed separately.

name: Bethelkerk (Gereformeerde Kerk)
description:
The Bethelkerk in Urk is the oldest church building of the Reformed Church of Urk. The first church on this site was built in 1851. It was a small building, where the wedding gate and the elder and deacon benches are now located in the Bethelkerk.

In 1867 the church was enlarged. In 1885 the oldest part from 1851 was demolished and replaced by the "large container", which is still there today. The part from 1867 was spared and is still used as consistory and meeting rooms. The church has 1,100 seats and was restored in 1951 and 1981.

name: Bethelkerk (Huizumerlaan)
description: The Bethelkerk in Leeuwarden, located on Huizumerlaan, is a modern church that replaced an older Bethelkerk on Wijbrand de Geeststraat and "De Rank". It serves as the church for the Christian Reformed Church of Leeuwarden, which was founded in 1893. The church has a congregation of 782 members. Services are held at 9:30 AM and 4:30 PM. The church also offers online services. The Bethelkerk is part of the Particular Synod of the North and the classis Leeuwarden.

name: Bethlehemkerk
description:
The Bethlehemkerk in Amsterdam-Noord, located at Zwanenplein 34-36, is a notable structure that once housed the Bethlehemkerk congregation. Constructed between 1923 and 1924, designed by architect Adriaan Moen.

The church's architecture features a high roof and a parabolic interior. Other stylistic elements include relatively small windows (excluding the church windows), alternating brickwork, heavy wooden doors, and stone accents. The east gable is decorated with a trapezium containing Alpha, Omega, and a labarum. A bell tower with horizontal lines is a distinctive feature. The building rests on a concrete foundation and cellar. The two large stained-glass windows, designed by H.J. Winkelman, depict "The Annunciation to the Shepherds" and "The Wise Men from the East". Queen Wilhelmina attended the inauguration on September 13, 1924. The church could accommodate 542 worshipers at the opening.

name: Bethlehemkerk
description:
The Bethlehemkerk is a Moluccan church building located in Middelburg, in the province of Zeeland, the Netherlands, on the Rijnstraat. The current building dates from 1992, replacing an earlier building from 1962. It is used by both the Geredja Indjili Maluku (GIM) and the Geredja Kristen Maluku Selatan (GKMS).

Construction of the new church began in early 1992, designed by architect S. Hitipeuw. It was put into use after approximately ten months, on December 12, 1992. The church hall has space for 180 seats, which can be expanded to 280 seats when needed. The building also functions as a meeting space for the Moluccan community. The church is designed in a style typical of Moluccan churches built in the 80s and 90s, including the use of circles and angled square shapes in the floor plan, as well as a colonnade as a transition element between inside and outside.

name: Beyartkerk
description: The Beyart has two periods. The first Beyart, also called the Valley of Josaphat (1476-1796), began with the settlement of Franciscan sisters. Only a ruin of the Gothic monastery chapel from this period has been preserved. A century after the dissolution of this monastery, the Brothers of the Immaculate Conception of Mary built a new monastery on the same site, which still exists in part and also served as the mother house of the congregation. In the 1970s, this monastery gradually transformed into a retirement home, also for non-religious people. The Sint-Lidwina Pavilion, a former hospital pavilion built in the 1930s, is also located on the monastery grounds.

name: Blijde Boodschapkerk
description:
The Blijde Boodschapkerk was a Roman Catholic parish church in the Overvecht district of Utrecht. The church was dedicated to the Annunciation. In 2003, the church was deconsecrated after the merger to form the Sint-Rafaëlparochie for the whole of Overvecht.

With the expansion of the Overvecht district with the Overvecht-Noord district, plans were also made for parish churches for this district. Although it was initially considered to establish two parishes for Overvecht-Noord, in the end there was only one. The parish was founded in 1970 and dedicated to the Annunciation. That same year, construction began and was completed in 1971. After the Heilige Geestkerk and the Emmaüskerk, this was the third Catholic church for Overvecht.

In 2005, the church was taken into use again by Chinese Christians, who kept the name of the church. The interior of the church has been used to furnish the new day chapel of the Rafaëlkerk.

name: Bloemgrachtkerk
description: The Bloemgrachtkerk, constructed in 1880, is a Reformed or Protestant church situated in the Bloemgracht. Its architectural style is neo-Gothic, which gives it a look that diverges from that of a classical church. The Bloemgrachtkerk is also a registered national monument.

name: Bogaardenkapel
description: I am sorry, but I don't have enough information to describe the church of the Bogaardenklooster in Maastricht based on the provided website. The text focuses more on the history of the monastery itself, its inhabitants, and its eventual dissolution, rather than providing specific details about the church's architecture or interior.

name: Bonifaciuskerk
description:
The Bonifaciuskerk in Medemblik is a Dutch church dating back to 1404, with its earliest mention in 1118. It was built using the ruins of a previous church that had burned down. Initially dedicated to Saint Boniface, it later included Saint Martin. After the Reformation in 1572, it became a Protestant church, retaining the name Bonifacius.

Despite fires in 1517 and 1555, the church largely remained intact. Inside, notable features include stained glass windows, one donated by Monnickendam in 1670 and another by the Rijnschippersgilde in 1671 depicting Noah's Ark. Also present is an hourglass indicating sermon length, brass chandeliers from 1591 and 1571, and the gravestone of Lord George Murray, whose actual grave is located behind the church. The tower, older than the church and owned by the municipality, is 70.99 meters tall with walls two meters thick.

name: Bonnefantenkerk
description: The church, part of the Bonnefantenklooster, features a classicist facade with four Ionic pilasters. The facade's triangular fronton showcases a late Baroque sculpture depicting the Resurrection. Hard stone niches, once housing statues of saints, flank the narrow sections. Inside the former church building, which now serves as a visitor center, the crypt is accessible. However, the original church interior no longer exists. The facade includes a chronogram above the door which translates to "The tomb of the Lord will receive glory".

name: Bontebrugkerk
description: The Bontebrugkerk is a church located in Bontebrug, in the municipality of Oude IJsselstreek, Netherlands. It is identified as a Protestant church. The church building was established in 1949 and designed by the architect Evert Jan Rotshuizen. The address of the church is Bontebrug 84, 7064LK. The church is part of the Protestant Church in the Netherlands.

name: Bovenkerk
description: The Bovenkerk, also known as the Church of St. Nicholas, is a large Gothic church and a prominent feature of the Kampen skyline. It is a large Gothic cruciform basilica. Inside the church is an early Renaissance rood screen, a stone pulpit, and a monumental organ. The church has a tower and a nave. In 1481/1482, bell founder Geert van Wou cast bells for the Bovenkerk.

name: Brandpunt
description:
Brandpunt is an ecumenical church building located in the Kattenbroek neighborhood of Amersfoort. The church is used by the ecumenical faith community "Het Brandpunt," which was founded in 1990. It is a collaboration between Dutch Reformed, Reformed, and Roman Catholics.

The building was put into use in 1994, designed in a modernistic style by architects Olsmeijer and De Graaf from Groningen. It features a hall church with a fan-shaped plan. Distinctive elements include the wooden roofs with overhanging, sloping canopies. The interior is simple, featuring a pulpit, a communion table, a baptismal font, and an openwork cross. An organ and harmonium provide musical accompaniment. The church has a main hall with 400 seats and several side rooms, including a quiet center.

name: Broederenkerk
description:
The Broederenkerk in Zutphen is a 14th-century monastic church. Founded as part of a Dominican monastery in 1293, it stands as one of the best-preserved monastic churches in the Netherlands. The church features a three-aisled, basilica-style nave with stone cross-vaults. A wooden bell tower, covered in copper, sits atop the roof.

Inside, the church has rich vault paintings from the early 16th century. A new baroque roof turret was added in 1772, and in 1826, a neoclassical entrance portal was added to the south side. After being used by the Protestant community, the building became a public library in 1983, a function it still serves today.

name: Broederenkerk
description:
The Broederenkerk, officially the Roman Catholic Saint Lebuinus Church, is located in Deventer. Construction took place between 1335 and 1338, commissioned by Eleonora of England. Before the church's construction, the Franciscan friars had already founded a monastery around 1300 at that location. Although the friars left the monastery and church permanently in 1579, the informal name of the church still recalls their centuries-long presence.

From 1579 to 1799, the church building was used by Deventer Protestants, with a short interruption. In 1799, the Deventer Catholic community regained possession of the Broederenkerk. The interior of the church was completely renovated in the neo-Gothic style in the mid-19th century. A restoration was completed in 2015, restoring the fourteenth-century roof.

name: Broederkerk
description: The Broederkerk is a reformed church in Kampen, and one of the four parish communities within the Protestant Church of Kampen, which is part of the Protestant Church in the Netherlands. The parish is oriented towards the Reformed Association. The community aspires to live and give from the Source, as stated in their policy plan: "Listening to the Word of God, we want to be a confessing, living, serving, and witnessing community in the line of the Reformation. We live from the completed work of Jesus Christ who took our guilt upon Himself." They eagerly anticipate the return of Jesus Christ.

name: Broekhovense kerk
description:
The Broekhovense Church, located in Tilburg, was part of the parish De Goede Herder until 2023, when it was deconsecrated. Dedicated to Our Lady of Good Counsel, it was designed by Jan van der Valk and completed in 1913. The church is a hybrid of a traditional cruciform church and a central building.

While often described as neo-Byzantine, the architectural style is an early example of expressionism in the Netherlands, particularly evident in the upper section of its 45-meter high square tower. A notable feature is the central dome made of reinforced concrete. The west side has an extended portal, adorned with a mosaic above the entrance. The staircase to the main portal is flanked by brick-built lion sculptures. In 1987, the interior was extensively renovated. The church is now a national monument.

name: Broerenkerk
description:
The Broerenkerk in Zwolle, Netherlands, originated as part of a Dominican monastery founded in 1465. Construction finished in 1512, featuring two naves and a single choir. In 1580, the church faced damage during the "Beeldenstorm," leading to the expulsion of the monks. From 1640 to 1982, it served as a Protestant church. After restoration in 1983-1988, it was repurposed for cultural events.

Since 2013, the Broerenkerk has been operating as a bookstore. The transformation maintains the church's gothic atmosphere, with the books arranged around the original walls and pillars. The high ceilings and gothic details create a unique environment for browsing and literary events are frequently hosted.

name: Broerkerk
description:
The Broerkerk in Groningen was a medieval church connected to a Franciscan monastery. Situated on Broerstraat, it was the first church in the city used by Protestants. From the 17th century, it was also known as Academiekerk.

In 1614, after Groningen joined the Republic of the Seven United Netherlands, the church became affiliated with the University of Groningen. Arp Schnitger built an organ for the church in 1702, incorporating parts from an older organ. By 1815, the organ was moved to the Der Aa-kerk.

In the 19th century, the church was returned to the Catholic community, but its dilapidated condition led to its demolition in 1895. A new church, the Sint Martinuskerk, was built on the site, later replaced by the University Library in 1982.

name: Buiksloterkerk
description:
The Buiksloterkerk is a former village church located in Amsterdam North, specifically in the dike village of Buiksloot. It's situated slightly off the Buiksloterdijk on the Buiksloterkerkpad. This church has a rural setting, complemented by a surrounding cemetery.

Restored to its former glory in 1995, it now serves as an attractive meeting place and a stage for culture in Amsterdam North. The interior features a beautiful pulpit and a special organ built by H. ter Hart, a famous Amsterdam organ builder. The Buiksloterkerk hosts concerts, theater performances, and various social events and is available for rental. It was added to the register of national monuments in 1970.

name: Buitenkerk
description: The Buitenkerk, or Our Lady Church, is an important part of Kampen's cityscape. Its construction began in 1369, commissioned by master builder Rutger van Ceulen. It has a turbulent history, marked by deterioration and the risk of collapse. A thorough restoration was completed in 1977, returning the church to full use. The Buitenkerk is the city's second parish church and is dedicated to Mary. The church's design features three halls, characterizing it as a hall church. It is a historic hall church with striking Brick Gothic architecture, gracing Kampen since the 14th century.

name: Burgwalkerk
description: The Burgwalkerk is a neoclassical church located in Kampen, in the province of Overijssel, Netherlands. It was built in 1874/1875. The church has a simplified neoclassical architectural style. A notable feature is its roof construction, which, for its time, had a remarkably large span without the need for supporting pillars inside the church or buttresses outside. The building has 850 seats. The organ was built in 1877 by Zwier van Dijk, an organ builder from Kampen. It has been expanded and improved several times since then, and underwent a complete renovation in 2007.

name: Buurkerk
description: The Buurkerk is a former medieval parish church located in Utrecht, Netherlands. It's situated on the Buurkerkhof and currently houses the Museum Speelklok, with its entrance on the Steenweg. The church is documented as having been burned multiple times in the 12th and 13th centuries. The unfinished tower dates back to 1370. In 1577, a cannon was placed in the tower, aimed at the Vredenburg castle during a siege. Around 1580, the church went through the Protestant Reformation and was officially handed over to Protestants in 1586. They whitewashed the walls and removed the choir to make way for a street. Since 1984, the building has functioned as a museum.

name: Calvariekapel
description: The Klooster Calvariënberg's chapel, originally oriented, had its layout altered around 1845 during the construction of the upper chapel. In 1902, the chapel was extended eastward, creating an entrance on the monastery's courtyard side through an opening in the adjacent cloister wing. The chapel runs parallel to the Calvariestraat. A high wall once stood here in the nineteenth century, shielding the insane asylum from the outside world. It is possible that the roof once featured a roof turret, but this was later removed.

name: Capucijnenkerk
description: The Capucijnenkerk, a former church, is located in the center of Maastricht, between the synagogue and the Ursuline convent. It is a simple, white-painted hall church with round arches. The church was originally built in the early 17th century, but it received its current form after a major restoration in 1681, following a fire. A stone in the west facade dates back to 1615. The monastery was founded in 1610 and dissolved in 1796. The east wing and the adjoining part of the north facade remain, with the head facade renovated in 1885. The sober, white-painted hall building features a large sculpted stone from 1615 in the gable top, displaying the coat of arms of Baron De Lens.

name: Catharinakerk
description:
The Catharinakerk in Zoutelande is a Protestant church located on Willibrordusplein. It is a national monument with fragments of late 13th-century brick Gothic architecture visible in its tower. The church's construction dates back to around 1270, with the current church tower likely originating from that time. The main building was constructed in the 14th century, originally almost twice as long and ending in a three-part choir.

During World War II, the church was severely damaged in 1944 and was unusable for services. It was later restored after the war. In the 15th century, the church was enlarged. During the Eighty Years' War, the church was badly damaged and only partially rebuilt. The church has a single-manual organ built in 1719.

name: Catharinakerk
description:
The Catharinakerk in Roden is a partly Romanesque-Gothic and partly Gothic church. Constructed in the 13th century, it was dedicated to Saint Catherine of Alexandria. In the early 15th century, the old choir was replaced with a Gothic one, and the tower was built at the end of the 15th century.

During a restoration in the 1930s, the plasterwork on the inside was removed, exposing the brick structure. The ship of the church is the oldest part. The choir was commissioned by the residents of the nearby Havezate Mensinge. The church contains well-preserved historical inventory, including a pulpit from the 17th century. A highlight is the Hinsz organ, which was put into use on December 6, 1779, and is still used in church services.

name: Catharinakerk
description:
The Sint Catharinakerk in Doetinchem, Netherlands, is a Protestant church with a rich history. It was originally built around 1200 and dedicated to Saint Catherine of Alexandria.

Throughout the Middle Ages, Doetinchem suffered several fires, including one in 1527 that destroyed almost the entire city center and the Sint Catharinakerk. It was rebuilt as a Gothic hall church with multiple naves of similar height and width.

During World War II, the center of Doetinchem was bombed, heavily damaging the church. The restoration took place between 1948 and 1963. An important change resulting from the war damage is that the tower now stands separate from the rest of the church.

name: Cellebroederskapel
description:
The Cellebroederskapel, likely dating back to 1512, is a late-Gothic hall church made of marl. It features a five-sided choir closure and a western gable. The windows in the south facade and choir have Gothic tracery, though only the tracery of the blind windows on the north side is original. During restoration in 1963-66, the baroque roof turret from 1705 was reconstructed.

Inside, the building consists of a single-nave space with a vault in four bays, the ribs of which together form a net vault. During the restoration, remnants of painted foliage and angel figures were found on this vault. A very rare remnant of the "Last Judgment" is located against the west wall of the nave. The chapel also houses a historic organ.

The chapel, once part of a larger monastery complex, is now a hidden gem. It is accessible through a gate on Brusselsestraat, leading to a serene courtyard. Today, it serves as a wedding location, concert venue, and meeting space.

name: Cenakelkerk
description:
The Cenakelkerk in Heilig Landstichting was constructed between 1913 and 1915 as a parish and pilgrimage church. It stands out in Dutch church architecture due to its design and detailing, drawing inspiration from early Christian architecture and Arabic styles, making it a unique example of Orientalism in the Netherlands.

The white plastered church has a large dome and two towers. The interior is like walking through an illustrated Bible. Jos Margry, Jan Wiebenga, and Jules Bilmeyer also contributed to the design and construction. A major restoration was completed in December 2010, and a celebration was held on Sunday, February 27, 2011, to mark the centenary of the founding act and the restoration's completion.

name: Chassékerk
description:
The Chassékerk, originally named Onze-Lieve-Vrouw van Altijddurende Bijstandkerk, is a former Roman Catholic church in Amsterdam. Proposed names like Baarsjeskerk were quickly dropped. Located on Chasséstraat in the western part of the city, it's now used as a dance studio.

Designed by architect Karel Petrus Tholens and built in 1926 in a modest brick style, the church was part of a complex that included a rectory, a sister house, a girls' school, and a kindergarten. The main altar faced east, symbolizing resurrection.

Due to declining church attendance, it was decommissioned in 1998. For a short time, a small chapel remained open until 2007. The building has two small towers on either side of the facade and once had three altars and stained glass windows. Currently, the interior has been renovated with dance studios, while preserving some original details.

name: Christ Church
description: Christ Church in Amsterdam, also known as the English Episcopal Church, is located on the Groenburgwal canal. The church building was designed by Pieter de Keyser. It was once a cloth hall and part of the Staalhof complex. Rembrandt's painting "De Staalmeesters" was displayed here until 1771. The church is an English-speaking Anglican church with a history spanning over 400 years in Amsterdam. It aims to be a welcoming and vibrant community, integrating into the local area by providing pastoral care and strong preaching. The church has three locations in Amsterdam: Centre, South and Southeast.

name: Christelijke gereformeerde kerk
description: The Christelijke Gereformeerde Kerk in Tholen is a church building and a religious community located in the city of Tholen, in the Netherlands. The building is located at Visstraat 14. The church's history goes back to 1870, with the first stone laid in May of that year. It initially served as a dance hall before being transformed into a church in 1929. In 1946, it officially became the Christelijke Gereformeerde Kerk. Renovations took place around 1966, which included modifications to the church benches, pulpit, and the relocation of the consistory. In 1982, a meeting hall was added. The building has high windows and a marble pulpit.

name: Christoforuskerk
description:
The Christoforuskerk, or Christophoruskerk, is a Roman Catholic basilica located on Molenstraat in Schagen, in the province of Noord-Holland. It is built in a neo-Gothic style and was designed by Alfred Tepe. The church is dedicated to Saint Christopher, and a stone with his image from the previous church is incorporated into the front portal.

Construction of the church began in 1881, and it was consecrated in 1883. The church has a tower with a spire of 25 meters. Inside the church, there are 12 pillars symbolizing the 12 apostles. The church was renovated in 1998. The high altar, designed by Fr W. Mengelber, was donated to the church in 1901. The church also houses an organ built in 1882 by John Nicholson, which is considered one of the finest romantic organs in the Netherlands.

name: Christus Koningkerk
description: The Christus Koningkerk was a Roman Catholic parish church located on Marshalllaan 139 in Utrecht, Netherlands. The church was dedicated to Christ the King. The parish was founded in 1960 for the Kanaleneiland district under construction. C.H. Bekink designed the church, which was completed and put into use in 1961. It was constructed using concrete and glass. However, the church was demolished in 1988. The parish was merged with the Wederkomst des Herenkerk.

name: Christus Koningkerk
description:
The Christus Koningkerk in Lievelde was a Roman Catholic church, built in 1954, designed by W.P.V. Dijkman. The construction started in December 1953, after a temporary church was used after the second world war. Before the church was built, a rectory was built and finished in 1950.

The facade features an extra brick wall with an entrance incorporating Ionic elements. Above the entrance, a rose window dominates much of the view. The tower is integrated with the facade and has several bells. The church was a municipal monument. The last Eucharist celebration took place on September 17, 2023, and the church was deconsecrated on October 2, 2023.

name: Christus Koningkerk
description:
The Christus Koningkerk was a Roman Catholic church in the Hengstdal district of Nijmegen, Netherlands. Designed by Johannes Zwanikken, the church was built in an expressionistic style. Construction started on July 14, 1932.

The church was made of reinforced concrete, covered with brick on the outside. The spire was permanently removed on March 3, 1990, after storm damage. The church was demolished in 1993, except for the tower. Today, a shopping center and apartment buildings are located on the site of the former church.

name: Christus Koningkerk
description: The Christus Koningkerk is a Roman Catholic church in Vorden, Netherlands. It was constructed between 1963 and 1964, designed by architect H.H.J. Starmans. Christus Koning, meaning Christ the King, was chosen as its patron saint. The church exhibits a clean, rectangular architectural style and features a separate bell tower. Both the church and the tower are built with brick.

name: Christus' Hemelvaartkerk
description:
The Christus' Hemelvaartkerk in Maastricht, located in the Pottenberg district, was originally a Roman Catholic church. Built between 1964 and 1966, it was designed by the architectural firm A.F. Brenninkmeyer. The church features a hexagonal floor plan based on a grid of equilateral triangles.

In 2011, after a series of burglaries and acts of vandalism, the parish church was closed. Since 2012, the Armenian Apostolic Church of Maastricht has been using the building, and in January 2013, it was consecrated and opened as the Surp Karapetkerk, which means Holy Forerunner, referring to John the Baptist. A slender belfry on three concrete legs marks the location of the church.

name: Co-kathedrale basiliek van de Heilige Nicolaas
description: The Co-cathedral Basilica of Saint Nicholas is located in Amsterdam, opposite the Centraal Station. Inside, after your eyes adjust to the darker interior, you will discover beautiful decorations, sculptures, stained glass windows and many paintings. The main facade features two towers and a rose window. The rose window contains a bas-relief sculpture depicting Christ and the four Evangelists, created in 1886. A sculpture of Saint Nicholas by Bart van Hove is in a niche at the top of the gable. Pope Francis elevated the basilica to co-cathedral.

name: Corneliuskerk
description:
The Corneliuskerk in Noordwelle is a late Gothic Evangelical Reformed church located in the province of Zeeland in the Netherlands. The church has a four-bay nave and a three-bay chancel with a 5/8 closure. Dedicated to Saint Cornelius before the Reformation, its construction dates back to the second half of the 15th century.

During the Eighty Years' War in 1575, Spanish troops sought refuge in the church. The church was set on fire, resulting in the death of all the soldiers. It was later restored. In 1754, a striking octagonal structure was added to the square lower levels of the tower. In 1892, the chancel was repurposed into a school, but this was reversed during a renovation in 1960. Today, the church is used for church services, weddings and funerals but also for concerts and lectures. It has a Bechstein grand piano and a church organ built by Flaes and Brunjes.

name: Cultuurkerk De Toekomst
description:
Cultuurkerk De Toekomst, formerly known as the Sint-Petrus en Pauluskerk until 2021, is a repurposed Roman Catholic church in Breedenbroek, Netherlands. Built in 1854-1855, the original design featured a single-nave structure with a square stone tower topped by a lantern and spire. Pointed arch windows and buttresses adorned the side facades.

In 1881, a priest's choir was added. Due to declining church attendance, the Utrecht diocese deconsecrated the building in 2015. From 2021 to 2023, it underwent significant renovations, including the demolition of a large portion of the church, transforming the remaining section into Cultuurkerk De Toekomst. The renovated space includes a small prayer room, meeting room, toilet facilities, and a kitchen. A glass roof covers the open section of the church.

name: Cunerakerk
description: The Cunerakerk is the main church of Rhenen and a prominent landmark. It owes its existence to the fact that Rhenen was an important pilgrimage site in the Middle Ages. Pilgrims came to see the relics of Saint Cunera, which have been venerated here since the eighth century. The church is a relatively large late Gothic church. The tower is 82 meters high and the pride of the church. Inside, the rood screen in Renaissance style from around 1550 and the choir stalls from 1570 are particularly noteworthy. Since the Reformation in 1580, the Cunerakerk has been used as a Dutch Reformed Church.

name: Damkerk
description:
The Damkerk in Hoogezand is a hall church located on Hoofdstraat. Its name refers to a dam that was once located in the former Winschoterdiep. The Vonkzaal is attached to the Damkerk. Together with some smaller rooms, such as the front room, consistory and the church office, this forms the Damkerk complex.

The Damkerk was built in 1669 by order of the city of Groningen. At the same time, the parsonage was built next to the church. The simple hall building has round-arched windows and the walls are supported by buttresses. In 1734, the church was considerably expanded on the south side. The Damkerk complex can be rented for funeral and wedding services, and music performances. The church building itself has no tower.

name: De Ark
description:
De Ark is a church building of the Protestant Church in the Netherlands (PKN), located in Veldhuizen, Ede. The name of the church refers to Noah's Ark.

The church hall has an octagonal shape with four long and four short sides. The sloping roof features triangular glass panels above the short sides and square panels above the long sides, creating a square flat upper section. These glass panels allow ample natural light to enter. The liturgical center and pulpit are situated on one of the short sides.

Around the church hall, there is a corridor with side rooms. Two of these rooms can be connected to the church hall by opening a roller door. The walls are made of brick in clean masonry. The floor consists of gravel tiles. The pulpit is constructed from concrete and light woodwork, while the sacrament table and baptismal font are also made of light wood. At the entrance of the church is a memorial stone with a text from Genesis 7 verse 1.

name: De Ark
description:
De Ark is a Protestant church building located in Kamperland, in the Zeeland province. It's situated on the Veerweg. The church was originally built in 1923 as a Reformed Church, replacing an older church from 1909.

Initially, the Reformed church of Kamperland emerged in 1866. Later, after a merger of several churches, it became the Reformed Church. In the years that followed, the building was renovated and expanded, including the addition of a meeting space. It acquired the name "De Ark" during one of these renovations. Following a national merger of several denominations into the Protestant Church in the Netherlands, the local congregations also merged in 2005, creating the Protestant congregation of Kamperland.

name: De Ark (Slotervaart)
description:
De Ark is a church building in the Slotervaart neighborhood in Amsterdam Nieuw-West. It was built in 1960-61, designed by architect Piet Zanstra. Since 2008, the building has been listed as a municipal monument and is on Amsterdam's Top-100 list of young monuments.

The church has bronze doors depicting four scenes from the story of Noah, designed by Irene Lopez-Zanstra. A unique aspect of the church is a prayer chapel, intended to be a space for reflection and prayer open to everyone during the day. The prayer chapel maintains its original stained glass window illustrating the Genesis creation story. The church building was renovated in 2015-2016 and also includes a professional kitchen, living room and activity rooms.

name: De Bron
description:
De Bron is a church building located at Vogelplein 1 in Amersfoort. It originally served as a Reformed church called De Open Hof. In 2004, it became part of the Protestant Church in the Netherlands, ministering to members in the Liendert neighborhood.

The church was renovated in 2011-2012, gaining a slanted roof to give it a more traditional church-like appearance. Marco Tavenier from Bureau MT in Amersfoort was the architect behind this renovation. Following the renovation, the Opstandingskerk was decommissioned. The church's organ dates back to 1959. De Bron is a contemporary Protestant community, open to diverse expressions of faith. The church is open every Friday afternoon for coffee, tea and socialising.

name: De Brug
description:
De Brug is a church building located on the Schuilenburgerweg in Amersfoort. It serves the members of the Protestant Community of Amersfoort in the Schuilenburg district.

The brick church, built in 1970, is designed in a modernist style. The relatively low church hall has a slightly sloping roof. There are also a number of low outbuildings. Originally a Dutch Reformed church, it later became part of the PKN. The church was renovated in 2006. The Chinese Christian Church Netherlands (CCGN) also uses the building. The organ dates from 1970 and was built by the Firma J. de Koff.

name: De Duif
description:
De Duif, or "The Dove," is a church located on the Prinsengracht canal in Amsterdam. Built in 1858, it was designed by Theo Molkenboer as the Roman Catholic St. Willibrorduskerk. It replaced an older church that had become too small and was the first Catholic church in the Netherlands to be built with a public entrance after religious freedom was proclaimed.

The church is built in the neo-classicist style with a Neo-baroque front. De Duif is now a rijksmonument (national monument) and is known for the large Smits-orgel inside, which is also a rijksmonument. After a restoration, the church is now used for various events, including concerts, dance performances, and weddings. It has a "floating" wooden floor and can accommodate hundreds of visitors.

name: De Eendracht
description: De Eendracht is a church building of the Liberal Religious Community NPB in Varsseveld, Netherlands. It was built in 1928, replacing the previous church from 1882. The plastered church has a small portal with a pointed gable on the street side. The facades feature pointed arch windows, always in pairs. A small lantern is placed on the roof. Inside, the church has a pointed barrel vault. The church has been designated as a municipal monument. In 2011, the church was largely renovated.

name: De Fontein
description: De Fontein in Leeuwarden is a church building located on the north side of the city. Formerly known as De Open Hof of the Reformed Church, it was renamed De Fontein in 2014. The church is managed by Beheer Kerkgebouwen Leeuwarden (BKL). The building offers various halls with capacities ranging from 15 to 300 people, along with a foyer. These spaces are suitable for a wide range of activities, including concerts, symposia, conferences, and presentations.

name: De Hoeksteen
description:
De Hoeksteen was a church building located in the city center of Haarlem. Constructed in a Neo-Romanesque style, its construction started in 1910 and it was in use from 1913 by the Christian Reformed Church in Haarlem-Center. It had a small, attached bell tower.

The church had an organ that was initially deemed too small and was replaced in 1948 with one from another church, featuring pipes dating back to 1863. The last service took place on April 27, 2003. Despite efforts to save it, the church was demolished in 2005 to make way for the Raakskwartier construction project.

name: De Hoeksteen
description: De Hoeksteen in Amersfoort is originally a Dutch Reformed church building. It is located at Klaartje Donzepad 59 in the Schothorst district of Amersfoort. Currently, it is part of the Protestant Church of Amersfoort. The church previously housed an organ from the Ontmoetingskerk, which was closed in 1984. The organ was installed in De Hoeksteen in 1987 and was restored and expanded in 2006. De Hoeksteen also organizes activities for the youth. JOKE (JOngerenKErk) is there for young people between 12 and 15 years old.

name: De Hoeksteen
description: De Hoeksteen was a reformed church in Barchem, Netherlands, built in 1898 and opened a year later. It was a simple, small hall church featuring three pointed arch windows on the street side of its side facade. Above these windows, small dormers were built into the roof. In 1980, it was significantly expanded with an extension featuring a flat roof. The church was affiliated with the Dorpskerk in Ruurlo. Organizationally, it fell under the PKN (Protestant Church in the Netherlands) starting in 2008. The last church service was held in 2016. The building was sold and, while maintaining its style, was converted to accommodate a physiotherapy practice and a gym.

name: De Hoeksteen
description: De Hoeksteen, meaning "the cornerstone," is a church building in Barneveld, Netherlands. It is used by the Reformed Congregations in the Netherlands. Opened in 2008, it's one of the largest church buildings in the country. The main hall has a height of 21.25 meters, and its spire reaches 37.75 meters high. The church has a seating capacity for 2531 people. The benches are arranged on different levels, ensuring everyone can see the pulpit. Besides the congregations in the Netherlands, there are five other congregations located in South Africa and North America.

name: De Kandelaar
description:
De Kandelaar is a former Reformed Church in Amsterdam Nieuw-West, designed by architect Geert Kliphuis. It was commissioned by the Reformed Church, and it was their first building in Amsterdam.
