The church has a hall with seating for 450 people, a council room, a hall, meeting rooms and a kitchenette. A parsonage is also attached. A special detail is the detached bell tower in front of the facade, which according to Kliphuis was both inviting and admonitory.

The building opened on January 31, 1964. The front and rear facades have a sawtooth pattern with alternating glass and brick strips, while the facade on the Burgemeester Fockstraat is entirely made of brick. The name refers to the Holy Scripture, a giver of light in the height and shines in the darkness. Since 1973, the Salvation Army has owned the building. In 2007, it was renovated and expanded. Since 2012, community center activities have also taken place there.

name: De Kandelaar
description: De Kandelaar in Amsterdam-Zuidoost is a multi-functional building that accommodates fifteen migrant churches. The building has five church halls with space for 900 worshipers. It also provides space for self-organisations, a daycare centre, and a catering facility. The building has four floors, with the daycare centre on the ground floor. In the central hall is a baptismal font donated by the Bond van Vrije Evangelische Gemeenten. The first floor contains offices, the second floor has four small church halls, and the third floor has a large church hall for 400 people.

name: De Kloof
description: The Compagnietheater is housed in a former Evangelical Lutheran church built in 1793 in the Dutch Classicism style. The interior originally had sparse decorations, in line with Lutheran principles. However, much of even those decorations, including cornices, were later removed. The building served different secular functions for over a hundred years. It was renovated in the late 90s by architect Francine Houben, who combined the authentic pillars and windows with industrial elements, creating a mix of classic and modern materials. The main hall retains its history with a ceiling that rises in round shapes and wooden columns.

name: De Krijtberg
description:
The Krijtberg Church, a Roman Catholic church located on the Singel in Amsterdam, was designed by Alfred Tepe and opened in 1883. Dedicated to St. Francis Xavier, it is known for its neo-Gothic style, featuring two pointed towers. Space limitations led to an unusually tall design with a monumental front. The interior, crafted by Friedrich Wilhelm Mengelberg, is exuberantly decorated.

Since 1654, there has been a Jesuit church at this location. The current church was built on the same site as previous clandestine churches. The Krijtberg's construction was never entirely finished, with new elements added over time, such as the confessionals dating from 1889 and stained glass windows installed in 1946.

name: De Liefde
description:
De Liefde is the common name for the Roman Catholic Parish Church of the Saints Nicholas and Barbara in Amsterdam-West. The first church building was built in 1786 outside the Singelgracht. The church, named De Liefde after the nearby cemetery, was dedicated to Saint Nicholas of Myra.

In the 1880s, a larger church was needed due to the construction of the Kinkerbuurt. A new church, a neo-Gothic, three-aisled basilica designed by P.J.H. Cuypers, was built between 1883 and 1885. In 1992, the old church was replaced by a new building. A flat complex was built, with a small section used as a parish church. The diocese relinquished this space in 2013.

name: De Nieuwe Stad
description: Kerkcentrum De Nieuwe Stad is a Dutch church in Amsterdam-Zuidoost (Bijlmermeer), built in 1992/1993 and designed by the architects Lafour and Wijk. The architects had previously worked in urban renewal areas but had not yet designed a church building. The building houses two church halls, a large hall, and communal areas. It replaced an earlier church center with the same name. At least two church halls allow simultaneous services by various denominations, including the Protestant Church of the Netherlands (PKN), the Roman Catholic Church, the Evangelical Brotherhood, the Evangelical Lutheran Church, and other denominations such as Perki, the R.K. Antillean Church, Baptist Church, Damascus Church, Global Revival, Maranatha, and True Faith.

name: De Pijler
description:
De Pijler is an evangelical church located in Lelystad, Flevoland, Netherlands. It was established in 1977 by pastor Gerard Langhenkel. Initially, the congregation met in a building called De Ark, but due to increasing numbers, they moved to De Pijler in 2000, which has a seating capacity of 1,047.

The church based its services on the community concept of the American Willow Creek Community Church. In 2007, the church parted ways with its founder, Gerard Langhenkel, who then started a new congregation. In 2010, Kees van Velzen, formerly associated with the Evangelische Omroep, became the pastor of De Pijler. In 2017, the church had an average weekly attendance of 1,100 people.

name: De Rode Hoed
description: De Rode Hoed is the largest and oldest hidden church in the Netherlands, located behind the facades of three 17th-century canal houses. It's found in Amsterdam's historical city center. The main hall, situated in the former wooden church, can accommodate up to 450 people. Besides the main hall, there are five smaller chambers, making it a flexible location for events, conferences, meetings, and dinners. The Oosterhuiszaal has unique elements like wooden pillars, authentic woodwork, two balconies, and a restored organ. It is known for its excellent acoustics and has been the venue for popular TV shows and political debates.

name: De Salvator
description:
The Salvator Church in Leeuwarden was built for the Reformed Church and designed by architect Egbert Reitsma. It was inaugurated on December 14, 1962. In 1966, a new organ built by the Verschueren company was installed. The last Reformed service took place in June 1994.

In 1996, the building was purchased by the Evangelical Church of Leeuwarden, who had previously been located in a former school. The adjacent parsonage and sexton's house were sold separately. The Salvator Church and the church community were then renamed De Salvator.

The interior was adapted for the evangelical services, with the pulpit and deacon benches removed and a larger stage installed. In 2014, the interior of the church hall was thoroughly renovated and modernized and in 2018, De Salvator became part of City Life Church and was officially renamed City Life Church Leeuwarden.

name: De Schakel
description: De Schakel is a church building in Leeuwarden, built in 1993 and designed by architectural firm Anne van der Meer. It is located in the Camminghaburen district. A narrow stained glass window, together with a horizontal crossbar, forms a cross. The church houses several works of art. The stained glass windows are memorials from young people to the Taizé Community. A wooden Celtic cross serves as a reminder of the island of Iona. De Schakel is a multifunctional building; in addition to church services, it is also used for meetings, exams, courses and concerts.

name: De Tabernakel
description:
De Tabernakel is the church building of the Christian Reformed Church in Ede, located in the province of Gelderland in the Netherlands. It is used for church services on Sundays and Christian holidays.

The church has a simple structure based on square and rectangular surfaces. However, this is hardly noticeable in the appearance due to the varying heights and building parts. The building is positioned diagonally with a sloping roof, on which there is a roof turret with a bell. The same sloping roof is reflected in the porch.

name: De Voorhof
description: De Voorhof in Woudenberg was built in 1975 as a joint church center for the Reformed Church and the Reformed Municipality of Salem. It was officially opened on May 19, 1976. The name was chosen based on Psalm 100, verse 4. The hall of De Voorhof was thoroughly renovated and modernized in the autumn of 2015. The youth room has also been modernized.

name: Der Aa-kerk
description:
The Aa-kerk, also known as A-kerk, is a historic church located in the center of Groningen. It is one of the city's most important medieval buildings, along with the Martinikerk. Originally a chapel devoted to Mary and Saint Nicholas, it became a parish church in 1247.

Between 1425 and 1495, the chapel was transformed into a brick Gothic church. Over the course of its history, the church has undergone several alterations due to iconoclasm, war damage, and natural events. The tower collapsed multiple times and was rebuilt. Today, the Aa-kerk is used as a venue for concerts, theatre, exhibitions, parties, and meetings, and is no longer used for church services.

name: Derde Jezuïetenkerk
description: The Canisianum, also known as the Second Jesuit Monastery, is a former monastery and theological faculty of the Jesuits in the center of Maastricht. The chapel served for some time as the auditorium of the university and is now a study hall. The mosaics in the apse and on the triumphal arch, and the stained glass windows were designed by Marianne van der Heijden. The hall contains stained glass windows by Hub Levigne (with the Liberation of Maastricht as its theme) and Henri Jonas (with the Betrayal of Maastricht). A large statue of Petrus Canisius by Charles Vos adorns the overhanging facade of the library.

name: Derde Minderbroederskerk
description: The Third Friars Minor Church, or Third Franciscan Monastery, was a monastery of the Franciscans in the center of the Dutch city of Maastricht. The monastery, built from 1856, was demolished in 1971. It was located behind the buildings on the north side of Tongersestraat and the east side of Abtstraat. Nowadays this area is called Patersbaan. Only the gate at the beginning of the Patersbaan is a reminder of the monastery. In 1970, the church and monastery were sold to a contractor, and a year later, the buildings, the church and the old chapel were demolished.

name: Dominicanenkerk
description:
The Dominicanenkerk in Maastricht is a Gothic monastery church located in the city center, near the Vrijthof. Constructed with marlstone, it was consecrated in 1294. The church's original function ended in 1795, after which it served various purposes, including use as a stable, depot, slaughterhouse, bicycle storage, exhibition space, and event venue.

In 2005, a large-scale renovation began, preserving sacral elements like stained-glass windows, frescoes, and 17th-century vault paintings. The oldest known wall painting, depicting the life of St. Thomas Aquinas from 1337, can be seen on the northern wall. Since 2006, the restored church has housed the Boekhandel Dominicanen bookstore. The former choir area now hosts a café.

name: Dominicanenkerk
description: The Dominican Church in Zwolle is part of the Dominicanenklooster, a large complex built between 1900 and 1902. The church, designed by architect J. Kayser in neo-Gothic style, is a cross basilica featuring a continuous claustrum corridor around a courtyard garden. The design was inspired by the old Dominican priory at Dusseldorf. The first stone was laid in 1900, and the church was consecrated in 1902. Inside, the Altar of the Blessed Sacrament with its tabernacle is a notable feature, along with several themed stained-glass windows. Today, the church is part of a parish that welcomes everyone.

name: Dominicuskerk
description:
The Dominicuskerk, also known as the Dominican Church, is a Roman Catholic church located on the Spuistraat in Amsterdam. Built between 1883 and 1893, it was designed by Pierre Cuypers, a renowned Dutch architect also responsible for the Rijksmuseum and Amsterdam Central Station. The church stands on the site of a former hidden church.

Cuypers designed not only the building, but also the interior, from the altar to the organ case and from murals to confessionals. The neo-Gothic altar was placed in the church almost two years after it was consecrated. The Dominicuskerk is still in use and the only Cuypers church in Amsterdam that is.

Although a high tower of 93 meters was initially planned, it was never constructed, resulting in the church's somewhat unremarkable tower today.

name: Dominicuskerk
description:
The Dominicuskerk is a Roman Catholic church in Nijmegen, located on the Professor Molkenboerstraat. It was built between 1948 and 1951, replacing the older Dominicuskerk that stood on the Broerstraat since 1373 but was damaged during World War II.

Architect Thomas Nix designed the current church in the traditionalist style of the Bossche School, including the parish complex around a courtyard. The Dominicuskerk is a cruciform church constructed with brick and concrete. A tympanum with sculptures by Jac Maris is situated between the nave and the choir. The semi-circular apse is on the east side, and a bell tower is on the south side.

name: Domkerk
description:
The Dom of Utrecht, historically St. Martin's Cathedral, is a prominent Gothic church in the center of Utrecht. Construction began in 1254, continuing the Romanesque cathedral of the Roman Catholic Diocese of Utrecht. Since 1580, it has been a Protestant church.

The 112.32-meter-high Dom Tower is the highest church tower in the Netherlands. Originally part of a larger church, the nave collapsed in 1674 due to a storm, leaving the tower separated from the remaining parts: the choir and transept. The complex includes a cloister and the large chapter house, where the Union of Utrecht was signed in 1579.

name: Don Boscokerk
description: The Don Boscokerk is a modern church building located in Maastricht. Designed by Harry Koene, it is characterized as a high cruciform church with a flat roof. Constructed entirely of brick, the church's interior features clean masonry and a concrete coffered ceiling. A notable feature is the five layers of five arched windows on either side of the altar area, filled with stained glass exhibiting geometric motifs. Originally a Roman Catholic parish church, it has been used as a Baptist church since 2017. Project developer Metropool Developement purchased the building in 2020.

name: Don Boscokerk
description:
The Don Boscokerk, also known as the Johannes Boscokerk, is a former parish church in Venlo-Oost. The construction of the church began in late 1955, and it was consecrated in 1957. The architects were Frans Stoks and Rats.

It is a basilica church with high side aisles, featuring a concrete skeleton clad in brick. The facade is flanked by two hexagonal bell towers, both topped with onion-shaped domes adorned with a cross. The notably wide nave is vaulted with a cross vault made of clean brickwork. The central nave is supported by concrete pillars. Due to declining church attendance and rising costs, it was deconsecrated in May 2016.

name: Don Boscokerk
description:
The Don Boscokerk was a former church in Alkmaar, located in the Overdie district. Built in 1961 and designed by architect Van Kranendonk, it was a modern church with a square floor plan and a unique design resembling a "stolpboerderij" (a traditional West Frisian farmhouse) without a tower.

The building featured a colonnade of concrete supporting a high wooden tent roof. Light entered the space from above through an opening in the roof, where a bell was also placed. Stained glass windows, crafted by Joep Nicolas, adorned the spaces between the pillars of the colonnade. Despite opposition from citizens, the church was demolished in August 2007. Some of the stained glass windows were relocated to the Sint Jozefkerk in Alkmaar, and the organ was moved to a church in Roermond.

name: Don Boscokerk
description:
The Don Boscokerk was a Roman Catholic parish church located on Mimosaplein in the Stratum district of Eindhoven. Built in 1953, it was designed by architect Kees de Bever and inspired by early Christian church architecture from the 6th century.

The church is a three-aisled brick structure. Unusually, the altar was located in the center, creating a T-shape with only a nave and transept. The central area is topped by a robust square structure with four attics holding bells, crowned by a pediment. A low, round tower sits in the middle. Other notable features include a nearly detached cylindrical tower to the left of the facade and a round baptistery.

Due to declining church attendance, the nave was used for services in the early 1970s, with community facilities in the transept. The final service was held on March 19, 2006, after which the church was sold. In 2020, the church was transformed into a residential complex with 17 apartments, while preserving the original aesthetic elements.

name: Donatuskerk
description:
The Donatuskerk in Leermens is one of the oldest churches in the northern Netherlands. Construction began around 1050, showcasing Romanesque, Roman-Gothic, and Gothic elements. The building incorporates both tuff stone and brick.

Inside, the nave and transept feature wooden ceilings, while the choir has a dome vault with painted brick patterns. Fifteenth-century murals, including one of Saint Ursula, adorn the interior. The church suffered heavy damage in a 1957 fire. The 17th-century pulpit is the only remaining old furnishing. The church has visible traces of history both outside and inside. On the vaults are paintings of the symbols of the four evangelists.

name: Doopsgezinde Kerk
description:
The Doopsgezinde Kerk in Assen originated in 1896 as a circle from the Mennonite congregation in Meppel, becoming independent in 1899. From 1902, the congregation met in the Nutsgebouw on Javastraat. In 1905, a piece of land was purchased on Oranjestraat for a church building. The new church was put into use in 1909.

Designed by city architect Taeke Boonstra, the building's exterior features Jugendstil elements, while the interior is sober. In the 1950s, an extension called "de Doevekamp" was added for joint youth work with the Vereniging van Vrijzinnige Hervormden. The church is listed as a municipal monument. The last church service was held on December 28, 2019, after 110 years, and the building was sold to an artist. The Mennonite Congregation of Assen was dissolved on January 1, 2020.

name: Doopsgezinde Vermaning
description:
The Doopsgezinde Kerk in Enkhuizen is located at the Venedie. The church, including its interior, has been a protected national monument since 1997. It was built in 1892 in Neo-Renaissance style, designed by architect U.J. Van der Meulen. The church replaced an earlier church from 1798.

The church's design is similar to one built in Vlissingen three years prior. The church space has a rectangular floor plan, with the portal entrance on the long west side and the consistory and meeting rooms on the east side. The pulpit, originating from the reformed church in Appeltern, stands against the east wall. The walls are plastered white, with green paneling in the lower zone.

name: Doopsgezinde kerk
description:
The Doopsgezinde Kerk (Mennonite Church) is a church building in Leeuwarden, in the province of Friesland, Netherlands. The church is a monumental classicist building without a tower.

The hall church was built in 1760. In 1832, a house next to it was demolished, and the church was given an entrance portico with Doric columns. The interior is covered by barrel vaults and a dome. The pulpit (1786) and the organ built by J.S. Strümphler (1786) both come from the Mennonite church "De Zon" in Amsterdam. The stained-glass windows on either side of the pulpit were made in 1954 by Joep Nicolas. The church occasionally serves as a venue for cultural events.

name: Doopsgezinde kerk
description:
The Doopsgezinde Kerk in Alkmaar is a hall church and a national monument. It is one of the oldest stone Mennonite churches in the Netherlands. The church was built in 1617 at the initiative of preacher Hans de Ries. It was originally built as a hidden church, as Mennonites were tolerated but not allowed to have visible churches. Until 1856, the front was hidden behind houses. The rear of the church was disguised as a warehouse facade.

In 1835, the church facade was renovated in Neoclassical style. In 1819, a cabinet organ was installed. In 1876, the interior was drastically renovated. In 1908, the windows were fitted with stained glass. In 1961, the almshouses attached to the church were demolished and replaced by a meeting hall.

name: Doopsgezinde kerk
description: The building at Ramen 31 in Hoorn, Netherlands, is a former Mennonite church. It is described as an old church building.

name: Doopsgezinde kerk
description: The Doopsgezinde Kerk in Utrecht was built in 1772/1773 on the site of the former 'Witte Leeuw' brewery. During that time, non-Calvinist Protestant groups weren't allowed to practice their religion, so the church was built with a 'residence'-like facade. Some structural elements of the brewery, particularly the side and back walls, were integrated into the church. The facade, however, was entirely new and designed in Louis XVI style. The interior is very plain, in keeping with the Mennonites' religious views. The layout of the church has a central women's section surrounded by the men's pews.

name: Doopsgezinde kerk
description:
The Doopsgezinde Kerk in Middelburg, also known as the Mennonite Church, is located on Lange Noordstraat. The building, dating back to 1889, was designed by the Mennonite architect Klaas Stoffels, who had previously designed the Paleiskerk in The Hague. The church's architecture is eclectic, incorporating elements from various neo-styles, particularly Neo-Renaissance.

The walls are constructed of brick with white natural stone layers. Inside, the pulpit and organ case were also designed by Stoffels. While the interior colors have been altered, the woodwork was adapted in 1986 to match the white and Swedish red of the church windows. In 2008, gold leaf was added to the organ case to enhance its details. The 19th-century building, excluding later additions, was declared a national monument in 1997, recognized for the integrity of both its exterior and interior.

name: Doopsgezinde kerk
description: The Doopsgezinde Kerk in Surhuisterveen, Friesland, is a church building dating back to 1804. The first stone was laid on May 5th, 1804. It is a simple hall church with a three-sided closed choir and an openwork roof turret topped with a weather vane in the shape of a ship. The walls feature round-arched windows and are articulated by shallow panels. A consistory connects the church to the parsonage, which dates back to 1865. The church is a national monument. The organ, built in 1975 by Klaus Becker, was installed in the church in 1980. In 2022 the tower was affected by wood rot and was removed for restoration.

name: Doopsgezinde kerk
description:
The Doopsgezinde Kerk in Winterswijk was built in 1711 as a hidden church, designed to resemble a warehouse. This was because, at the time, religious freedom was not fully established, and other religions were tolerated but not completely accepted.

In case of danger, a means of escape was added to the building. Inside, it features a wooden vault. The year of construction is noted on a foundation stone in the facade. The church is now a rijksmonument, a protected national monument.

name: Doopsgezinde kerk
description:
The Mennonite Church in Groningen is located in a side alley of the Oude Boteringestraat. Originally, a wooden hidden church was located here, behind a house. The current church building was constructed after the Mennonites gained full equality during the French era. The church was inaugurated on October 29, 1815.

In 1809, two Mennonite congregations, the Oude Vlamingen and the Waterlanders and Vlamingen, merged. The church has a neoclassical style. In 1852-1853, the church was expanded. The demolition of the house in front made the church visible from the street. Major renovations in 1961 and 1990 altered the interior, including replacing the old organ with a Marcussen organ and a modern liturgical center. The church has stained glass windows from 1915 and 1935.

name: Doopsgezinde kerk
description:
The Doopsgezinde Kerk, also known as the Mennistenkerk, is a former church building located on the Stadsgravenstraat in Enschede. It is a municipal monument. The church has a wooden tower with a spire on a gable with sandstone coping. Next to the church is the former sexton's house, which consists of a ground floor and an attic. This building is now used as a city brewery and café.

The Mennistenkerk previously stood on this site from 1769 but was destroyed in a city fire in 1862. The church was rebuilt and reopened in 1864. The Mennonite congregation sold the church building in 1971, after which it had various functions.

name: Doopsgezinde vermaning
description:
The Doopsgezinde kerk in Middelie, also known as the 'church of Middelie', is a church built in 1899, replacing a smaller wooden church. In 1899, the Mennonite community decided to build a new church. The construction was partly made possible by a donation from brother J.D. Bark.

The interior has a wooden roof and is mostly preserved in its original state. The interior includes a pulpit, a seating plan and two chandeliers from the time of construction. Under the organ is a memorial stone with text and the year of the laying of the first stone in 1899. The church is a national monument. The building is still used as a church for the Mennonite congregation of Middelie and Axwijk.

name: Dorpskerk
description:
The Dorpskerk Huizum, dating back to the 12th century, is the oldest monument in Leeuwarden. It boasts a valuable interior and is currently used for concerts, exhibitions, and lectures. The church and its old graveyard attract many visitors.

Key features inside include the pulpit, the only one in Friesland from pre-Reformation times, notable pews, baptismal objects from the Golden Age, and sculpted limestone tombstones. A bronze relief from the Dutch poet Jan Slauerhoff can also be found within the church.

name: Dorpskerk
description: The Dorpskerk in Blokker is a Dutch Reformed hall church dating back to the 19th century. It stands on the same site where its medieval predecessor was destroyed by fire in 1864. While the exact origins of a church at this location are unknown, it is documented that a parish existed in Westerblokker around 1513. Based on drawings and engravings, the original church likely had late-Gothic features from the early 16th century. The church tower has an octagonal spire covered with slate. At the very top is a weathervane on top of a gilded pomegranate that represents Jesus Christ. The church organ was built in 1871 and its case is in Neo-Renaissance style.

name: Dorpskerk
description: The Dorpskerk in Kleverskerke is a Protestant church. The current building dates from 1862, but a chapel already stood on the site in 1251. In 1861, a tender was held for the demolition of the old church and the construction of a new church. The first stone was laid on April 2, 1862, and the new church was put into use on September 14. In 1905 an organ was purchased. In 1975, a new one-manual organ was purchased and placed on a gallery. The church is located in Kleverskerke, which is a road village and one of the smallest villages in the Netherlands.

name: Dorpskerk
description: The Dorpskerk in Nieuw- en Sint Joosland is a Protestant church. The current church, featuring neo-Gothic and neo-Romanesque elements, was built in 1883, replacing a church from 1650. In the late 19th century, the old church became dilapidated, leading to the construction of a new one. The last service in the old church was held on February 26, 1882, after which it was demolished. The current church was opened on May 6, 1883. The building is a hall church with Gothic windows. A new organ, built by Van Vulpen from Utrecht, was installed on June 3, 1976.

name: Dorpskerk
description: The Dorpskerk in Kamperland is a former Protestant church building located on Veerweg. Constructed in 1901, the church was decommissioned and sold in February 1998. As of 2017, the building has been repurposed into a restaurant. A 23-year-old entrepreneur transformed the church into a family brasserie, retaining the original high, wooden ceiling and old church floor. The facade tower was also preserved as a recognizable feature.

name: Dorpskerk
description: The Dorpskerk in Dieren is a neoclassical building located in the Gelderland region. It was built between 1846 and 1848 by order of Sophia Wilhelmina van Heeckeren van Kell, widow of Jacob Unico Wilhelm van Wassenaer Obdam, who resided at Hof te Dieren. In 1876, a new section was added to the north side, giving the church a T-shape. The rectangular hall church features round-arched windows and a simple tower of three brick sections. The top section has masonry pilasters at the corners, and a square wooden upper story with clock faces and a domed roof. The entrance portal has consoles and a crowning pediment. As of 2005, the church is privately owned and has been renovated into office spaces.

name: Dorpskerk
description:
The Dorpskerk in Hoog-Keppel is a late Gothic pseudo-basilica dating back to the 15th century. Originally, it had side aisles, but around 1740 the north aisle was demolished, followed by the south aisle later that century.

The oldest mention of the church is in a document from 1310, mentioning a new altar dedicated to Maria. Since 2012, the Dorpskerk Hoog-Keppel is owned by Gelderse Kerken. Since 2023, the consistory has served as office space for this foundation. Besides church services, church weddings and funerals, the Dorpskerk is also available for civil wedding ceremonies. Moreover, the Dorpskerk is increasingly developing into a regionally known exhibition center and concert hall.

name: Dorpskerk
description:
The Dorpskerk in Opheusden is the oldest church in the village. It's a late Gothic village church featuring a three-aisled, pseudo-basilica nave and transept, dating back to 1524. The choir is even older, originating from the 15th century.

The church was damaged during war actions in 1940, and restored and expanded in 1952. It has a tower with a bell from 1609. Since 2007, it has been used by the Restored Reformed Church. The church has a rich history, and underwent roof restoration in 2008.

name: Dorpskerk
description:
The Dorpskerk in Ruurlo, originally the Onze Lieve Vrouwekerk, is a Protestant church built in the 14th century. It features a brick ship and chancel, covered by a roof with cross-ribbed vaults. Originally a Roman Catholic church dedicated to St. Willibrordus, it became a Dutch Reformed church after the Reformation.

Throughout the centuries, the church has undergone several restorations due to age and storm damage, notably in the late 18th century. During World War II, the German army confiscated the church bells, which were replaced with new ones after the war. In 2018, the interior was renovated to create a flexible space for various events, including concerts and meetings. The church includes a pulpit from the 17th century and an organ made in 1840.

name: Dorpskerk
description: The Dorpskerk of Vaassen has a tower that dates back to the 15th century, while the nave was built in 1853. The current church is over 150 years old and is the focal point of the village of Vaassen. Before the current structure, another church stood on the same site. In 1852, architect Looman from Deventer was commissioned to design a new church because the previous one was too small. Contractor Wegerif from Apeldoorn built the new church. The Dorpskerk was the first church building in Gelderland built in the neo-Gothic style. In 2002, a new mechanical organ was built in the old organ case by organ builder René Nijsse.

name: Dorpskerk
description: The Dorpskerk, also known as the Antoniuskerk, is a Protestant church in Vorden, Netherlands. The first known mention of it as a parish church dates back to 1235. Around 1500, a side aisle was added to the north side. On the east side is a 3/8 choir closure with pointed arch windows. The church tower dates from the 14th century and was raised during renovations around 1500. The tower now consists of four sections and is crowned with a constricted spire. After the Reformation, when the church passed to the Protestants, the murals and statues disappeared from the church. Some murals were made visible again in 1995. The church organ from 1833 was made by Hinderk Berends Lohman and restored in 1982.

name: Dorpskerk
description:
The Dorpskerk of Heesbeen is a single-nave, rectangular church with arched windows dating back to the 18th century. Underneath a layer of plaster, remnants of the north and south walls of a Romanesque tuff church can be found, with clear traces of a Romanesque window in the south wall. The original choir was replaced in the 18th century with a brick, rectangular choir. The brick tower is much older, likely from the 14th century.

Inside, you can find an oak pulpit and a lord's pew from the 18th century. Also notable is a tombstone featuring sculpted figures of Willem Torck, lord of Heesbeen, who died in 1557, and his wife Bartha Pieck. Surrounding the churchyard is a brick wall with a gatehouse on the north side, featuring a gable roof between stepped gables. The belfry contains a bell made by J. van Haer in 1393.

name: Dorpskerk
description:
The Dorpskerk in Staphorst is one of the largest churches in the Netherlands, measured by the number of seats. It is used for church services by the Restored Reformed Church in Staphorst. The current church was built between 1952 and 1954, because the previous one had become too small for the growing congregation. The tower of the old church from 1763 has remained.

In 1991-92, the church was considerably enlarged, because the building had become too small. At the same time, the tower was raised from 20 to 32 meters, because otherwise the relationship between the church and the tower would no longer be correct. The church has a seating capacity of 2,300.

name: Dorpskerk
description:
The Dorpskerk in Driewegen is a Protestant church that was inaugurated in 1678, built in a classicist style. It was one of the first Reformation churches in Zuid-Beveland. The facade features an inscription about fundraising by the Lords of Watervliet in 1659 for the church's construction. The facade is decorated with natural stone, and above it, there is a tower on the ridge of the church.

Inside the bell tower, there is a tower clock from 1906. The church has a simple interior with a pipe organ at the front. The pulpit is sculpted and dates back to 1679. The entrance to the churchyard is flanked by brick pillars with shield-bearing lions, bearing the arms of Driewegen and Coudorpe. The pipe organ incorporates older parts, with the organ case dating from 1914 and the internal components from 1933.

name: Dorpskerk Almen
description:
The Dorpskerk in Almen is a Protestant church with a history dating back to the 13th century. The church itself was built in the 14th century. By 1271, there was already a parish in Almen. During the Reformation, the church became Protestant, and Almen received its first preacher in 1598.

The brick church tower consists of three sections and contains two bells from 1645, cast by the brothers Pieter and François Hemony. Inside the single-nave church is an 11th-century baptismal font made of Bentheim sandstone. It was found during excavation work under the floor of the tower portal in 1834 and then regained its original function. A crypt beneath the choir holds the graves of notable people, including mummified remains of noble families.

name: Driekoningenkerk
description:
The Driekoningenkerk in Noordgouwe is a Dutch Reformed church dating back to 1462. It was built next to the former Sion Carthusian monastery. After the Reformation, the monastery fell into disrepair, and stones from the monastery were used for the church's restoration in 1577.

The church has a single-aisle layout with a wooden barrel vault, a three-sided choir, and two transept-like chapels with ribbed vaults. In 1846, the southern chapel was demolished, and the church was adorned with neo-Gothic decorations. The 1953 flood severely damaged the building, but during restoration work, the southern chapel was reconstructed, and the exterior appearance was restored by reversing the 1846 changes. The church tower is built into the nave and surrounded by a church moat.

name: Eben-Haëzerkerk
description:
The Eben-Haëzerkerk in Arnemuiden is a Reformed church building located on Kerklaan. It was constructed between 1966 and 1967 to replace an older church on Lionstraat. The congregation is part of the Protestant Church in the Netherlands since 2004.

The church's origins trace back to August 19, 1888, with the establishment of a dissenting congregation in Arnemuiden. Early services were held in a barn. Within a few years, a small wooden church was built on Molenweg. This building was considered unattractive and was even called "the shed."

name: Eben-Haëzerkerk
description:
The Eben-Haëzerkerk is one of the largest churches in Apeldoorn, it was opened on October 6, 1995. The church was built for a special district congregation founded in 1979, which is affiliated with the PKN and part of the Reformed Association. Valk architects from Soest designed the building.

Besides the large church hall that can accommodate 750 to 800 people, the building has several rooms for church meetings and associations. The Steendam organ in the church was completed in 1997. The organ builder and the architect were able to collaborate early in the construction, so the organ and the building form a cohesive whole.

name: Eikstraatkerk
description: The Eikstraatkerk is a former church building in the Dutch city of Hoorn. It's a hall church with a gable roof and a front porch, built in 1933-1934 by architect Cornelis Trappenburg from Hilversum in the style of the Amsterdam School. The narrow church tower has a spire with three horizontal discs at its base. From 1934 to 2001, the church was used by the Orthodox Reformed Church and was also rented by the Evangelical Brethren. After its closure, the church was converted into an apartment complex. The exterior of this expressionistic church with a tower has been well preserved.

name: Eilandskerk
description: The Eilandskerk was located on Bickerseiland in Amsterdam. The original wooden building was replaced by a stone structure starting in 1736, and the new church was completed in 1739. In 1877, Vincent van Gogh visited the Eilandskerk to hear his Uncle Stricker preach. He attended multiple services there and wrote about them to his brother Theo, describing one service by Jan Jacob Lodewijk ten Kate. The church was very busy, and the square outside was full of carriages. The Eilandskerk was demolished in 1950. Today, the Bickersgracht canal and the surrounding islands evoke the atmosphere of old Amsterdam.

name: El Fath-moskee
description: The El Fath Mosque in Maastricht-West is a Moroccan mosque. It is a brick building distinguished by a square minaret. The mosque is part of the Islamic Society. A Turkish cultural center is located behind the mosque. The mosque is located on Sint Lucassingel.

name: Elbakerk
description:
The Elbakerk, officially named Elisabeth and Barbara, is a former church building in Haarlem, Netherlands. The name Elba is a portmanteau of Elisabeth and Barbara. Built as a neo-Gothic cruciform basilica, designed by architect A.A.M. Bruning, its construction was tendered in 1905 and likely completed around 1906-1907.

The church was closed in 1995. The Anneessens organ was moved to the St. Liduinakerk, now St. Adelbertuskerk, also in Haarlem-Noord. The neo-Gothic Maria and Sacred Heart altar, main altar, and the former St. Vincentius altar were moved to the Sint-Vincentiuskerk in Volendam in 1997. Around 2001, the former church building was converted into a complex with apartments and office spaces, retaining many original details such as high vaulted ceilings and stained glass windows.

name: Elimkerk
description: The Elimkerk in Amersfoort is a church building of the Reformed Congregation, located at Waterdaal 1. The brick hall church has a fan shape with ascending side gables and a high facade, but lacks a tower. Inside the facade, the organ is mounted, and below it is the pulpit with the lectern, and next to it the baptismal font, all in a sober, modern style. The rest of the interior is also simple, yet bright. The church was built in 1993 and designed by architect J. Valk from Soest. The monumental organ was manufactured in 1984 by B.A.G. Orgelmakers. The church is surrounded by a number of outbuildings, where various church and social activities take place.

name: Elimkerk
description:
The Elimkerk in 's-Gravenpolder is a church building used by the local Reformed congregation. The congregation was established in May 1924, and initially used a smaller church building from September 19, 1924.

As the congregation grew, a new and larger church was built, with the foundation stone laid on September 11, 1976. The architect was M. van Dijk. The church has been expanded in stages, including in 1991 and 2006. In 2006, the church was expanded by 400 seats and the number of side rooms increased. An old organ was expanded and put into use on June 22, 2007. The church is still in use by the congregation.

name: Elleboogkerk
description:
The Elleboogkerk is a neoclassic hall church located on the Langegracht in Amersfoort. The building is 33 meters high. Dating back to 1820, it was destroyed by fire on October 22, 2007, but has since been fully restored.

Since January 2024, both Kunsthal KAdE and Museum Flehite have been using this location for their programming. It serves as a meeting place for art and (urban) culture, also providing space for music and performances. The Elleboogkerk is now a unique exhibition space focusing on contemporary art, particularly large-scale installations.

name: Elthetokerk
description:
The Elthetokerk was a Reformed church building, located in the Indische Buurt in Amsterdam-Oost. In 1913, the community opened a neighborhood center on Javastraat. The church was built in 1929, designed by Cornelis Kruyswijk and inaugurated in the presence of Queen Wilhelmina. The building was closed and demolished in 1992.

The former church was built in the Amsterdam School style and was an important work by Cornelis Kruyswijk. The church had a rectangular shape, but the interior was radial, with the pews arranged in arcs facing the pulpit and organ. The church tower was attached to the side of the church on Insulindeweg. After demolition, the congregation returned to the center on Javastraat.

name: Emmakerk
description:
The Emmakerk, now known as Kerkelijk Centrum De Bron since a merger in 1999, is located in Amsterdam-Oost. It is dedicated to Emma of Waldeck-Pyrmont. The original plans for the church arose from the need for a closer place of worship for residents of Watergraafsmeer, who previously had to travel to Amsterdam or Diemen.

The church was built in 1937-38 based on a traditionalist design by architect Gijsbert Friedhoff, and included an accompanying bell tower and rectory. The main entrance is elevated and accessed by stairs, with three portals framed by stone blocks and arches, each containing a double wooden door. Above the portal are elongated stained-glass windows. In the 1990s, the building was renovated, and a ten-meter high glass wall designed by Jan Beutener was installed.

name: Emmauskerk
description: The Emmaüskerk in Utrecht was a Roman Catholic church, built in 1967 in the Overvecht district. It's an interesting modern church designed without a tower. However, it was closed in 1984 and sold to the Moroccan Islamic community for 2.5 million guilders. The church building was then converted into a mosque, now known as the Omar Al Farouk Mosque. In 1984, the Roman Catholic Emmaüs parish found a new home in the Johanneskerk. The Emmaüskerk was designed by architectural firm Kraayvanger from Rotterdam, particularly by architect J.P.I. Maas.

name: Emmaüskerk
description:
The Emmaüskerk is a church building in the Dutch city of Amersfoort, located on the Noordewierweg. It serves the members of the district congregation of the Protestant Church of Amersfoort in the Soesterkwartier.

The church was originally named Emmakerk and was taken into use on December 19, 1929. In 1997, its name was changed to Emmaüskerk to indicate that the Dutch Reformed Church and the Reformed Church were continuing together in this building.

The building, designed by Amersfoort architect G. van Hoogevest, is a brick structure under high gable roofs, featuring an attached square tower with a striking wooden spire covered by a gable roof and wooden sound holes underneath. The interior is vaulted by an almost parabolic wooden barrel vault. The organ dates back to 1875 and was built by Henry Willis & Sons for the Saint Michael's Church in Blackburn, England. It was placed in the Emmakerk in 1985.

name: Engelse Hervormde Kerk
description:
The English Reformed Church is located in the Begijnhof in Amsterdam and is one of the city's oldest buildings. The church building is home to an English-speaking congregation affiliated with the Church of Scotland and the Protestant Church in the Netherlands.

Originally a Roman Catholic chapel from the 14th century, it was used by beguines. In 1578, it became municipal property and the chapel was closed. In 1607, the church reopened for English-speaking Protestants. Services have been held in English almost continuously since then. The church has around 320 members of 30 nationalities and can seat 385 people. Since the late 1970s, the church has been an important venue for chamber music, hosting around 70 concerts a year.

name: Engelse kerk
description:
The English Church in Middelburg is a late Gothic chapel that was part of the Cellebroeders monastery. Built between 1471 and 1484, the chapel served as a place of worship for the English community from 1629 after the Reformation. In 1921, the English community was dissolved, and the church was transferred to the Dutch Reformed Church, retaining its name.

The church is a single-nave structure with a 3/8 choir closure. It is constructed of brick with natural stone accents around the pointed arch windows. Inside, it features a pulpit from the 17th century and a single-manual organ built in 1761. Today, the English Church serves as a multi-functional center for art, culture, and historical exhibitions.

name: Enserkerk
description:
The Enserkerk is the former Reformed Church located on the former island of Schokland. It was built in 1834, replacing an older church from 1717. In 1859, Schokland was evacuated, but the church was preserved. After the Noordoostpolder was reclaimed in 1942, the island became surrounded by land.

For a time, the church was used as a stable. From 1947, it housed the Schokland Museum. After hosting changing exhibitions until 1990, it was restored to its original state and is now used as an exhibition space and wedding location. The church contains an electronic Heyligers organ. Today, it stands as one of the oldest buildings in the Noordoostpolder.

name: Europalaankerk
description: The Europalaankerk in Heerenveen, designed by Jo Vegter, was built in 1967. Louis Le Roy noted that the church influenced the choice of materials and the shape of the garden in its immediate surroundings. According to him, the spatial forms of the church are continued in the spatial structure of the garden, with the church increasing in height towards the garden. The church was designed to connect visually with the garden. The Europalaankerk is also listed as one of the churches in Friesland.

name: Evangelisch-Lutherse Kerk
description: The Evangelisch-Lutherse Kerk in Ede is a church with a rich liturgical tradition and a strong emphasis on church music. Services focus on the Gospel. It is located at Beukenlaan 12, 6711 NH Ede. The church is part of the Protestant Church in the Netherlands, and the community has a members page on their website. The church is involved in projects that engage children and young people in important moments within the church year, like the 'Sing the year around' project, to involve them in the services.

name: Evangelisch-Lutherse Kerk
description: The Evangelisch-Lutherse Kerk in Arnhem was built around 1898, designed by architect A.R. Freem. It's a striking neo-Gothic church with a tower. The church is made of red brick. A small adjacent house for the caretaker was built in Neo-Renaissance style. The building used to be a place of worship for the Evangelical Lutheran community, after their previous church at the Korenmarkt became too small. In 2017, the last church service was held, and the building was sold to a project developer. The Evangelisch-Lutherse congregation now gathers in the Oud-Katholieke St. Willibrorduskerk. Currently, the former church functions as a restaurant.

name: Evangelisch-Lutherse kerk
description:
The Evangelisch-Lutherse Kerk in Leeuwarden, Friesland, is a church building dating back to 1681, though largely rebuilt in 1774 into a spacious hall church. The facade, renovated in 1888, features large arched windows and a memorial stone from 1774 with a rococo frame.

Inside, the church has a stucco vault. The pulpit was crafted in 1774 by Willem Groeneveld, and there's a funeral shield for Jonkheer Andreas Möller, who died in 1690. The organ, the third for the church, was initially built in 1712 by Arp Schnitger, replaced in 1800 by Albertus van Gruisen, and again in 1869 by L. van Dam en Zonen, incorporating parts from the Van Gruisen organ.

name: Faliezustersklooster
description:
The Faliezustersklooster, also known as Feilzustersklooster, formerly Convent Sint-Catharinadal or Sint-Catharina Bongart, is a former monastery in the center of Maastricht. The building is located on the Begijnenstraat on the edge of the Jekerkwartier.

The facade of the Faliezustersklooster is constructed of brick on a plinth of hard stone. Typical of the Maasland Renaissance style is the roofline with consoles. The window and door frames and the mullions of the windows are made of hard stone on the ground floor and marl on the first floor. The diagonally divided window shutters are painted red and white, lending the building extra charm. The east facade has a stepped gable and the west facade consists of timber framing. The adjacent monastery church was demolished around 1865.

name: Fenix
description:
The Fenix was a church in Leeuwarden, built in 1960 and designed by architect Wouter Ingwersen. The church was located in the Valeriuskwartier district and served as the second church building for the Reformed Parish of Leeuwarden-West.

The Reformed community intentionally built three churches in northern Leeuwarden with bird names. The Fenix ​​church building had a bell tower on the south facade and was renovated in 2002. In 2003, it received the Flentrop organ from the demolished Goede Herderkerk. The last service was held on May 20, 2012. The church was sold in 2016 and demolished in 2018. It also housed a stained glass window by Jan Murk de Vries.

name: Fonteinkerk
description:
The Fonteinkerk is a church building in Amersfoort, located on Robert Kochstraat. Construction began in February 1965, and it was put into use on August 24, 1966. The building, designed by architect David Zuiderhoek, is a brick structure featuring non-parallel walls and a striking sloping roof. Provisions were made for a church bell, but one was never installed.

In 1970, an organ built by K.B. Blank & Zoon was added. In 2012, the spaces of the former Leusderkerk were renovated under the guidance of architect Ulrike van Schagen, and the annex was renamed Huis van Zuid. The church is part of the Protestant Church of Amersfoort and serves as a meeting place and is also available for rent for concerts, lectures and meetings.

name: Foreestenhuis
description: The Remonstrant church is housed in the right-hand rooms of the Foreestenhuis. It features a mahogany pulpit with a backdrop, a copper lectern, and a stand for another copper lectern. The church also has an organ built by H. Knipscheer in 1865, which was modified and expanded in 1947 with a free pedal by D.A. Flentrop. The modifications and expansion from 1947 are not protected as part of the monument.

name: Franciscus van Assisikerk
description: The Franciscus van Assisikerk is a church building in Reijmerstok, located in the South Limburg municipality of Gulpen-Wittem, Netherlands. It is situated on the main street of the village. The church was built in 1922 with elements of expressionism, designed by architect Jos Wielders from Sittard. The building is constructed of brick in two shades and is placed transversely to the road, featuring a rectangular plan with rounded corners and covered by a gable roof with slates. On the street side, at the head end of the church, is the tower with the entrance. Between the street and the church is an access staircase to reach the higher church. The church is a national monument.

name: GGiN Opheusden
description: The church building of the Netherlands Reformed Congregations in Opheusden is located on Kerklaan. The building was constructed in 2000 and expanded in 2008/2009, designed by architectural firm Van Beijnum from Amerongen. This brick hall church has 2,850 seats, making it the second-largest church in the Netherlands based on seating capacity. The current minister is G.M. van Putten. The church also features an organ with 34 voices, built by BAG Orgelmakers in Enschede and put into use on July 12, 2002.

name: Galileakapel
description: The Galileakapel is a church located in Leeuwarden. Nearby attractions include the Fries Museum and Boomsma Beerenburg Distillery. It is situated close to the city center, approximately 450 meters from Nummer 100 - 2 apartments. The Oosterkade bus stop is also within walking distance.

name: Galileërkerk
description:
The Galileërkerk was a former church building in Leeuwarden, in the province of Friesland. It started as the chapel of the Franciscan monastery, "Galilea," founded in 1457 outside the city walls. In 1498, the monastery moved to Tweebaksmarkt. The chapel became a Reformed church in 1580 after the Reformation.

The Galileërkerk was demolished in 1940. Parts of the church were moved to other churches. The pulpit is now in Joure, the Van Dam organ is in Tholen, and some tombstones are in Minnertsga. Some building fragments are in the Fries Museum. The church also had a rich organ history with several dispositions over the years.

name: Garnizoenskerk
description:
The Garnizoenskerk in Bad Nieuweschans was built in 1751 and initially served the soldiers stationed there. The building was designed with a multi-functional character, with the attic used for ammunition and hay storage. The consistory, located behind the church, used to house two horse stables, with a staircase leading to the hayloft.

In the 19th century, these functions were discontinued, and the attic was removed, giving the church space a vault. Inside, the pulpit from the early 19th century stands out. The text boards originally hung in the Der Aa-kerk in Groningen. The church also has a special bench for soldiers who were arrested. The single-manual church organ was made in 1874 by Hermanus Knipscheer and was moved to Nieuweschans in 1925. The church was last restored in 2001 and now serves as a Protestant church and wedding location.

name: Garnizoenskerk
description:
The Garnizoenskerk of Oudeschans is a former garrison church built in 1626. It initially served the military stationed in Oudeschans. The church is a simple hall church. A notable feature is the integrated design of the church and parsonage, which were connected in 1772. Before that, the church was part of the Landhuys complex, where all military affairs were handled.

Inside, a painted illusion of an organ adorns a panel, concealing the tower clock mechanism. The church has a wooden vault resting on painted consoles. It also features a pulpit with carvings, a copper hourglass holder, and simple benches. The church is owned by the Stichting Oude Groninger Kerken and serves as a venue for concerts and a multi-functional center for the village.

name: Gasthuiskapel
description:
The Gasthuiskapel in Tholen, located at Kerkstraat 15, is currently used by the Reformed Congregation "Immanuël". The Gothic chapel, made of brick, is built lengthwise along the street. It features a gable roof with a flèche. The interior has a wooden barrel vault. The organ was built in 1975 by the Van Vulpen company.

The chapel's history dates back to 1312 when Ewout Pietersz van Gabriee founded a guesthouse. After a fire in 1452, the guesthouse was rebuilt, along with the chapel dedicated to Saint Lawrence. In 1577, the Reformation took place, and the guesthouse was used to store gunpowder. In 1631, a new guesthouse was opened, and the chapel served as a sick ward. In 1832, three houses were built in the chapel. The municipality of Tholen purchased the chapel in the 1960s. It was restored from 1973-1975 and has been rented to the Reformed Congregation "Immanuël" since 1975.

name: Gasthuiskerk
description:
The Gasthuiskerk in Middelburg was built in 1493-1494 as a chapel of the Sint Barbaragasthuis. After the Reformation, it was used by English merchants for 10 years. From 1798 to 1846, Roman Catholics worshiped in this church. Since 1846, the church building has been used by the Christian Reformed Church.

Until 1962, the church was less visible because houses were built against it on both the Lange Delft and the Nieuwstraat. These were demolished in that year, and the church was restored, acquiring its current appearance and the late medieval chapel became clearly visible. The windows were fitted with a bricked 'sugar baker's frame' infill. In the central style of the entrance door is a largely authentic 16th-century Madonna statue. The doors of the church are over 500 years old and are among the oldest doors in the Netherlands.

name: Gasthuiskerk
description:
The Gasthuiskerk in Doesburg is a monumental church building that started around 1340 as a "gasthuis" (a type of hospice or guest house). Over the years, it has been used as a church building by various religious groups. From 1790, the church was owned by the Lutherans, and since 2000, the Remonstrants have also been using the church.

The renovated church now functions as a modern venue with a diverse cultural program, including concerts, operas, exhibitions, poetry festivals, open stages, lectures, cultural excursions, and cabaret performances. It is also used for business meetings, such as congresses, workshops, meetings, weddings, funerals or memorial services. A new glass entrance with a reception desk, cloakroom and toilets was added. During all these adjustments, the old Gasthuiskerk was kept as visible as possible, both inside and outside.

name: Gasthuiskerk
description:
The Gasthuiskerk, also known as the Kleine Kerk (Little Church), is a Protestant church in Zierikzee with a rich history dating back to the 15th century. Originally a chapel built next to a hospice for poor strangers and the sick, it became property of the Walloon Reformed community in 1587 and later the Dutch Reformed Church.

In 1651, the church was expanded with a gallery. The facade was adorned in 1653 with Zierikzee's coat of arms. The interior features a pulpit from the 17th century and regents' benches. The church has undergone several restorations, most recently in 1992-1994. During the summer months, the church is open to the public.

name: Geboorte van de Heilige Johannes de Doper
description: The Geboorte van de Heilige Johannes de Doper (Birth of Saint John the Baptist) is a Roman Catholic church located in Montfoort, Netherlands. It is a designated national monument. The church's interior has a contemporary feel, but retains many authentic elements. A renovation in 2009 brought modernizations such as glass walls to reduce the church's size, and support functions were positioned within the building. The old sacristy was transformed into a secretariat, kitchen, and repro room. A new entrance hall, a living room, meeting rooms, and a documentation area were added inside. The building is a three-aisled hall church in Neo-Gothic style constructed with brick. It features hexagonal towers on a square base and intricate ribbed vaults.

name: Gedachteniskerk
description:
The Gedachteniskerk in Rhenen is a Roman Catholic parish church, constructed as a national memorial monument. Jules Kirchner designed the church, embodying the theme of "fall and rise, death and resurrection." Built in 1959, it commemorates war victims and those who sacrificed their lives for freedom during World War II.

The church features a low, horizontal memorial hall for remembrance and a vertical church space directed towards the heavens for worship. A nationwide "stone action" funded its construction in 1954. The building's central dome allows light to enter uniquely from all directions. It also has a Verschueren organ from 1959 known for its acoustics.

name: Geertekerk
description: The Geertekerk in Utrecht, dedicated to St. Gertrude of Nivelles, has a rich history. Constructed around 1255 in Romanesque style, it originally lacked a tower. The current tower was added soon after the initial construction. In the early 14th century, the church expanded with a choir and transepts. The side aisles were added later, with the original outer walls becoming the pillars visible today. The church acquired its present-day exterior in the 15th century, featuring doorways in the aisles and a sacristy. After the Reformation, it served various purposes including a Reformed church, stable, barracks, and warehouse. After restorations, it is now owned by the Remonstrant Community and hosts weekly Sunday services and other events due to its excellent acoustics and flexible space.

name: Geerteskerk
description: The Geerteskerk is a Protestant church in Kloetinge, Zeeland. Around 1100, a wooden chapel likely stood on the site, later replaced by a stone building. This building was expanded in phases into the current church. The side and main choirs date from the 13th century, showcasing Flemish Gothic brickwork. The nave, in its current form, dates from the end of the 15th century. Originally dedicated to Saint Gertrude, the church took its current form around 1525. The church tower, completed in 1494, was initially separate from the church but was connected to the nave in the 16th century.

name: Gelderhorst
description: Based on the provided search results, there's no specific mention of a church building within De Gelderhorst. De Gelderhorst is described as a center for elderly deaf people in the Netherlands, offering housing, care, and support while respecting Deaf culture and Dutch Sign Language. The buildings are designed with round shapes and ample daylight to facilitate communication. It appears the focus is on creating a supportive living environment for the deaf community, rather than providing religious facilities.

name: Georgiuskerk
description:
The Sint-Georgiuskerk in Bredevoort is a neo-Gothic church. It is a municipal monument designed by architect Alfred Tepe. The church was built in 1876.

Before this church was built, the Catholic residents of Bredevoort were no longer allowed to hold church services in the old Sint Joriskerk after the siege of Bredevoort and the introduction of the Reformation in 1597. For a long time, they used the German Kruiskapel, just across the border.

name: Georgiuskerk
description:
The Georgiuskerk is a Roman Catholic church in Terborg, Netherlands. A "waterstaatskerk" was erected on the site of the church in 1842. In 1877, a tower designed by Alfred Tepe was added. This tower consists of four sections with pointed arch windows and sound holes. The tower is crowned with an incorporated spire. The three-aisled nave was built in 1913 and 1914, designed by Jan Stuyt.

The church's patron saint is Joris, and it was consecrated on September 29 by the Archbishop of Utrecht, Henricus van de Wetering. Stained glass is incorporated into the windows of the side and rear facades. In 2018, the church was sold and transformed into an event space. A terrace with a view of the Paasberg has been constructed at the rear.

name: Gerardus Majellakerk
description:
The Gerardus Majellakerk is a former Roman Catholic church located in the Indische buurt in Amsterdam-Oost. It was built in 1925 and designed by Jan Stuyt, intended as the focal point of a Catholic complex that included housing, a monastery, and two schools. The church's design was inspired by Byzantine churches, particularly the Aya Sophia in Istanbul, which Stuyt had seen during a pilgrimage.

A key feature is its large twelve-sided crossing tower. A western tower was initially planned but never constructed. The church faced upkeep challenges, exacerbated by the departure of wealthier residents and secularization. In 1992, it was decommissioned and transferred to Stadsherstel Amsterdam, which converted it into rentable spaces. Since 2012, it has been home to the Nederlands Philharmonisch Orkest and the Nederlands Kamerorkest, with the central space transformed into a concert hall known as the NedPho-Koepel.

name: Gerardus Majellakerk
description: The Gerardus Majellakerk is a Roman Catholic parish church in Utrecht. The church building was designed by the architect H.W. Valk. The church is dedicated to Saint Gerardus Majella.

name: Gerardus Majellakerk
description:
The Gerardus Majellakerk, also known as Sint-Gerardus Majellakerk or Trouwlaankerk, is a Roman Catholic church in Tilburg, along the Wassenaerlaan. It's dedicated to Gerard Majella, who was canonized in 1904, and since 2012, it belongs to the parish De Goede Herder.

Designed by Joseph Cuypers and his son Pierre Cuypers Jr., the church was completed in 1923. The church has a basilica floor plan. Its walls are made of brick, and it features a wooden roof covered with red tiles. The nave measures 35.5 meters long and 16 meters wide. Lower side aisles flank the nave, separated by pillars supporting arches. The church also has a clergy house that was built at the same time. Since 1988, part of the nave has been used for meetings and as a chapel dedicated to Padre Pio.

name: Gereformeerde Gemeente
description:
The church building of the Gereformeerde Gemeenten in Colijnsplaat is a former church located on the Oost Havenstraat. It was built in 1931 as a small hall church in Neo-Romanesque style, designed by architect P. Huibrechtsche and has 200 seats.

In 1930, some members of the local Old Reformed Church decided to leave this church association due to a church legal matter. They decided to join the Reformed Church of Kortgene. A local congregation was founded in Colijnsplaat on July 20, 1931. Following this, it was decided to have their own church built.

However, it was taken out of service in 1989 and has since been used as a woodworking shop.

name: Gereformeerde Gemeente
description: The Gereformeerde Gemeenten church building in Kamperland is located on Veerweg. The original building dates back to 1960. It has been expanded twice, once in 1976 and again in 2015. In 1960, the new church building had 80 seats. In 1975, 35 seats were added. In 2015, the church building was expanded with two halls and some ancillary rooms, increasing the number of seats to 180 and a new entrance was added.

name: Gereformeerde Gemeente
description: The Gereformeerde Gemeenten church building in Kortgene, Netherlands, dates back to 1927, replacing a smaller church from 1914. In 1953, the building suffered severe damage due to the North Sea flood. It was also damaged in 2004 when it was set on fire. The church was restored after both incidents and has remained in use by the Reformed Congregation. The simple hall church was extensively rebuilt in 1954 due to damage during the flood, giving the church its current form. The organ, dating from around 1750, was restored in 1981 and cleaned in 2004 after the fire.

name: Gereformeerde Gemeente
description: The church of the Gereformeerde Gemeenten in Poortvliet is located at Zuidstraat 15. It is a simple brick building without a tower. The church was taken into use in 1930 by the Gereformeerde Gemeente, which was founded the year before. Initially, it had 157 seats. After a gallery was installed in 1951, the number increased to 212. Until 1950, a cantor supported the service, after which a chamber organ was placed on a small attic above the porch. In 1957, the organ was replaced by an organ built in 1929.

name: Gereformeerde Gemeente
description: The Gereformeerde Gemeenten church in Scherpenisse is located at Schoolstraat 4. The current church building dates from 1984. It was built next to the old church, which is still in use as an annex. The church has a gable roof with a roof turret. The church houses an organ built in 1931 by Valckx & Van Kouteren, originally from the Zuiderkerk in Groningen, which closed in 1983. In 2008, the organ was placed above the pulpit and a third keyboard was added.

name: Gereformeerde Gemeente
description:
The church of the Reformed Congregations in Sint-Annaland is located at Weststraat 25. It is a very sober building with a gable roof. Initially, a harmonium was used to accompany the singing. In 1956, a Spiering organ was installed. This was replaced in 1987 by an organ built by the company Fama & Raadgever.

Another church of the Reformed Congregations in the Netherlands is located at Tuinstraat 39a. It is a simple brick hall church under a gable roof. The old church was converted into a community hall. In 2020, the church building was expanded again.

name: Gereformeerde Gemeente
description: The Gereformeerde Gemeente church in Westkapelle, Zeeland, was inaugurated in 1949. It serves as the place of worship for the local congregation. The church was built to replace a previous building that was destroyed during the Second World War in 1944. In 1975 a meeting hall was added to the church and the interior was renovated in 2001. The local Reformed congregation was founded in 1921. The church has 260 seats.

name: Gereformeerde Gemeente in Nederland
description:
The Church of the Reformed Congregations in the Netherlands in Sint-Annaland is located on Tuinstraat 39a. The congregation originated around 1854, with early members primarily from the local Dutch Reformed Church. In 1907, it officially became a Reformed Congregation.

A separation occurred in 1953, and in 1960, this congregation joined the Reformed Congregations in the Netherlands. Due to continuous growth, a new church building was put into use in 2000. Services are held with psalms from Datheen. The church building itself is a modest brick structure with a saddle roof. Around 1960, a Pels organ was installed, which is still used in the new church. The church was expanded again in 2020.

name: Gereformeerde Kerk
description:
The Gereformeerde Kerk in Rottevalle is a church building located in the Dutch province of Friesland. The church that stands today was built in 1937, designed by T. van der Kooi from Drachten. This replaced an older church building from 1874.

In 1937, a complex consisting of a Reformed church, a parsonage and a garden wall was realized in Rottevalle. The church has a rectangular floor plan with two two-sided extensions at an oblique angle. The building is covered by a steep gable roof with matte black glazed Roman tiles. The facades are constructed of red, flamed bricks. The church is separated from the road by a garden wall.

name: Gereformeerde Kerk
description: The Gereformeerde Kerk in Andijk dates back to 1929 and was designed by architect Egbert Reitsma. Because of its size, the church is also called the "Reformed Cathedral". Since 1985, the church has been a national monument. The tower has elements of expressionism and Gothic style. Inside, there are depictions of trade, technology, agriculture and shipping. The church is located at Middenweg 4, 1619 BL Andijk.

name: Gereformeerde Kerk, gesloten in 1985
description:
The Gereformeerde Kerk in Zonnemaire is a former church building located at Dijk van Bommenede 26. It was originally a warehouse that was converted into a church in 1897. However, in 1982, the church was sold to a private owner. After serving as a diving guesthouse, it was ultimately converted into a residential space.

In 1920, an organ was commissioned from A.S.J. Dekker from Goes. This organ was dismantled on August 28, 1982, and after restoration, it was placed in the reformed church of Brouwershaven. On March 6, 1983, it was put back into use there.

name: Gereformeerde Kerk, gesloten in de jaren 90
description:
The Gereformeerde Kerk in Driewegen, also known as Eben-Haëzer, is a former church building located in the village of Driewegen. It was founded on November 10, 1907, by ministers K. van Anken and K. Oussoren. In 1912, a parsonage was built next to the church.

The building is a small hall church with notable decorative brickwork on the facade. In the late 1990s, the church was decommissioned when the congregation merged with the local Reformed church. The building was then sold to a private owner who established a garage there. Since 2021, it has been owned by MUSICO Reizen and serves as both an office and a concert space.

name: Gereformeerde kerk
description: The Gereformeerde Kerk in Venlo was a Reformed church building, located at Monseigneur Nolensplein 45 in Venlo. The church was built in 1911 and was the first Gereformeerde church building in Dutch Limburg. Tjeerd Kuipers was the architect. The church had a charming appearance with an octagonal tower to the left of the facade. It was decommissioned in 1968 and demolished in 1970. Before a new church building was put into use in 1974, the Reformed Church was a guest in the Joriskerk.

name: Gereformeerde kerk
description: The Gereformeerde Kerk, also known as Eben-Haëzer, was a church building in Arnemuiden, constructed in 1903 on Lionstraat. Due to its poor structural condition, a new church was built in 1966 and put into use in 1967. Consequently, the church on Lionstraat was demolished in 1968. In 1903, the old building was sold, and a new plot was purchased on Lionstraat, where a new stone hall church was built. The total costs amounted to 8028.36 guilders. Architect Huson from Vlissingen was assisted by the minister's son, Berend Boeyinga, who later became an architect. The church was inaugurated on Wednesday, December 2, 1903.

name: Gereformeerde kerk
description: The Gereformeerde Kerk in Sint-Laurens is a former church building located near the hamlet of Brigdamme. In 2019, the church was sold to a Messianic community. Originally, the Gereformeerde Kerk in Sint Laurens emerged as the 'Nederduitsche Gereformeerde Kerk (doleerende)' in 1889. Later, in 1924, a new church was built. The church's origin traces back to the burning of the church of Brigdamme in 1562, after which the inhabitants were added to the parish of Sint Laurens. A new building followed in 1644, constructed as a hall church in accordance with the Reformed tradition.

name: Gereformeerde kerk
description:
The Gereformeerde Kerk in Colijnsplaat, located on Beatrixstraat, is a former church building. It was originally built in 1870 but underwent significant renovations in 1967. The church was decommissioned in 2005 and has since been repurposed into a residential house.

Another church at Oost Havenstraat was a small hall church without a tower, built in neo-Romanesque style. It was designed by architect P. Huibrechtsche and opened on September 25, 1931, with a seating capacity of 200. Due to declining membership, the community was dissolved on June 18, 1989, and the building was sold. It has been used as a carpentry workshop since then.

name: Gereformeerde kerk
description: The Gereformeerde Kerk in Geersdijk is a former church building located in the Zeeland village of Geersdijk. The original church was built in 1864 for the Christian Secessionist Congregation. In 1958/59, a new church was built with a generous financial donation from the National Disaster Fund, opposite the Reformed Church. The foundation stone was laid in 1958, and the church was put into use in 1959. In the 1980s, a partnership was established with the Reformed Church. The last church service was held on June 23, 2013, and the church has been for sale for almost two years since then.

name: Gereformeerde kerk
description: The Gereformeerde Kerk, also known as De Uitkomst, is a former church building in Wissenkerke, located on Ooststraat. The building dates back to 1868. In 1981, it was sold to a music association and decommissioned for religious services. It is a simple hall church without a tower. Currently, the building serves as a cultural center and is used by the music association "De Uitkomst" and the Harmonievereniging Apollo. The church is not a monument.

name: Gereformeerde kerk
description:
The former Reformed Church in Anna Jacobapolder is a former church building located at Langeweg 40 in the municipality of Tholen. It was taken into use in 1895.

In 1960, the building was decommissioned and used as a storage place. Eventually, the building was converted into a living space. A new Reformed church was built in 1959 at Langeweg 51 to replace the 19th-century church building. In 1965, the tower of the old church building was demolished.

name: Gereformeerde kerk
description:
There are two church buildings mentioned. The former Reformed Church in Anna Jacobapolder, located at Langeweg 40, was originally built and put into use in 1895. However, it was taken out of service in 1960 and repurposed as a storage place. Later, the building was converted into a residential space.

The current Reformed Church is located at Langeweg 51. This building was put into use in 1960, replacing the older church building. The Reformed Church is the only church in the village of Anna Jacobapolder and is part of the Protestant Church in the Netherlands. The church has about 180 members and describes itself as a small, lively community with all ages represented, striving to be an open and welcoming church for the entire village.

name: Gereformeerde kerk
description: The Reformed Church in Veere is a former church building located on the Kaai in Veere. It was built in 1905 but was taken out of service in 1997. The church had an organ that was already present in the old church. In 1888 a pipe organ was put up for sale.

name: Gereformeerde kerk
description:
The Gereformeerde Kerk in Lioessens, located in the Dutch province of Friesland, is a Reformed church building. The T-shaped church with expressionistic elements was built in 1927 according to the plans of architect Ane Nauta. The first stone was laid on May 30, 1927.

A stone at the left side of the entrance has the text "Give the Lord the glory of His name". The organ was made in 1876 by Lodewijk Ypma and placed in the church in 1932. It originates from the Sint-Martinuskerk in Bolsward. The church is located on Doarpsstrjitte 16.

name: Gereformeerde kerk
description: The Gereformeerde Kerk in Appingedam, Netherlands, is a church building constructed in 1927 for the local Reformed Church. Designed by architect Egbert Reitsma, it is a hall church built in the Amsterdam School style. This is evident in its use of brickwork and decorative elements in the facades, with a rectangular layout wider than its predecessor.
