The church features a high parabolic ceiling, stained glass windows, and geometric ceiling paintings. The exterior is defined by purple-brown sintered bricks arranged in various bonding patterns. A church has stood on this site since 1852, with the current building inaugurated on December 1, 1927.

name: Goede Herderkerk
description:
The Goede Herderkerk was a church building located in the Dutch city of Leeuwarden, in the province of Friesland. The Reformed Goede Herder Kerk was commissioned by the Church Board of the Reformed Municipality of Leeuwarden. A.C. Nicola? was the architect in 1951, with A.J. Feddema as a collaborating architect in 1953 and 1954.

The octagonal church is comparable to the Maranathakerk in Eindhoven, which was built in the same period. The traditional cornice at the top of the facade is absent in Leeuwarden. The narrow, high pentagonal windows had larger proportions, which defined the facade. The church lost its function as a result of shrinking church attendance.

name: Goirkese kerk
description:
The Goirkese Church, or H. Dionysiuskerk, is a neo-Gothic church building located on Goirkestraat in Tilburg Oud-Noord. After the Heikese church, it is the oldest church in Tilburg and the first neo-Gothic water management church in the Netherlands. The oldest part of the church is the oldest Neo-Gothic Catholic church building in the Netherlands.

In 1715, a barn church stood on the site where the church is now. Catholics gathered here secretly because their religion was forbidden at the time. Although sober in appearance, this church has a relatively lavish interior. The church has an impressive interior, which was initially filled with pieces from the barn church, gradually grew into a true museum of ecclesiastical art.

name: Grauwzusterskapel
description: The former monastery chapel, built in a sober Baroque style, dates back to 1705. The rectangular chapel measures 13.5 x 5.5 meters and consists of five bays. The interior has been heavily modified and is currently used as a temporary exhibition space. Of the five windows on the south side, three have been bricked up. A sacristy was probably added on the east side in the 19th century. The entrance portal was added at the end of the 18th century. The keystone with the year 1705 probably comes from elsewhere. Various church furnishings have been preserved from the inventory.

name: Groenestraatkerk
description:
The Groenestraat Church, also known as the Heilige Antonius van Padua-Sint Annakerk, is located in the Hazenkamp neighborhood of Nijmegen. Built in 1909-1910, this Roman Catholic church was designed by Albert Margry in the Neo-Gothic style. The building is a three-aisled cruciform basilica constructed of brick.

The facade features two towers of unequal height, with the tallest reaching 56 meters. The church's choir contains stained glass windows made by Frans Nicolas & Zonen from Roermond. The Groenestraat Church is a national monument, as is the adjacent rectory, which was also designed by Margry. The church is dedicated to Saint Anthony of Padua.

name: Groenmarktkerk
description:
The Groenmarktkerk, formally the Sint-Antoniuskerk, is located on the Nieuwe Groenmarkt in Haarlem. Constructed in 1843 and 1844, it was until 2022, the second oldest Roman Catholic church in the city. The patron saint of the church is Antonius of Padua.

Designed by Flemish architect Tieleman Franciscus Suys, who also designed the Mozes en Aäronkerk in Amsterdam, the church's style is neoclassical with Baroque influences. The Ministry of Cults at the time required the church to accommodate 2000 people, which led to changes in the original design. The facade was widened with bare bricks, and a gallery was added inside, transforming the single-nave church into a three-nave structure. A second gallery was added in 1854.

name: Grote Kerk
description:
The Grote Kerk in Hoorn is a church located in the West Frisian city of Hoorn, in the province of North Holland, Netherlands. It is located on the Kerkplein, which surrounds the church. The church is a landmark in the Hoorn cityscape.

The symmetrically designed cruciform church, known as Grote Kerk, is constructed of brick with numerous decorative natural stone elements and covered with slate gable roofs. It was built between 1881 and 1883 in Neo-Renaissance style. The brick facades are richly decorated with masonry, interspersed with natural stone bands and blocks, as well as arched windows with stained glass.

name: Grote Kerk
description:
The Grote Kerk in Marken is a reformed church. It's a three-aisled pseudo-basilica which is a national monument. The church was built between 1903 and 1904, designed by A.H.L. Kups, though the design dates back to 1896.

The building has a saddle roof covered with slates and a tower at the entrance. Inside, the white plastered church space is divided by two rows of four cast-iron "Italian" columns. The central nave is covered by a barrel vault, and the lower side aisles have a flat ceiling per bay, separated by arches. The wooden pews and organ date from the time of construction; the organ has been moved to the gallery.

name: Grote Kerk
description:
The Grote Kerk in Veere is a large church that dominates the small city. Its construction began in 1332, with expansions in 1470, but it was never fully completed. Throughout its history, besides religious services, it has served various functions, including a military hospital and a workhouse. During the Walcheren inundation in 1944 and the 1953 flood, it even sheltered livestock.

Though its treasures and ornaments have disappeared over time, remnants of old gravestones can still be seen in the windows. Today, the church is a cultural venue hosting music, art, and theater events and offers an interactive experience showcasing Veere's history. Its tower is 52 meters high and can be climbed during the high season.

name: Grote Kerk
description:
The Grote Kerk, also known as Koninginnekerk, is a church building in Apeldoorn. The church has historical ties with Paleis het Loo and a visible rich, Royal past.

The Grote Kerk was built in 1892, designed by J. Verheul Dzn, after a fire destroyed the previous church in 1890. The current church was built on the foundations of the Waterstaatskerk of 1842. The church is owned by the PKN and is used every Sunday for church services. The interior was modernized in 1960, but later restored.

name: Grote Kerk
description:
The Grote Kerk, also known as the Sint-Maartenskerk or Sint-Werenfriduskerk, is a Dutch Reformed church in Elst, in the municipality of Overbetuwe. The church is built on an elevated site. Before the church, there was an open-air sanctuary of the Batavians in prehistoric times. In Roman times, two Roman temples stood there. The first Christian church was built in the 8th century.

The current church dates back to the late Middle Ages. Archaeological research has revealed that the church was built on the foundations of a Gallo-Roman temple. In the 15th century, the church was transformed into the Gothic church that exists today, and the tower was built. In September 1944, the church was largely destroyed during the Battle of Arnhem but was rebuilt after the war.

name: Grote Kerk
description:
The Grote Kerk in Harderwijk is a Gothic cruciform basilica, dating partially from the 14th and 15th centuries. Originally much larger, it was initially named the Onze-Lieve-Vrouwekerk and dedicated to Mary. Since the Reformation in 1578, it has been used for Protestant services.

In 1415, after the parish church of St. Nicholas burned down, a decision was made to enlarge a Mary chapel for use as a church. The 14th-century building obtained a new chancel with ambulatory, a transept, and a tower that exceeded the height of the St. Eusebius Church in Arnhem, making it the tallest in Gelderland. A large portion of the church was lost when the tower collapsed in 1797, destroying part of the nave. Subsequently, the remaining part of the nave was closed off with a new facade in a sober Louis XVI style, under the guidance of Teunis Wittenberg.

name: Grote Kerk
description: The Grote Kerk in Neede is a Protestant church. The original church was built around 1506, and in 1616 it came into the hands of the Protestants. Except for the tower, the church was demolished in 1846 and replaced by a "waterstaatskerk". In September 1945, the church burned down, presumably due to a short circuit. In the years that followed, the church was rebuilt, with the tower in its original state. The church was inaugurated in March 1949. The tower was designated as a national monument in 1966. The history of Neede runs parallel with that of the Grote Kerk. The Roman church was dedicated to St. Caecilia and belonged to the diocese of Munster. It came into reformed hands in 1616 through Prince Maurits.

name: Grote Kerk
description: The Grote Kerk, also known as Johannes de Doperkerk, is a three-aisled cruciform church located on the Markt in Wageningen. The first church on this site was built in Romanesque style after Wageningen received city rights in 1263. In the 15th century, the church was expanded with a north aisle in Gothic style, and in the 16th century, the rest of the church was renovated in the same style. The tower has a set of three bells, one of which dates back to 1542. The church has been renovated to have a multifunctional character and is used for various activities, including church services, concerts, exhibitions, and community gatherings.

name: Grote Kerk
description:
The Grote Kerk, or Onze-Lieve-Vrouwekerk (Church of Our Lady), is the most important monument in Breda. The church is built in the Brabantine Gothic style and has a tower that is 97 meters tall. Its plan is in the shape of a Latin Cross.

Construction began in 1410 with the choir. The Prinsenkapel, located north of the choir, serves as the mausoleum for the ancestors of the Dutch royal family. It houses the tomb of Engelbrecht II of Nassau and was built between 1520 and 1525 by Count Hendrik III of Nassau-Breda. The church has a rich history and is a national heritage site.

name: Grote Kerk
description:
The Grote Kerk in Enschede is located on the Oude Markt. The original church dates back to the Middle Ages but underwent thorough modifications in the 19th century. The nave of the church can accommodate 400 visitors. It is known as the living room of Enschede and is part of the Wilminktheater & Muziekcentrum Enschede, available for rent for events and parties.

The church has a rich history, with an initial construction as a small wooden church around the year 800. It was expanded in the thirteenth century with a stone building in Romanesque style. A major renovation took place in 1928, giving the exterior and interior their current form. Inside the Grote Kerk, you can find the Stadscarillon of 49 bells.

name: Grote kerk
description: The Grote Kerk, or St. Agatha Church, in Beverwijk is a late Gothic hall church and the oldest church in Beverwijk. Despite several renovations, the church has largely retained its medieval character. The first masonry church was destroyed in 1576 by Spanish troops. It was rebuilt between 1592 and 1648, resulting in the current three-aisled hall church. Parts of the walls and pillars of the destroyed church remain, as does the tower dating from 1475. The building is used by the Protestant community of Beverwijk. The interior features a pulpit, baptismal gate and benches, a choir screen, and several pews dating back to the 17th century.

name: Grote of Andreaskerk
description:
The Andreaskerk in Hattem, also known as the Grote Kerk, is the oldest church building in Hattem, Netherlands. The church is located in the city center and used by the Reformed Protestant community for church services, organ concerts, and other musical events.

The church has Romanesque origins dating back to around 1225. The tower has a brick core with tuff cladding, featuring Lombard bands. The church also houses an organ built by Jan Slegel, completed in 1677, which was restored in 1974, retaining its 16th-century carvings and painted shutters.

name: Grote of Jacobijnerkerk
description: The Grote of Jacobijnerkerk is the oldest and architecturally most significant church in Leeuwarden. Built between 1275 and 1310 in Gothic style, it was originally part of a Dominican monastery founded in 1245. The church has been a central meeting place for over seven centuries. Inside, a modern interior combines with age-old elements, including the graves of Frisian Nassaus in the choir, a 17th-century pulpit, and the famous Müller organ from 1724-1727. The church hosts conferences, concerts, symposia, meetings, lectures, and parties, providing a flexible space for various events.

name: Grote of Johannes de Doperkerk
description: The Grote Kerk, also known as the Johannes de Doperkerk (John the Baptist Church), is a Gothic pseudo-basilica located in Wijk bij Duurstede, Netherlands. Its construction began in the 14th century, and in 1366 it became a chapter church. In 1486, under Bishop David of Burgundy, the church was significantly expanded, and the construction of the tower started. However, only one section of the tower was completed. The new choir burned down in 1579 and was never rebuilt, resulting in a straight east wall. Since 1580, the church has been in Protestant hands. The interior features a pulpit from 1667 and a "Kiespenning" from 1619. The church has been a national monument since 1965.

name: Grote of Laurentiuskerk
description:
The Grote of Laurentiuskerk is a Protestant church in Varsseveld, Netherlands. Around 1150, Varsseveld separated from Zelhem as a parish. In 1245, the church became the property of the Bethlehem monastery and was dedicated to Saint Laurentius, hence the name Laurentiuskerk.

The church was largely destroyed by fire in 1723, except for the tower. However, the tower was damaged by lightning in 1793. Both the nave and the tower were rebuilt. The reformation in the Varsseveld area took place between 1580 and 1590. The name of the church was then changed to Grote Kerk, but the name Laurentius has always remained in popular usage, hence the name "Grote of Laurentiuskerk". The church is now suitable for concerts, performances, lectures, exhibitions and church services. A special aspect of the church are the stained glass windows, which were installed during the restoration from 1971 to 1978.

name: Grote of Lebuïnuskerk
description:
The Grote of Lebuïnuskerk, also known as the Great Church or St. Lebuinus Church, is the main church of Deventer. It is a Gothic hall church that was constructed between 1450 and 1525. The church was originally dedicated to the English missionary Lebuinus and was considered one of the most important churches in the Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Utrecht.

In 1580, Calvinists took control of the church, removing the interior decorations and renaming it the Great Church. Today, the church is owned by the Protestant Church in the Netherlands, while the tower is owned by the Municipality. The tower has a narrow spiral staircase with 220 steps that are open to the public at certain times.

name: Grote of Maria Magdalenakerk
description:
The Grote of Maria Magdalenakerk, dating back to 1423, is located in the center of Goes. The construction of the church in its current form began around 1470 with the choir. The church was intended to be a three-aisled hall church, but it became a basilica.

In 1618, a fire destroyed much of the church, and the nave was rebuilt in Gothic style between 1619 and 1621. A high roof turret with a carillon was built in the 17th century. The carillon has 47 bells. The interior is simple, like a regular Protestant church, with a pulpit from 1594 and a floor covered with tombstones. The stained-glass windows were installed in 1929 and 1930 after a restoration.

name: Grote of Martinikerk
description:
The Grote of Martinikerk in Doesburg is the main church of the Hanseatic city. It is also known as the Hervormde Kerk, Sint-Maartenskerk, and Sint-Martinuskerk. The church was constructed in the late Gothic style.

Inside the church, the main nave has wooden vaults, while the side aisles have stone net vaults and cylindrical pillars. The church also features a sacristy next to the southern side aisle near the choir.

The Grote of Martinikerk has a Walcker organ from 1916, which features four keyboards, 75 registers, and 5,415 pipes. Additionally, there is a Flentrop choir organ from 1953 and a cabinet organ built around 1805 by Freytag.

name: Grote of Onze-Lieve-Vrouwekerk
description: The Grote of Onze-Lieve-Vrouwekerk is a Protestant church in the city of Tholen, in the Netherlands. The late-Gothic church building, built in Brabantine Gothic style, is made of brick and covered with Gobertange stone. The oldest parts of the church date back to the 14th century. After being elevated to a collegiate church in 1404, the church experienced its greatest prosperity. The nearly 50-meter-high tower is visible from a great distance. Inside the church, wall paintings from around 1570 were found under a layer of whitewash during a restoration.

name: Grote of Sint-Barbarakerk
description:
The Grote of Sint-Barbarakerk is a Protestant Gothic cruciform basilica located on Grote Kerkstraat in Culemborg. The historic church building dates back to the early 14th century and has been expanded several times over the years. It burned down in 1654 and was rebuilt. From 1963 to 1968, it was restored under the supervision of Monumentenzorg.

The church has many interesting sights, including two historical organs, seven copper crowns, a sculpted pulpit, beautiful communion silver, a silver baptismal font, and a marble grave monument from 1745. The church tower contains a carillon with 47 bells.

name: Grote of Sint-Bavokerk
description:
The Grote or Sint-Bavokerk is a late-medieval church in Haarlem, situated on the Grote Markt. It was dedicated to Saint Bavo before the Reformation. Constructed between 1370 and 1520, this cruciform church stands in the city center and showcases Brabant Gothic architecture. A 78-meter-high wooden, lead-covered, late-Gothic crossing tower tops the intersection of the transept and nave.

Originally a Catholic church, it became the cathedral of the Haarlem diocese in 1559. However, in 1578, Protestants took control during the Reformation. The church contains the famous Müller organ from 1738 and gravestones of notable figures like Frans Hals.

name: Grote of Sint-Clemenskerk
description:
The Grote of Sint-Clemenskerk is a Protestant church in Steenwijk, Netherlands. Before the Reformation, it was dedicated to Pope Clement I. The church has a long construction history. Around 900, a wooden church stood on this site, later replaced by a building of tuff stone or framework.

The tower of the Grote or Sint-Clemenskerk, called "Steenwiekertoorn," is 86 meters high and the oldest structure in Steenwijk, built in the 15th century. The spire was added in 1914 after the tower was used as a water tower in 1907. Inside the church is an organ from 1860, built by Petrus van Oeckelen from Haren.

name: Grote of Sint-Gertrudiskerk
description:
The Grote of Sint-Gertrudiskerk in Workum is a late Gothic cruciform church, the largest of its kind in Friesland, featuring notably large windows. Construction of the current church began around 1480 with the choir and continued, with interruptions, until 1616. There are indications that the church was intended to extend to the tower but was cut short due to financial constraints.

Around 1580, the church transitioned to Protestant hands. Few Roman Catholic artifacts remain, save for the choir screen from 1569 and some stone carvings. Inside, the pulpit dates back to 1718. During a restoration between 1939-1951, remnants of an older, smaller building were found.

name: Grote of Sint-Gudulakerk
description:
The Grote of Sint-Gudulakerk, also known as the Hervormde Kerk, is a Protestant church in Lochem, Netherlands. A church has stood on this site since around 950, initially a wooden structure with a 12-meter tower.

The current church is a late-Gothic hall church located in the city center. It was built in the 12th century as a Roman Catholic church and is named after Saint Gudula. The church features a west tower and is constructed of brick in a Gothic style. Inside, there's an organ built in 1758, originally for a church in Alkmaar. The church also contains wall paintings of Saint Roch, Saint Christopher and Saint Sebastian.

name: Grote of Sint-Jacobskerk
description: The Grote of Sint-Jacobskerk is the main church of Vlissingen, located in the province of Zeeland, Netherlands. Its construction largely took shape in the early 16th century, following earlier expansions. The tower and the low choir possibly date back to 1328. In 1572, it was converted for Protestant worship. A large fire damaged the church in 1911, leaving only the stone shell and some pillars standing. It was rebuilt afterward, but many old interior pieces were lost. From 1953-1954, the church was repaired, fixing damage from the war and the 1953 flood. A full restoration took place in 1997-1998, and the interior was redecorated to make the church suitable for purposes beyond religious services.

name: Grote of Sint-Janskerk
description: The Grote of Sint-Janskerk in Linschoten, Netherlands, is originally a 13th-century Catholic church dedicated to John the Baptist. After the Reformation, it became a Protestant church. The current church dates back to the 13th century, when the chapel was rebuilt and expanded with a tower in the west. The upper part of the tower was built in the 15th century. In 1482, the church partially burned down during the Hook and Cod wars. In 1627, the church building, except for the tower, was plastered to hide the irregular brickwork. This plaster layer was removed during the restoration in 1974-1977. South of the church is a winding wall, probably built around 1770. Today, the church is used for Sunday services by the Protestant Church of the Netherlands (PKN) community.

name: Grote of Sint-Laurenskerk
description: The Grote or Sint-Laurenskerk in Alkmaar is a landmark, formerly Protestant church, now used for secular purposes. Also known as the Grote Kerk (Great Church), it is the largest church in North Holland, north of the North Sea Channel. The church is built in the Brabantine Gothic style. Inside, the church features soaring ceilings, striking stained glass windows, antique organs and many artworks. The building stands in the middle of the old town of Alkmaar. It is known as the city's crowning jewel and celebrated its 500th anniversary in 2018. Access to the church is free when no events are taking place.

name: Grote of Sint-Laurenskerk
description: The Grote of Sint-Laurenskerk in Weesp is a late Gothic cruciform church built between 1429 and 1462, on the site of a former Romanesque church. In 1577, it became a Protestant church. The church lost much of its original furniture during this transition, but the Gothic choir screen was preserved. The church tower, a remnant of the earlier Romanesque church, houses a carillon cast in 1671 by Pieter Hemony. The tower is 40 meters high, while the interior of the church building is 58 meters long and 22 meters high. The building is a national monument and is used by the Protestant Congregation of Weesp and Driemond.

name: Grote of Sint-Maartenskerk
description:
The Grote of Sint-Maartenskerk in Tiel is a late Gothic cruciform church, though it was never completed. It consists of a nave with a clock tower and a separate sexton's room. The clock tower is made of tuff, while the naves are constructed from brick. Inside, the church features a wooden barrel vault over the central aisle, supported by octagonal brick pillars. The side aisles have star vaults.

A baptismal chapel, built in 1554, includes cross-ribbed vaults on natural stone columns. Above this chapel is a library covered with a star vault. The church also contains a carillon installed in 1964, with one remaining bell named Salvator from the original ten bells of the 16th century. The church has been a landmark in Tiel for over a thousand years and is used for various events, including church services, exhibitions, and concerts. The municipality of Tiel owns the church since March 1, 2025 and is planning a restoration.

name: Grote of Sint-Maartenskerk
description:
The Grote of Sint-Maartenskerk in Zaltbommel is a large basilica, considered an important example of Lower Rhine Gothic architecture. It features a three-aisled nave and a single-aisled choir. The church has an 11th-century predecessor.

The three naves of the church are covered by net vaults. The lower area of the tower has a star vault, and the choir has ribbed vaults. The exterior is largely covered in tuff stone, except for the choir. Originally, the tower had a 100-meter-high spire, but it burned down after being struck by lightning in 1538. Today, it is a Protestant church.

name: Grote of Sint-Michaëlskerk
description:
The Grote of Sint-Michaëlskerk in Zwolle, also known as Academiehuis Grote Kerk Zwolle, is a gothic three-aisled church built between 1370 and 1452. It once had the tallest tower in the Netherlands, which collapsed in 1682 after several lightning strikes. Today, an octagonal consistory stands where the tower once was.

Inside, highlights include the 16th-century choir screen, the pulpit, the Schnitger organ, and the pews. Fragments of 15th-century frescoes, a fragment of the former Sacrament tower, and a tympanum with the old city coat of arms can also be found. The church now serves a new function in Zwolle, hosting exhibitions, concerts, theater, films, and expositions. It is a place where spirituality and culture come together.

name: Grote of Sint-Nicolaaskerk
description:
The Grote of Sint-Nicolaaskerk in Edam is the town's old city church and the largest hall church in the Netherlands. Its construction began in the first half of the 15th century. The church has a late-Gothic style. Around 1540, the church obtained its current size and is about 88 meters long and 35.5 meters wide.

A large fire in 1602 damaged the church, after which it was rebuilt. Most of the stained glass windows date from between 1606 and 1635. Another fire in 1699 damaged the tower, which was subsequently rebuilt to a lower height. The church contains a main organ made in 1663 and a cabinet organ from the mid-19th century.

name: Grote of Sint-Nicolaaskerk
description: The Grote of Sint-Nicolaaskerk is the main church of Monnickendam, Netherlands. This Gothic building is located on the edge of the old city center. Construction started after 1400, with the chancel completed by 1450, and the tower built between 1510 and 1550. It is a three-aisled church, with the roofs of the aisles resting on the outer walls and 24 pillars. The almost ten-meter-wide oak choir screen is a highlight. After the Reformation, the church was refurnished for Protestant worship. The church is open to the public during the summer months and is also available for rent for events like exhibitions, concerts, and weddings.

name: Grote of Sint-Nicolaaskerk
description:
The Grote of Sint-Nicolaaskerk in Elburg is a prominent medieval church that dominates the city's skyline. Its construction was authorized in 1397 by the bishop of Utrecht, Frederik van Blankenheim, and it was dedicated to Saint Nicholas, the patron saint of sailors and fishermen. The church was built in Gothic style. The tower, lacking a spire since a lightning strike in 1693, consists of a base and three sections with pointed arches.

Around 1580, the church came into Protestant hands, resulting in the addition of an oak choir screen and two choir stalls. A thorough restoration in the 20th century revealed special murals under layers of whitewash. The church features an organ built in 1825. During the summer, the church is open to visitors, and the tower can be climbed.

name: Grote of Sint-Nicolaaskerk
description:
The Grote of Sint-Nicolaaskerk in Eemnes, Utrecht, is a late Gothic structure dating back to the 15th century. It was built on a terp-like elevation near the Wakkerendijk. Originally dedicated to Saint Nicholas, the church's ship and chancel were constructed in the 15th century.

Inside, the church features wooden panels, an old pulpit made in 1604 in the style of the Dutch Renaissance, and a copper gate dating from 1649. The ceiling, which is adorned with wooden flowers, dates back to 1790. The consoles for the wall plates and the support beams are decorated with wood carvings. The church also has a tower that dates back to 1521.

name: Grote of Sint-Stephanuskerk
description: The Grote of Sint-Stephanuskerk is a late-Gothic hall church located on the Markt in Hasselt, Netherlands. It occupies a prominent place in the city. A church has stood in the middle of Hasselt since the 14th century. Inside the church, a 16th-century painting of Saint Christopher can be found.

name: Grote of Sint-Stevenskerk
description:
The Grote of Sint-Stevenskerk, usually called Stevenskerk, is the oldest and largest church in the center of Nijmegen. The church was built in the 13th century on a small hill. Its construction began around 1254, initially in late Romanesque style, with the lower part of the tower still reflecting this. In subsequent centuries, construction continued in the Gothic style. The church has a tower of 71 meters high.

In 1273, Albertus Magnus consecrated the church. The church was severely damaged by bombing in 1944, and the restoration took 25 years.

name: Grote- of Sint Catherinakerk
description:
The Grote Kerk, or St. Catharinakerk, in Nijkerk, Netherlands, was initially built in 1461. After a city fire, it was rebuilt in 1540. The church features a nave with two aisles and a chancel. The white tower, a later addition from 1776, replaced an older spire.

Inside, the church boasts an exceptional mid-18th-century organ adorned with Louis XV carvings. The organ was made in 1756 by M. van Deventer. The pulpit and baptismal font date back to 1789. The church also contains a carillon of 30 bells.

name: Grote- of Sint-Nicolaaskerk
description:
The Grote of Sint-Nicolaaskerk in Oosthuizen, also known as the Church of Oosthuizen, is a late Gothic cruciform church. Constructed between 1511 and 1518, it replaced an older building from 1476. The church features a modest roof turret.

Inside, there are twelve mourning shields commemorating François van Bredehoff and his family. A mausoleum for Van Bredehoff is also present. The rood screen dates from the Renaissance period, while the pulpit is from 1664, dating to the Baroque era. The church organ has parts dating back to the 16th century.

name: Gummarus en Pancratiuskerk
description:
The Gummarus and Pancratius Church is a single-aisled, neo-Gothic church building located on Breedstraat in Enkhuizen. Although the building itself is not a national monument, the communion bank, the pulpit crown, and the secretary organ inside the church are recognized as such.

The parish has roots in the two medieval Catholic parishes of Enkhuizen. After Enkhuizen joined the Prince of Orange in 1572, the parish churches were given to the Protestants, and Catholics had to leave. From 1633, Catholics used a warehouse on Breedstraat as a church, dedicated to Saint Gummarus. Around 1652, a second parish church was founded on Venedie, dedicated to Saint Pancratius. In 1781, the latter was closed and merged with the one on Breedstraat, after which the church was dedicated to both Saints Gummarus and Pancratius.

name: H. Johannes de Doper en H. Bernarduskerk
description:
The H. Johannes de Doper en H. Bernarduskerk is a Roman Catholic church building on the Oranje Nassaulaan in the Hoograven district of Utrecht. The church is dedicated to Saints John the Baptist and Bernard of Clairvaux. This small church was built to replace two larger parish churches, the Johannes de Doperkerk and the Sint-Bernarduskerk.

In 1941, an emergency church was built for Catholics in Hoograven on Detmoldstraat, dedicated to John the Baptist. Due to ongoing population growth, one church was not enough, and in 1962 the Sint-Bernarduskerk was added on Camminghaplantsoen. Due to the secularization that started shortly thereafter, two church buildings proved to be too many for one district. After the church was put into use in 1992, the two other churches were demolished.

name: H. Kruisverheffingskerk met losstaande oude toren
description:
The Heilige-Kruisverheffingskerk is a church building with a separate tower in Cadier en Keer, in the municipality of Eijsden-Margraten. The church marks the central square and is centrally located in the old village. It is located on the Kerkstraat.

The church is not a national monument, but the tower is. The church is dedicated to the Holy Cross. The church has a transept arm, which was originally intended as a children's chapel, but is now used as a day chapel. The current church was built in 1957, with the first stone laid on October 27, 1957, and put into use on July 13, 1958.

name: H. Maria Geboortekerk
description: The H. Maria Geboortekerk is a Roman Catholic church in Losser, in the Overijssel region of the Netherlands. Located on the northwest side of the center, the church was built in a neo-Gothic style between 1901 and 1902, designed by Alfred Tepe. The design shares similarities with a hall church. A presbytery, constructed in 1904 by the same architect, is connected to the south side of the church via a low intermediate section. To the west of the complex lies the Catholic cemetery. Both the church and the presbytery have been designated as municipal monuments since 2008. The church has been in continuous use since 1903.

name: H. Maria Hemelvaartkerk
description:
The Heilige Maria Hemelvaartkerk (Church of the Assumption of Mary) in Bavel is a neo-Gothic cruciform church located on Kerkstraat. It features a church tower with a spire and a mechanical clock from 1888. The church was constructed between 1885 and 1887 and has a perimeter of approximately 200 meters.

Inside the church, there was once a stained glass window of Brigida and a Brigida altar made in 1891; the altar was replaced around 1975 with a simpler, newer altar. The church's design, by J.J. van Langelaar, a student of Pierre Cuypers, is inspired by mature French Gothic architecture. The church is built with Dutch brick and decorated with natural stone bands.

name: H. Pastoor van Arskerk
description:
The Pastoor van Arskerk is a modern Roman Catholic church located in the Loosduinen district of The Hague. Situated in the Waldeck neighborhood, its design is influenced by structuralism and brutalism. Dedicated to the French saint Johannes Maria Vianney, the church's construction began in 1968, and it was consecrated in December 1969.

The building is constructed from gray concrete blocks and lacks a tower. The interior is simple, and the design incorporates circles in various places, such as the entrances and skylights. The church is known for its spatial variation, differences in height, and play of light. The building's innovative layout has influenced church construction in the Netherlands.

name: H.H. Barbara en Antoniuskerk
description: The H.H. Barbara en Antoniuskerk in Culemborg is a parish of the Old Catholic Church of the Netherlands. It is located at the Varkensmarkt and is dedicated to Barbara, the patron saint of Culemborg, and Antonius the Great. The church is a national monument with a typical 17th-century Dutch religious architecture.

name: H.H. Engelbewaarderskerk
description:
The H.H. Engelbewaarderskerk is a former Roman Catholic church in Hoorn, officially founded on April 15, 1958, to relieve the crowded H.H. Cyriacus and Franciscuskerk. The rectangular hall church features a sculpturally designed bell tower above the main entrance. A colorful stained-glass window depicting a guardian angel is located on the left wall of the presbytery.

Since 2011, the church has not been used for religious services. It now serves as a funeral center. On May 12, 2023, a fire broke out in the bell tower, causing smoke damage. The building is listed as a municipal monument.

name: H.H. Lambertus en Genovevakerk
description:
The H.H. Lambertus en Genovevakerk is an old church located on a hill in Holset, in the Dutch province of Limburg. It is a parish church dedicated to Saint Lambert of Maastricht and Saint Genevieve of Paris. The building is a national monument constructed using limestone from Vijlen.

The church may have originated as an early medieval hall church, extended and heightened in phases from the 12th century. The tower was completely rebuilt in 1736, and the church underwent thorough restoration in 1841-1842.

name: H.H. Nicolaas en Barbara
description:
Located in the center of Valkenburg, the parish church, dedicated to Saints Nicholas and Barbara, is built from marl. It is the oldest of the two churches in the center of Valkenburg. The church dates back to the 13th century, though it was much smaller then.

The church incorporates both Gothic and Romanesque architectural styles. It has been destroyed and rebuilt several times. Pierre Cuypers participated in its restoration. The church was first mentioned as a chapel in 1228 and became an independent church in 1281. The tower was added in the mid-13th century but not completed until around 1465.

name: H.H. Simon en Judaskerk
description:
The H.H. Simon and Judaskerk is a Roman Catholic church located in the town of Ootmarsum, in the municipality of Dinkelland. It is dedicated to the apostles Simon and Judas Thaddeus. The church stands as the only example of Westphalian Romanesque Gothic architecture in the Netherlands. Typologically, it is a remarkable building, combining features of a hall church and a pseudo-basilica.

The church was built in different periods. Most of it, including the nave and western transept, dates back to the 13th century. The style of these parts is similar to that of some churches in Westphalia, with a great resemblance to the church of Legden. The nave's floor plan is based on the bound system. The central nave has two bays, while the side aisles have four.

name: Hasseltse kerk
description:
The Hasseltse Kerk, dedicated to Our Lady of the Rosary, is a neo-Gothic church located in the former hamlet of Hasselt in Tilburg Oud-Noord. Consecrated in 1898, it was designed by architect Hubert de Beer. The church has a large neo-Gothic style, with two staircase towers on the facade and a high crossing tower. In 1998, the last service was held.

Since 2005, the building has been used as a neighborhood center called De Poorten. During the renovation into a multicultural center, a fire broke out in 2003, destroying the roof and tower. The former church was restored, and a new steel tower was added. Several interior pieces, like the main altar and pews, were moved to another church.

name: Heikese kerk
description:
The Sint-Dionysiuskerk, commonly known as the Heikese kerk, is a Catholic church in Tilburg dedicated to Saint Dionysius of Paris. It is Tilburg's oldest church. The original church was destroyed by fire in 1595 during the Eighty Years' War and rebuilt in 1619. In 1648, the church was taken over by Protestants, and Catholics used a border church in Steenvoort.

The current church, built in Waterstaats style between 1827 and 1829, features a nave with three equally high vaulted aisles and a three-sided closed choir. In 1895, it was modified in Neo-Gothic style and expanded with two chapels on the west side. Attached is a 15th-century tower from a previous church. The interior includes a marble high altar from the 18th century and a pulpit in Waterstaats style.

name: Heilig Hart kerk of Paterskerk of Augustijnenkerk
description:
The Augustijnenkerk, also known as Paterskerk and R.K. Heilig Hartkerk, is a church building located on Tramstraat 37 in Eindhoven. It was built at the end of the 19th century for the Augustinian fathers of the adjacent Mariënhage Monastery. The church was their property until December 2017 and is now owned by DELA.

The church features a 66-meter high hexagonal tower, topped by a statue of the Sacred Heart of Jesus. Above the church door are statues of the patron saints of the Order of Augustinians: Augustine, his mother Monica, and Nicholas of Tolentino. The interior features clean brickwork. The stained glass windows in the transept facades are by Daan Wildschut and Charles Eyck. The furnishings are Neo-Gothic, partly by Jan Custers.

name: Heilig Hart van Jezuskerk
description:
The Koepelkerk, officially the Heilig Hart van Jezuskerk (Sacred Heart of Jesus Church), is a monumental church in Maastricht. It is located near the Maastricht railway station. The church has served as a Roman Catholic parish church since its construction, and since 2021, it also houses an Eritrean Orthodox community.

The church was built between 1921 and 1923, with expansions in 1929 and 1953. The architects were Alphons Boosten and Jos Ritzen. The design incorporates a prominent dome and is considered an example of expressionist architecture. The interior features a marble altar and stained-glass windows. The church has been designated as a national monument since 1997.

name: Heilig Hart van Jezuskerk
description:
The Heilig Hart van Jezuskerk, located in the Op de Heide district of Tegelen, Venlo, is a former church. Built in 1931-32, it's a large three-aisled church with a pentagonal choir and a simple, adjacent tower. The church was designed in an expressionistic style by Caspar Franssen and his son Joseph.

The building features a chapel dedicated to Our Lady of the Heath, adorned with murals by René Smeets from 1946. In 1943, a two-manual organ was installed. The last service was held on September 9, 2011. Since 2020, the building has been repurposed into a sports center. The church has the status of a municipal monument.

name: Heilig Hart van Jezuskerk
description:
The Heilig Hart van Jezuskerk is a church building in Haanrade, in the municipality of Kerkrade, in the Dutch province of Limburg. The church is located on the Meuserstraat. In front of the church, there is a Sacred Heart statue and a Lourdes grotto. About 100 meters northwest of the church, there is a cemetery with a second Sacred Heart statue.

The non-oriented church building in Neo-Romanesque style is a cruciform church and consists of a narthex with a three-section tower and a tent roof on the north side, a three-aisled basilica-style nave with four bays, a transept, and a choir with a bay, gable, and pentagonal apse. The central nave, transept arms, and choir have a gable roof, and the side aisles have a lean-to roof. The facade has an arcade of three round arches, and the rest of the building has round-arched windows. The church has no buttresses. The building is constructed using Kunrader stone, marlstone, and bluestone. The church was built in 1931, designed by Caspar Franssen and Joseph Franssen from Roermond. It has been a national monument since 2001.

name: Heilig Hart van Jezuskerk
description:
The Heilig Hart van Jezuskerk is a parish church located in the Dutch city of Roermond. It was designed by Caspar Franssen and Joseph Franssen and built in 1923. The church is located in the residential area of Roermondse Veld, between the city center and Maasniel, and was built for the residents of one of the first systematic expansion districts.

The building is a brick structure in a traditionalist style, leaning strongly towards Neo-Gothic. It is a complex structure. The central space is covered by an octagonal dome with a lantern on top. This is flanked by four square turrets with another octagonal section on top. The facade is also flanked by two octagonal stair towers. The facade has three pointed arched entrance doors.

name: Heilig Hart van Jezuskerk
description:
The Heilig Hart van Jezuskerk (Sacred Heart of Jesus Church) is a Roman Catholic church in Rothem, in the Dutch South Limburg municipality of Meerssen. Built in 1929 by architect Jos Wielders, it has been a national monument since 1997.

The church is situated on a square and forms an ensemble with the former rectory at the rear and the former chaplain's residence to the left. The building, in an expressionistic style from 1928-29, is constructed of yellow and red brick and consists of a church tower, a nave with narrow side aisles, a narrow higher choir, and a low apse. The interior is mostly authentic and partly designed by Wielders. The church has both rectangular steel windows and large pointed arch windows.

name: Heilig Hartkerk
description: The Heilig Hart Church in Venlo is a monumental Roman Catholic church prominently located on the axis of the Straelseweg, forming a visual connection from the city center. In front of the church is a roundabout where the Veldenseweg and Straelseweg split. The Federatie Parochies VenloStad and Venterra are transforming the church area into a residential area called Residentie Heilig Hart, with the design by Verheijen-Smeets Architecten. The plan includes demolishing former parsonages on Paulus Potterstraat to construct a small-scale residential complex with apartments. The church itself will house luxury apartments, while preserving the building's characteristic elements. A communal meeting space will be created under the central dome, and the surrounding area will be landscaped with greenery.

name: Heilig Hartkerk
description: The former Roman Catholic Heilig Hartkerk in Utrecht East, in the Oudwijk neighborhood, was built from 1927 to 1929, designed by architect Jos Duynstee in the Amsterdam School style. The church was consecrated on May 23, 1929. It remains a prominent monument in Utrecht East, featuring a high tower with a clock. The clock is a clear characteristic of the Amsterdam School, with its brickwork and soft green tiles behind the clock face. In the late 1990s, the church was converted into a residential complex with 23 apartments.

name: Heilig Hartkerk
description:
The Heilig Hartkerk (Sacred Heart Church) is the parish church of Altweerterheide, located at Bocholterweg 112 in the municipality of Weert. The three-aisled brick building exemplifies brick expressionism. A striking feature is the square tower attached to the choir, covered with a tent roof and adorned with an Art Deco Sacred Heart image embedded in one corner.

The church's construction in 1935-1936 was prompted by the growing population of Altweerterheide in the early 20th century and a corresponding need for a larger church building. Jos Cuypers and Pierre Cuypers Jr. designed the church as a replacement for a temporary church built in 1925. The church's bell dates back to 1936, and in 1937, the chaplaincy was elevated to a parish.

name: Heilig Hartkerk
description: The Heilig Hartkerk (Sacred Heart Church) in Maarssen is a Roman Catholic church located at Breedstraat 3. It was designed by Alfred Tepe and consecrated on September 9, 1885. The church is a Neogothic cruciform basilica with three-sided closed transept arms and flying buttresses. The church tower has angled buttresses and three niches with limestone tracery in each section. Inside the church, there are cross-ribbed vaults and stellar vaults. The church features artworks by renowned ecclesiastical artists, including the sculptor Friedrich Wilhelm Mengelberg, the silversmith Gerard Brom and his sons, and the glazier Geuer. The church is a national monument.

name: Heilig Kruiskerk
description:
The Heilig Kruiskerk in Amersfoort is a former Roman Catholic church located in the Kruiskamp district. In 2022, a Baptist community started using the church. The church was consecrated to the Holy Cross during the Roman Catholic period.

The architect, Herman J. van Wissen, had already completed several projects in new housing estates and was given the opportunity to design a church in the same modern style. Construction began in 1956, and the church was consecrated in 1958 by the then Bishop of Utrecht, Bernardus Alfrink. It is considered an architecturally significant reconstruction church, featuring a detached bell tower and many interesting details. The trapezoidal floor plan was innovative in post-war Catholic church construction in the Netherlands.

name: Heilig Sacrament
description:
The Sacramentskerk is a church building located on the Kometensingel in Tuindorp Oostzaan in Amsterdam-Noord. It was built in 1952 as a Roman Catholic church. The church is an example of the Bossche School style, designed by architects Evers and Sarlemijn. The building's main form, use of materials, and detailing of the interior and exterior are virtually intact.

The church replaced an earlier wooden emergency church from 1924. Originally, there was an older organ with a neo-Gothic case on the gallery above the entrance. During a renovation in 1980, the church space was reduced, and the organ disappeared. In 2008, the church was decommissioned, and the church hall was largely dismantled. The building remained in use for neighborhood activities. After a long period of demolition plans, the Sacramentskerk obtained the status of a municipal monument in 2015.

name: Heilig-Hart-van-Jezuskerk
description: The Heilig Hart van Jezuskerk (Sacred Heart of Jesus Church) is a Roman Catholic parish church in the Dutch city of Maastricht, located in the Oud-Caberg neighborhood. The church has a traditional design and is a municipal monument. The church's location is on the edge of Maastricht, near the border with Smeermaas, and is situated slightly higher than the road. To the right of the church is a large parking lot. The church was built in 1876-77, the tower dates from 1900 and the choir received its current form in 1936-37.

name: Heilig-Hartkerk
description:
The Heilig Hartkerk in Haarlem is a former Roman Catholic church. This neo-Gothic hall church with a transept was built in 1902 by architect Peter Bekkers. The church features a pointed gable on each bay, octagonal stair towers next to the facade, a polygonal closed choir, and side chapels. Inside, it has square pillars with colonnettes and ribbed vaults.

In 1980, the building became a national monument. In 1996, the church was redeveloped into apartments. A project developer created 61 apartments within the church structure, ensuring that the exterior remained largely unchanged, and original elements like the stained-glass windows were preserved. The renovation won the "Nationale Restauratieprijs" in 1999 for its reversible installation, which allows for the apartments to be removed and the church restored to its original state if needed.

name: Heilig-Kruiskapel
description:
The Heilig Kruiskapel in Utrecht was a small chapel situated on what is now Domplein, nestled between the Dom Church's missing nave and the vanished Sint-Salvator Church. It was an oriented chapel, less than twenty meters long, originally consisting of a rectangular hall, a slightly constricted, straight-closed choir, and two transepts connected to the nave. In the early 19th century, meals were prepared and distributed to the poor there, giving the church the name Soepkapel (Soup Chapel). The chapel was demolished in 1829.

In 1423, the chapel was rebuilt in Gothic style, during which the southern transept was likely demolished. The outlines of the former chapel are indicated in the paving of Domplein.

name: Heilige Annakerk
description: The Heilige Annakerk in Hintham is a parish church built in 1909-1910 by architect W.Th. van Aalst in Neo-Gothic style. It is a replica of the church in Aillant-sur-Tholon, France, designed by Viollet-le-Duc. The church is a three-aisled cruciform basilica with a tower on the west side featuring an octagonal spire. The tower and roofs are covered with slate tiles. The interior has been restored and simplified over the years, with a modernised entrance and singer's gallery. The church includes stained glass windows in the left transept chapels.

name: Heilige Caeciliakerk
description:
The Sint-Ceciliakerk, also known as Sint-Caeciliakerk, is a church building in Veldhoven, in the Dutch province of Noord-Brabant. Located on Dorpstraat in Veldhoven Dorp, the church is a national monument dedicated to Saint Cecilia.

A water management church was built in 1834. The outlines of this church are marked in the pavement in the square in front of the current church. The current Caeciliakerk was built to replace a nineteenth-century water management church that had become too small. In 1913-1914, the new, neo-Gothic church was built, designed by architect Wolter te Riele. Over the years, especially after 1950, the church has been renovated and redecorated several times.

name: Heilige Familiekerk
description:
The Heilige Familiekerk was a Roman Catholic church in Maastricht, located on Old Hickoryplein in the Wyckerpoort neighborhood. It was built between 1959 and 1961, designed by Theo Boosten. The church was an example of a building that consciously sought new forms, designed to provide a fitting closure to the south side of the large rectangular square.

It was a hall church on a rectangular plan, consisting of various, mostly symmetrical parts, which were placed asymmetrically. The brick building was spanned with a steel structure. A striking feature was the three, actually five-sided entrance portal. The church was closed in 1997 due to a decline in churchgoers and demolished in 1999.

name: Heilige Familiekerk
description: The Heilige Familiekerk, located in 't Kruis in the Dutch municipality of Heerhugowaard, is a Roman Catholic church. Together with the adjacent parsonage, it forms a municipal monument. This striking white church was built between 1922 and 1923 by a local contractor, Bot. The original Neo-Gothic design was by J.F. Klomp from The Hague, but the church later underwent significant renovations, giving the pointed arch windows an almost Art Deco-like appearance. Only the choir at the rear still exhibits Neo-Gothic elements. The church features a modern entrance portal and an open bell cage above it, housing two bells named Aagje and Adriaan after the parishioners who donated them. The church interior was thoroughly restored in 1988, and various other changes have been made to the whitewashed church since then.

name: Heilige Geestkapel
description: The Waag in Alkmaar was originally built in the 14th century as a chapel for the adjacent Holy Spirit Hospital. This hospital provided free accommodation for poor travelers for three days and nights, and also cared for the sick. In 1566, the Bishop of Haarlem permitted the hospital to repurpose the building for weighing purposes. By 1582, the weighing activities were moved to the larger Holy Spirit Chapel, which was no longer used for religious services. The conversion of the chapel into a weighing house was completed in 1583. Today, the Waag houses the Dutch Cheese Museum and a tourist information office. The tower has a carillon played weekly and an automatic display with horses, knights and a trumpet player.

name: Heilige Geestkerk
description:
The Holy Spirit Church in Venlo is a Roman Catholic church building. The church was built in 1963 and consecrated the following year. It is a modern building with a striking concrete structure.

The church has a rectangular floor plan and is characterized by its high, narrow windows, which provide plenty of natural light. The interior is simple and functional, with a focus on the altar and the liturgical space. The Holy Spirit Church is not a monumental building.

The church has stained glass windows and a bell tower.

name: Heilige Geestkerk
description: The Heilige Geestkerk (Holy Spirit Church) in Heerenveen is a Roman Catholic parish church. The current church, the fourth one, was built in the center around 1933. It was designed by architect H.C.M. van Beers in a traditionalist style. The three-aisled church features a crossing tower with a small spire and a tower with a high spire containing three bells. The connected baptistery also has a spire. The pulpit comes from the studio of the sculptor Friedrich Wilhelm Mengelberg. The organ was made in 1867 by Adema. The church is a national monument.

name: Heilige Geestkerk
description:
The Heilige Geestkerk in Roermond is a former church building located on the Minderbroedersingel. Since 2011, it has housed a healthcare center. The church is a round central building, also known as a "domed church," with a protruding portal, an apse at the rear, and a high dome with a lantern.

Frits P.J. Peutz designed the church, and the first stone was laid on May 21, 1956. It was consecrated on June 6, 1957. The building features a concrete skeleton clad in marl. A modest openwork bell tower stands to the right of the main entrance. The church hall was reduced in size in 1994, and a restoration and renovation took place in 1995-1996. The last Holy Mass was held on Saturday, February 20, 2010. The organ is still located in the former church, above the entrance. In 2000, the church was designated as a municipal monument.

name: Heilige Lambertuskerk
description: The Sint-Lambertuskerk, now known as Christus Koningkerk, is located in Meerveldhoven in the municipality of Veldhoven. The large, three-aisled church was rebuilt with a tower. Within the church is the chapel of Onze-Lieve-Vrouwe ter Eik. The church is dedicated to Saint Lambertus. While the rebuilt church itself, constructed in 1952, is not a Rijksmonument, certain parts of the interior are, particularly the historic right side aisle. In 2015, the church's name was changed to Christus Koningkerk, becoming the main church of the merged parish of Christus Koning.

name: Heilige Maria Magdalenakerk
description:
The Maria Magdalenakerk in Zaandam is a former Old Catholic church building, located in the center of the city. It's designed as a "barn church". In 1695 this building was constructed during a time when non-Calvinist religious houses were only grudgingly allowed. The church was also used as a Remonstrant church for some time.

Inside the church, there are several statues, including those of Willibrord and Bonifatius placed on the tabernacle. The furniture, altar with paintings, candlesticks, pulpit, and other elements are all made in the Baroque style. The organ, dating back to 1714, was originally from a hidden church on Keizerstraat in Amsterdam and was installed in Zaandam in 1809. The church is now used by the Basisgemeente Ecclesia once every three weeks.

name: Heilige Nicolaaskerk
description: The Heilige Nicolaaskerk (St. Nicholas Church) in Baarn is a municipal monument named after Saint Nicholas of Myra. Since 2011, the building and its religious community have been part of the Roman Catholic parish of Saints Martha and Mary. The church replaced a Neo-Gothic church from 1861 and was consecrated in 1905. It is a three-aisled Neo-Gothic hall church without a transept. The tower to the right of the facade is unfinished, and there is a staircase tower to the left of the facade. The church has beautiful stained glass windows in the choir, made by the F. Nicolas & Zn studio in 1906. The exterior and interior were restored in three phases in the 2000s and 2010s.

name: Heilige Stede
description:
The Heilige Stede, or Nieuwezijds Kapel, is a Dutch Reformed church in Amsterdam built in 1908. It stands on the site of a former 15th-century church, which itself replaced a chapel destroyed in a city fire in 1452. The original chapel was built in 1347 to commemorate the Miracle of Amsterdam.

In 1566, the chapel suffered damage during the Beeldenstorm and later became a Protestant church named Nieuwezijds Chapel. In 1908, the Protestant church fathers had the building deconstructed to consolidate space and generate income by selling the surrounding land. Today, the church is hidden behind a wall of shops. Since 2006, the former church houses the Amsterdam Dungeon, a horror theme park.

name: Heilige-Familiekerk
description:
The Heilige-Familiekerk (Holy Family Church) in Venlo was built in 1939, designed by the architects A.J. Kropholler and F.H. Stoks in the traditionalist style. The church features a high and wide central nave with narrow, lower side aisles. A tower is integrated into the front of the church.

The building materials used are brick and natural stone, with pointed arch windows containing stained glass. Inside, the high central nave has a ceiling with large wooden beams resting on small corbels. Spanning between the central nave and side aisles are pointed arch openings supported by natural stone columns. In front of the church is a statue of Henri Belletable, founder of the Archconfraternity of the Holy Family.

name: Helige Maria Hemelvaartkerk
description: The Heilige Maria Hemelvaartkerk (Holy Mary Assumption Church) in Aardenburg was built in 1850 and consecrated in 1851. It was designed in early neo-Gothic style. The original structure still includes the nave and the tower. In 1924, the chancel was demolished, and the church was enlarged with a dome and a new chancel. The church has a special devotion to Our Lady of Aardenburg, also known as Our Lady with the Inkpot. The church is open daily for visitors between 9:00 and 17:00.

name: Helperkerk
description: The Helperkerk is a church building in late-eclectic style located in the city of Groningen. Situated on the Coendersweg in the southern district of Helpman, it was built in 1900 by order of the then Dutch Reformed Church. The building served as a replacement for a church established in 1875 on the Helperkerkstraat, the foundation stone of which is embedded in the Helperkerk. The inauguration took place on December 23, 1900. In 1938, the church was expanded by the Groningen architectural firm Nijhuis & Reker, extending and widening the building and adding association rooms and two apartments at the rear. The organ was moved from the west side to the east side, and stained glass windows were added. Since 1991, the church has been owned and used by the Evangelical Church of Groningen. The building is a municipal monument.

name: Hervormde Kapel
description:
The Evangelisatiegebouw, also known as the Reformed Chapel, is a former church in Deventer, constructed between 1890 and 1893 for the Reformed Church Rehoboth. The building includes a main church hall and another section spread over two floors.

It was built on land purchased from the municipality of Deventer, previously used for the foundation of the Noordenberg Tower and part of a canal bed. The building is made of brick. In 1973, the building was acquired by the Reformed Churches. It functioned as a church until 2009, after which it was repurposed.

name: Hervormde Kapel van Den Oever
description:
The Gasthuiskapel in Den Oever was originally part of a complex including a guest house, one of the oldest charity institutions in North Holland, dating back to the 14th century. The chapel itself was added in the 16th century, dedicated to Saint Elisabeth. Initially separate, the buildings were later connected.

In the 1960s, the complex was dismantled. The dilapidated guest house was beyond repair and unsuitable for museum display. However, the Gasthuiskapel was carefully disassembled and rebuilt in 1967 as one of the first structures in the Zuiderzee Museum's open-air museum. The chapel's blue slate floor largely originated from the former Dutch Reformed church of Lutjebroek. Sadly, fresco traces on the walls in Den Oever were lost during reconstruction. The pulpit bears the inscription "Those who believe in Christ through God's spirit have a place prepared here and above." The cabinet organ, made in 1853 by Hermanus Knipscheer, came from the Enkhuizen cemetery.

name: Hervormde Kerk
description: The Hervormde Kerk in Coevorden, also known as the Grote Kerk or Kruiskerk, is one of the earliest Protestant churches in the Netherlands. It was built between 1639 and 1645 on the site of an older, dilapidated church. The church has a Greek cross ground plan and was constructed using Daler and Bentheimer stones. In the 16th century, the previous church suffered from shelling during the Eighty Years' War. The reformed and Hervormde church communities of Coevorden merged to form a Protestant community, and the Kruiskerk was decommissioned.

name: Hervormde Kerk
description:
The Hervormde Kerk in Hoornsterzwaag, Netherlands, is a church building located in the province of Friesland. This hall church with three-sided closure was built in 1621, as indicated by the year anchors on the west facade. The church was renovated in 1856 and is now a national monument.

No longer used for religious services, the building serves as a concert venue. A freestanding bell tower, rebuilt in 2007, houses a bell cast in 1688 by Petrus Overney. For a number of years the church functioned as an atelier for a painter. Currently, the church also provides lodging in cooperation with "Heilige Nachten".

name: Hervormde Kerk
description:
The Hervormde Kerk, now known as Gereformeerde Kerk 'De Kandelaar', is a church building in Opeinde, Friesland, Netherlands. Built in 1908, it was designed by architect Wolter te Riele according to central building principles. The church is unique as the only reformed church in Te Riele's body of work, who primarily designed Roman Catholic church buildings.

The building has a Greek cross ground plan. The tower has two sections with a tent roof and houses a clock from 1659. Above the entrance is a reused mannerist facade stone from around 1630. In 1975, the church and the attached consistory room were enlarged. The interior is covered by a dome and the arched windows have stained glass. The pulpit from the 17th century comes from the old church. The organ from 1909 was made by Bakker & Timmenga. The church is a national monument. In 2012, the church was sold and taken over by the Reformed Church, which had previously met in Olterterp.

name: Hervormde Kerk
description:
The Hervormde Kerk in Ammerzoden, also known as the Ruïnekerk (Ruin Church), is one of two church buildings belonging to the Hervormde Gemeente of Well en Ammerzoden. A notable feature of the church is that a large part of it has been a ruin since the 17th century.

Originally dedicated to Mary and called Onze-Lieve-Vrouwekerk during the Catholic period, the church is a Gothic cruciform church featuring a three-aisled nave, a transept, both dating back to the first half of the 16th century, and a deep, single-aisled choir with a polygonal closure from the 14th century. The nave and transept have been in ruins since 1672. The remaining section of the church is still used for services.

name: Hervormde Kerk
description:
The Hervormde Kerk in Beekbergen is a Dutch Reformed village church. The current church building was constructed in the 15th century, replacing an older 11th-century church. The original material, tuff stone from the Eifel region, was reused in the construction. The choir was added at the beginning of the 16th century.

The lower part of the tower dates back to the 13th century. At the end of the 15th century, the tower was heightened with a brick section. The current spire was placed in 1867. The church houses an organ from 1779, designed by Johan Gustav Schilling. The organ was originally located in the Oude Kerk in Apeldoorn and was donated to the Beekbergen church when the former was demolished in 1842.

name: Hervormde Kerk
description: The Hervormde Kerk, also known as the Kapel van Bronkhorst, is a Protestant church in the Dutch town of Bronkhorst. It was built in the 14th century with funds from Gijsbert V van Bronckhorst and his wife, Catharina van Leefdael. The church is a Gothic brick building with a three-sided closure, buttresses, and depressed pointed arch windows. A portal extension is located against the west facade. The roof and bell tower were built after the city fire of 1633. The church underwent architectural reconstruction in the 1960s.

name: Hervormde Kerk
description:
The Hervormde Kerk in Geesteren is a late-Gothic church. The ship and choir date back to the late 15th century, while the tower is from the 14th century. The church is unique in the Achterhoek region due to its saddle roof and stepped gables. The lower sections of the tower have small Romanesque and early Gothic columns.

The church suffered damage during the Eighty Years' War and was set on fire in 1586 by the State Garrison of Lochem. It was restored in 1628. The south wall is made of grey tuff stone from the original construction period. During the restoration of 1929/30, traces of the old vaults were discovered and reconstructed.

name: Hervormde Kerk
description:
The Hervormde Kerk in Gelselaar is a small neo-Gothic church featuring a tower above the entrance. This tower includes a slender, constricted spire, topped with a star and a weather vane. The church's side facades are adorned with pointed arch windows. Inside, a notable feature is the 17th-century pulpit.

Originally, around 1440, a chapel stood on the site, dependent on the mother church of Neede until the Reformation in 1616. In 1617, Gelselaar became an independent Reformed parish. The current "waterstaatskerk" replaced the chapel in 1841. The church is in a quiet area of Gelselaar surrounded by houses and a footpath.

name: Hervormde Kerk
description: The Hervormde Kerk, also known as the Protestant chapel, is a Protestant church in Megchelen, Netherlands. The white-plastered hall church was first mentioned in 1411 and was probably built as a chapel then. The church tower with a small spire was added to the building in 1776. The church has a clock tower with a peal of two bells, one of which is from J.R. Voigt, 1787, with a diameter of 61 cm, and a modern bell. A single-manual organ, made around 1870 by Eckert using older pipework, is also present.

name: Hervormde Kerk
description:
The Hervormde Kerk in Otterlo is a historical village church with a tower, dating back to 1215. The single-nave church has an early 14th-century ship without buttresses and a simple brick tower, likely from the same period, featuring an overhanging arched frieze and a slender spire.

The ship was raised in 1865 and has a 19th-century cove ceiling. The church's exterior is plastered. The chancel features 17th-century furniture, including paneling and benches with ear ornaments within arches surrounded by acanthus foliage, a well-carved pulpit, and simple lordly pews against the chancel's straight sides. The church also has two 17th-century-style copper chandeliers. A mechanical tower clock is out of use. The church has had an organ since 1897.

name: Hervormde Kerk
description:
The Reformed Church, locally known as the Grote Kerk (Great Church), is located in Scherpenzeel, Gelderland. A large fourteenth-century castle, home to the noble Scherpenzeel family, once stood in the village just south of the church.

The church has a history that includes the Reformation and the Second World War. It features a Friedrichs organ, a Koff organ and an Adema organ. Notable sights include a copper lectern donated in 1712 and a Ten Commandments board from 1714. The church also has a pulpit.

name: Hervormde Kerk
description: The Hervormde Kerk, also known as the St. Joris and Barbarakerk, is a Protestant church in Terborg. This single-nave church has been constructed and modified in sections over the centuries. It was originally dedicated to Joris and Barbara of Nicomedia. Around 1370 there was already a chapel in this place. In 1372 Hendrik van Wisch had an altar dedicated to Maria and Saint Georgius. Terborg became an independent parish in 1382. During the Reformation, the church transitioned from Catholic to Reformed hands. The church has a distinctive tower built in 1746 by G. Ravenschot.

name: Hervormde Kerk
description:
The Hervormde Kerk, also known as the St. Joriskerk, is a Protestant church in Voor-Drempt. The first chapel on the site was founded in 731. In the 11th century, the chapel was replaced by a church, of which the Romanesque church tower still stands. The ship is Gothic (circa 1400) and the choir is about 100 years younger.

In 1868, the church was renovated in the neo-Gothic style, but in the mid-20th century, it was restored to its original style. The church became known for its tapestries in the sixties, which were knitted by the Drempt neighborhoods to improve the acoustics.

name: Hervormde Kerk
description: The Hervormde Kerk in Wehl is a Protestant church built in 1858, replacing an earlier church from the early 18th century. The Protestant community in Wehl was founded in 1725. Around 1900, a tower with a spire was added to the church, housing a bell from a church in Steggerda. The church is a single-nave, neo-Gothic building featuring cast-iron window tracery. The organ was built by H. Haffmans. In 1988, the then-municipality of Wehl designated the church as a municipal monument.

name: Hervormde Kerk
description:
The Hervormde Kerk in Wichmond is a Protestant church built in the mid-19th century, which formed the basis for the growth of Wichmond. The first mention of a church in Wichmond dates back to 794 when Liudger founded a church. That church was destroyed during the Eighty Years' War.

The current church and parsonage were built just after the middle of the 19th century for the Dutch Reformed community. Behind the church is the Withmundi building, which is used for church and social activities. The church and parsonage are municipal monuments. The Knipscheer organ from 1867 is a national monument.

name: Hervormde Kerk
description: The Kerk van Bourtange, located in the town of Bourtange in Groningen, was built in 1869, replacing the old garrison church. The older church was the first newly built Protestant church in the province of Groningen and had been in use since before 1607. The current church still contains a triptych with the text of the confession of faith from 1607. The church is used for services by the Reformed community of Bourtange, which is part of the Protestant Church in the Netherlands. In the back wall of the church are two stones; one with the coat of arms of the united provinces.

name: Hervormde Kerk
description: The Hervormde Kerk van Delfzijl, also called Centrumkerk, was built in 1830 as a successor to the Garnizoenskerk of Delfzijl. The Garnizoenskerk of Delfzijl was built in 1614. The church is located at the Molenbergplein in the center of Delfzijl. The Protestant Church of Delfzijl has three church buildings.

name: Hervormde Kerk
description:
The Kerk van Garmerwolde is a medieval church, considered one of the finest late Romanesque churches in the region. Originally a Romanesque cruciform church with a free-standing saddle roof tower, it dates back to the 13th century. In the 19th century, the ship was demolished, leaving the transept, crossing, and choir.

The interior features well-preserved painted melon vaults and is open to visitors. The church is also available for rent for various events, including wedding services, funerals, receptions, concerts, and exhibitions. It also serves its original function, holding a reformed service once a month. Since 2020, the tower contains an exhibition with an Escher-inspired staircase.

name: Hervormde Kerk
description:
The church in Harkstede is a notable building with a strongly historicizing character. Completed in 1700, it stands out due to its medieval appearance, despite being built in post-Reformation times. Henric Piccardt and Anna Elisabeth Rengers, the founders, intentionally designed it to evoke the Middle Ages and to serve as a lasting memory of themselves.

Beneath the entire church floor are enormous, vaulted crypts. The high church is clearly visible along the Hoofdweg and the church tower dates back to the Middle Ages, with repairs done in 1657. The current church was built against the old tower between 1692 and 1700 in a primarily Gothic style. The exterior of the church was restored in 2009, and the interior restoration was completed more recently.

name: Hervormde Kerk
description: The church of Lellens is a church building of the Dutch Reformed Church in the village of Lellens, in the municipality of Groningen. It is a simple, straight-closed hall church with a gable roof and an openwork roof turret. According to the foundation stone in the south wall, the church was built in 1667. The church was built by Hilbrandt Gruis and Geertruit Hoorenken, residents of the Lellens castle. The pulpit with sounding board in late-Mannerist forms (1668), a large painted sign with 64 quarter coats of arms of the Gruys-Tamminga families (1690) and two pews are part of the church inventory.

name: Hervormde Kerk
description:
The Church of Midwolde is a Romanesque church in the Westerkwartier municipality in Groningen, constructed in the 12th century. Despite later expansions and renovations, its Romanesque character is still evident in the round-arched windows. The tower's construction also began in the 12th century and was extended around 1400. Most of the windows are now Gothic.

The interior is dominated by the marble tomb of Carel Hieronymus van In- and Kniphuisen and his wife, Anna van Ewsum, designed by Rombout Verhulst. A sculpture of her second husband, Georg Wilhelm van Inn- and Kniphuisen, by Bartholomeus Eggers, was later added. On either side of the tomb are elevated lordly pews from 1660, slightly higher than the pulpit designed in 1711 by Allert Meijer, with wood carvings by Jan de Rijk. A stained-glass window commemorates the Van Panhuys family. The church has been owned by the Stichting Oude Groninger Kerken since 1971 and has been a national monument since 1973.

name: Hervormde Kerk
description: The reformed church of Nieuw-Beerta was built in 1856, replacing a 17th-century church. It is a so-called "waterstaatskerk," one of the churches built in the Netherlands between 1824 and 1875 with support from the national government. The north-south oriented church stands on the edge of the village, on the south side of the road from Nieuw-Beerta to Beerta, and is located on the old, long-unused cemetery. The church was transferred to the Stichting Oude Groninger Kerken in September 2003. The church remains available for church services for the ecclesiastical municipality. The church has a Hardorff organ built in 1857, the only one in the province of Groningen.

name: Hervormde Kerk
description:
The Kerk van Noordbroek is an imposing cruciform church built in the early 14th century. Its style is mainly Late Romanesque, recognizable by the layout and treatment of the walls, featuring a lower and upper level with decorative masonry in the upper section. However, its high walls and pointed arch windows give it a Gothic appearance.

Inside, the church boasts dome vaults, murals, and vault paintings, along with remnants from its Catholic past, like an aumbry in the choir and a piscina. The interior is richly adorned with a choir screen, an elaborately carved pulpit, and a Schnitger organ. The local committee organizes exhibitions, lectures, organ recitals and guided tours and church services are also regularly held.

name: Hervormde Kerk
description:
The Kerk van Schildwolde dates back to the seventeenth century. The current church was built in 1686 on the foundations of an older church from the thirteenth century, after the Reformation. It is a simple hall church constructed of brick with a layer of plaster.
