A notable feature is the separately standing Juffertoren, a remnant of the original church. The Juffertoren has a legend connected to it about three rich sisters. Inside the church, a pulpit with twisted columns, a coat rack, stairs and soundboard from 1666 can be found.

name: Hervormde Kerk
description: The Kerk van Sellingen is an early Gothic church building in the village of Sellingen in the municipality of Westerwolde in East Groningen, built around 1300. The church once belonged to the abbey of Corvey. Late Gothic paintings were discovered in the church in the 1920s, including images of Saint Christopher and Saint Margaret, signed by 'brother Jan van Aken' and 'Johannes'. The church's roof is partly made of hollow and convex tiles. The roof turret was placed on the church in 1858. The pulpit dates from the mid-17th century and was placed in the Sellingen church in the 19th century. The church organ was built in 1952.

name: Hervormde Kerk
description:
The church of Ten Boer is a medieval church building located in the village of Ten Boer in the Dutch province of Groningen. It was built as a monastery church in the 13th century, next to the Benedictine convent. After the dissolution in 1485, the monastery was demolished, but the church remained as a parish church.

Inside, notable features include the hooded council bench and two monks' benches in the choir. The pulpit dates from the second half of the seventeenth century. The church organ was built in 1894 by the Groningen organ builder Jan Doornbos, who often used material from eighteenth-century organs in his constructions. A memorial stone in the north wall indicates that the church was restored in 1565.

name: Hervormde Kerk
description: The Kerk van Uitwierde is a Dutch Reformed church located on the village mound in Uitwierde, in the municipality of Eemsdelta. The current church was built in 1839, while the freestanding church tower dates back to around 1200. The medieval church suffered significant damage during the siege of Delfzijl (1813-1814) by French troops. The current church is built in a neoclassical style. The church again sustained heavy damage during the liberation of Delfzijl in the Second World War, and it was restored in 1948. The Van Dam organ, originally from the church of Heveskes, was placed in the church in 1975 and dates from 1888. Two tombstones from the Wincken family are immured next to the church entrance.

name: Hervormde Kerk
description: The Church of Vlagtwedde refers to the Dutch Reformed church in the village of Vlagtwedde in East Groningen. The church dates back to the second half of the 13th century. However, it doesn't have a medieval appearance because the church is covered with plaster. A unique feature is the monumental pipe organ inside the church, dating from around 1850. The former Reformed Church, also known as the 'Pearl of 'Weite' by the locals, was built in 1934 by architect B. Geuchies. The tower was added a few years later.

name: Hervormde Kerk
description:
The Kerk van Wedde, also known as the Grote Kerk, is first mentioned in the 11th century, possibly as a wooden predecessor to the current building. The current Romano-Gothic church was constructed in the first half of the 13th century. In the 15th century, it was expanded and heightened. However, in 1666, part of the church was lowered due to damage from war. The windows were enlarged after the Reformation, replacing the narrow Gothic windows. The tower was added much later, in 1860, and houses a bell from 1817.

Inside, the church features a 17th-century pulpit made in Leer in 1679, and a "drostenbank" dating back to around 1700, adorned with the Groningen coat of arms. Several residents of the Wedderburcht are buried in the church, including Haye Addinge (1492). The last "drost" of Westerwolde, Albert Hindrik van Swinderen, is also buried there. A Flentrop choir organ without pedals, built in 1979, replaced a harmonium that had been there since 1904.

name: Hervormde Kerk
description: The church of Wittewierum is a former reformed church building in the village of Wittewierum, in the municipality of Groningen. The current church was built in 1863 and has been owned by the Stichting Oude Groninger Kerken (Old Groningen Churches Foundation) since 1977. The church is a broad hall church with a straight-closed choir. The architectural style is clearly eclectic. The facade includes a neoclassical door frame, pointed arch windows with neo-Gothic cast iron tracery, a tympanum as a facade covering, and cast iron pinnacles and an openwork roof turret decorated with neo-Gothic motifs. Since the last restoration in 2003, the church has mainly been used for exhibitions and events.

name: Hervormde Kerk
description:
The Hervormde Kerk in Eijsden, built in 1906, showcases Neo-Gothic elements and was designed by architect J.M. Odinot. It is a single-nave church featuring a rectangular layout and a saddle roof covered with Maas slate. A tower with a pointed tent roof is integrated into the front facade, also covered with slate.

The church is constructed with brick and hard stone. It includes rectangular wooden doors with pointed arch fanlights and pointed arch stained glass windows. Inside, the church has retained its original wooden pews, pulpit, and paneling. The interior color scheme, designed by Sjef Hutschemakers, features earthy tones at the bottom, transitioning to a soft blue ceiling adorned with gold-leaf rosettes, creating a serene atmosphere.

name: Hervormde Kerk
description:
The Hervormde Kerk in Aalburg is a Protestant church located in the old village of Aalburg, which is part of Wijk en Aalburg in the municipality of Altena. The church has a long history, with the original church possibly founded around the year 1000. The oldest record of a church dates back to 1012. Originally, it was dedicated to St. Trudo and belonged to the Abbey of Sint-Truiden.

A wooden church was replaced by a tuff stone building between 1055 and 1082. In 1630, the church burned down due to lightning and was rebuilt. During the Second World War, the church was severely damaged. After restoration in 1955, a new consistory was built and an organ was installed. Due to growth, a new church building was constructed in 2011 and put into use in 2012.

name: Hervormde Kerk
description:
The Hervormde Kerk in Dinteloord is a church building located at Westvoorstraat 26. It is a square brick structure built in 1693, designed by Johan van Swieten. The church features a square, dome-covered bell chamber on the roof, supported internally by four wooden columns. A square staircase tower is located against the rear facade.

The church was heavily damaged during the war in 1944 but was restored afterward in its original form. Above the entrance, there's a niche with a natural stone frame, featuring a stone cartouche with the inscription "1693" and the coat of arms of King Stadtholder Willem III, made by Jan Blommendaal.

name: Hervormde Kerk
description: The Hervormde Kerk in Eethen is a historical church building. The church has a Romanesque nave made of tuff stone dating back to the 12th century, featuring small windows in round-arched fields separated by wall dams. In the 13th century, the church was expanded westward with one bay and a flat-topped tower, which was further raised in the 15th century. In the second half of the 15th century, the church was enlarged with a Gothic choir that is higher than the nave. The walls are made of brick, with layers of tuff stone. The church sustained heavy war damage and was restored between 1948 and 1951.

name: Hervormde Kerk
description:
The former Hervormde Kerk (Reformed Church) of Schijndel, also known as Napoleonskerkje, is a neoclassical church located on Hoofdstraat in Schijndel. The church is surrounded by tall trees. It is a listed monument, but no longer used as a house of worship.

After the medieval church was returned to the Catholics in 1801, the Protestants needed their own church building. Construction was approved in 1808 and completed in 1811, although the building indicates the year 1808. The membership decreased, and in 1823 the congregation merged with that of Sint-Michielsgestel.

name: Hervormde Kerk
description:
The Hervormde Kerk (Reformed Church) of Veen is a medieval church building located in the village on Grotestraat. Originally built around 1100 as a Catholic church from tuff stone, it transitioned to the Dutch Reformed Church during the Reformation.

The church features a Romanesque nave, extended in the 13th century with a brick section and a brick tower. Inside, it has wooden barrel vaults, a 17th-century pulpit, and two 18th-century lord's pews. A restoration in 1961-1963 reversed some 19th-century alterations. The church community is part of the Protestant Church in the Netherlands.

name: Hervormde Kerk
description: The Hervormde Kerk in Abbekerk is a Dutch Reformed church with national monument status. The church has a tower that once belonged to the secular municipality instead of the ecclesiastical municipality. The walls of the ship are constructed from reused bricks. A barometer from 1878 hangs on one of the outer walls. The tower has a stone with the year 1656, but the brick spire is of a later date. The balustrade, on the other hand, is original. The church also has a consistory room, which housed a Sunday school and is a 19th-century expansion.

name: Hervormde Kerk
description:
The Hervormde Kerk (also known as the Church on the Gouw) in Opperdoes, North Holland, is a church building dating from around 1530. However, church services were held on the site where the church stands for even longer.

The modest church is located in the heart of the village on a slightly elevated churchyard. The church has a single nave and a five-sided closed chapel with a tower. The church was restored in 1942. The pulpit dates from 1688. The church tower has a rooster on the point and a chicken on the roof of the ship. The spire that is currently erected dates from 1939/1940. Since the merger of the Reformed and the Reformed, the Reformed church is only used for special celebrations. The weekly church services are held in the (ex)Reformed church on the Noorderpad.

name: Hervormde Kerk
description: The Hervormde Kerk, or Grote Kerk, of Schermerhorn, was first put into use in 1636, though a church stood on the site since 1520. The current building is a protected monument. Built between 1634 and 1636, the Dutch Reformed Church was constructed in the Gothic style, taking the form of a basilica. The interior reflects Schermerhorn's maritime past, with a stylized harpoon tip on the spire and two ship models hanging inside. The pointed arch windows are part of the Unesco Top 10 stained glass windows in the Netherlands. The wooden barrel vault is painted with floral motifs. The floor is raised for safety during storms and floods.

name: Hervormde Kerk
description:
The Hervormde Kerk in Losser is located at Raadhuisplein 2 in the center of Losser. Next to the church is the Aleida Leurinkhuis. The church was built in 1810 after the Protestants had to return the old Sint-Martinuskerk to the Catholics.

In 2010, the church and the Aleida Leurinkhuis were thoroughly renovated and connected by a glass corridor, creating a modern church center. Both buildings are national monuments, as is the organ inside the church. The church is a simple hall church with pointed arch windows and a roof turret. The single-manual organ was built in 1725 by Diedrich Martens.

name: Hervormde Kerk
description:
The Hervormde Kerk in Wilnis, province Utrecht, is a church building used by the local Hervormde congregation. Constructed in 1877-1878, it was designed by architect F.J. Nieuwenhuis from Utrecht in an eclectic style. The church is situated on the northeast side of Wilnis, parallel to the Ir. Enschedeweg.

It's a hall church with a rectangular layout, featuring a saddle roof covered with muted Dutch tiles. A tower is positioned on the south side, and a consistory was added on the north side. The tower has a square plan with four sections. The fourth section has chamfered corners, openings, a clock, and a surrounding brick balustrade with pinnacles.

name: Hervormde Kerk
description:
The Hervormde Kerk in Burgh is the oldest Protestant church building on the island, constructed between 1671 and 1674. This Renaissance-style church owes its existence largely to Pieter de Huybert. The brick building is designed in the shape of a Greek cross with lower side arms.

The church has faced significant challenges, including a fire in 1924 and war damage in 1945. It was rebuilt in 1948, with the tower reconstructed in 1949, based on images from before 1924. Despite the restorations, the historic atmosphere of the church has been preserved. The church features an organ built in 1794.

name: Hervormde Kerk
description: The Hervormde Kerk in Kapelle is located in the center of the Zeeland ring village in Zuid-Beveland. The church was built in different centuries. The tower dates back to around 1300, the nave to the first half of the 15th century. The north choir is late 15th century, the tomb chapel early 16th century. The tower is 65 meters high, making it the highest tower in South Beveland. Inside, the church is very simple, but very light. The church is home to the Reformed Church of Kapelle.

name: Hervormde Kerk
description: The Hervormde Kerk in Kerkwerve is a church building located on the island of Schouwen-Duiveland in the Netherlands. The building was constructed in 1900, replacing a dilapidated medieval church that was closed in 1895 and demolished. The construction of the new church was undertaken by contractor Willem Lemsom from Kerkwerve for 13,250 guilders and completed in 1901. A notable feature of the church is its pulpit, which dates back to around 1700 and was salvaged from the former church. In 1987, a new organ was installed by Jaap Fama & Piet Raadgever, replacing the old Spiering organ from 1953.

name: Hervormde Kerk
description:
The Hervormde Kerk, also known as the Open Havenkerk, is a Protestant church building in Oost-Souburg. Originally a Catholic Onze-Lieve-Vrouwekerk, its Gothic tower dates from the first half of the 14th century, with the ship being built in the 15th century. The church was severely damaged during religious conflicts in 1572.

In 1582-1583, the damage was repaired, and the choir was demolished to make the church suitable for Protestant services. Alterations were made to the interior in the 19th century, including a higher roof. The original columns were replaced with wooden ones, and the tower was raised. Restorations took place in 1949-1950 and again from 2005-2011. Since then, it has been used not only for church services but also for social-cultural activities.

name: Hervormde Kerk
description: The Hervormde Kerk in Schore is a Protestant church belonging to the Dutch Hervormde Kerk, located in the province of Zeeland. The church that stands today was built in 1942, replacing the previous church which was destroyed by war. The current church has a front tower and an attached consistory. An organ was installed in the church shortly after it was built. The church community has faced financial challenges over the years to maintain the church.

name: Hervormde Kerk
description:
The Hervormde Kerk in Waarde is a Protestant church belonging to the Protestant Church in the Netherlands (PKN). The old village church is likely founded shortly after 1222, linked to Cistercians who performed embankment work in the area. In the 15th century, it was a large stone hall church with a tower, possibly with two or three aisles.

In 1589, the building was destroyed by fire, leaving only the south aisle and sacristy. The columns of the north aisle are still visible in the north wall. The tower, dating from the last quarter of the 14th century, stands somewhat isolated south of the south aisle due to the disappearance of the north aisle. The church is used weekly for services and is available for cultural activities and civil marriages.

name: Hervormde Kerk
description: The Hervormde Kerk in Zonnemaire, located in the Dutch province of Zeeland, is a neo-Gothic church built in 1867-1868. It replaced a previous church from the 15th century. Rotterdam architect J.C. Bellingwout designed the church. The tower is partially a remnant of the older church. Inside, the pulpit originates from the old church building, and the marble base comes from the previous baptismal font. The wooden benches were brought from the St. Laurenskerk in Rotterdam and placed in the church in 2000-2001. The church also has a Flaes organ built in 1871, which remains in its original condition. The pulpit and organ are national monuments.

name: Hervormde Kerk, afgebroken in 1985, herbouwd in het Nederlands Openluchtmuseum te Arnhem
description:
The Hervormde Kerk in 's-Heerenhoek is a simple hall church that dates back to the early 19th century. It features a bell-shaped facade and a memorial stone above the framed door. The building is plastered at the base and has pointed arch windows and buttresses on the sides. A roof turret sits atop the gable roof.

Originally located in 's-Heerenhoek in Zeeland, it was built in 1672 and relocated to the Open Air Museum in Arnhem in 1988. The church is still in use, among other things.

name: Hervormde Kerk, afgebroken in 1985, herbouwd in het Nederlands Openluchtmuseum te Arnhem
description: The Nederlands Openluchtmuseum features a Zeeland church, which is available as a wedding location. The museum is considered a special place to get married. You can even take a ride on the wedding tram. The church itself was relocated from its original location and rebuilt in the museum, like many of the other buildings.

name: Hervormde Kerk, afgebroken in 1985, herbouwd in het Nederlands Openluchtmuseum te Arnhem
description:
The Eusebius Church, also known as the Grote Kerk, is the largest church and building in Arnhem, standing at 93 meters tall. Its construction began in 1450, intended to rival the St. Steven's Church in Nijmegen, and replaced an older church dedicated to St. Martinus. Although it suffered severe damage during the Battle of Arnhem in 1944, it has been restored and remains an icon of the city.

Inside, the church showcases Late Gothic architecture. The interior features the tomb of Duke Charles of Gelre, dating back to 1531. A unique panoramic elevator takes visitors to the top of the tower, offering a view of Arnhem and its surroundings. The crypt contains human remains. Today, the Eusebius Church serves as a tourist attraction and a venue for various events and exhibitions.

name: Hervormde Sint-Nicolaaskerk
description: The Reformed Church, also known as St. Nicholas Church, is located in Broek in Waterland and is the oldest building in the town. The church is a historical monument and an iconic building in the village. Originally built in the 15th century, this late Gothic building consists of two naves, a north and south portal, and a tower to the west. The tower has a wooden superstructure dating back to 1648. The interior features wooden barrel vaults, columns with list capitals, and round arches. Inside are a pulpit from 1685, a baptismal gate from the second quarter of the 17th century, and stained glass windows depicting the history of the church.

name: Hervormde Sint-Victorkerk
description:
The Hervormde Sint-Victorkerk in Wijchen, also known as the Sint-Victorkerk, is a church with a rich history and architectural significance. Originally a Roman Catholic church dedicated to Saint Victor, it transitioned to become a Dutch Reformed church during the Reformation. The church features a distinctive tower and a nave, reflecting its historical development.

Throughout the centuries, the Sint-Victorkerk has undergone several renovations and expansions, adapting to the changing needs of its congregation and architectural styles. Today, it stands as a prominent landmark in Wijchen, serving as a place of worship and a testament to the town's religious and cultural heritage.

name: Hervormde kerk
description:
The Hervormde Kerk in Stompetoren, also known as De Ark, is a nationally listed church that gave the North Holland village of Stompetoren its name. It was built in 1662-1663 following a decision by the polder board. Although built as a Protestant church, its design is in the late Gothic style. The church tower was intentionally built without a spire.

The church is a single-nave cruciform church featuring a wooden barrel vault. Inside, the church contains a pulpit, lectern, and benches dating back to the 17th century, along with copper chandeliers from the same era. The organ was constructed in 1862. During a restoration in 1950-1955, the bricked-up windows in the nave were reopened and fitted with glass.

name: Hervormde kerk
description: The Hervormde Kerk in Broek op Langedijk is a 15th-century church building located on Dorpsstraat 72. The church was mainly built in the 16th century, with the oldest part being the choir from the 15th century. Inside the church, there is a pulpit from 1709, a baptismal arch from the 17th century, and a Ten Commandments board from 1642. The organ, made by the German organ builders Gebrüder Euler, dates from 1884 and has two manuals, 20 registers, and a free pedal. The church is still an important meeting place for many residents, with services held every Sunday at 10:00 and 19:00.

name: Hervormde kerk
description:
The Hervormde Kerk in Heerhugowaard, currently named Ontmoetingskerk, is a church building located in Heerhugowaard. In 1866, the Protestant committee in Heerhugowaard decided to build a new Waterstaatskerk on the Middenweg, centrally located in the village.

The church houses an organ with a carmine red case, made in 1873 by Amsterdam organ builder Pieter Flaes. It originates from the demolished Hervormde Kerk in Lutjebroek and was moved to Heerhugowaard in 1972. Since a thorough renovation in 1985, it has two manuals, 13 registers and a free pedal. A gilded entrance gate has stood in front of the church since 1983. The church is still used for church services and also serves as a cultural center, in collaboration with the neighboring community center De Brink.

name: Hervormde kerk
description:
The church of Etersheim was built around 1900 for the Dutch Reformed community in Etersheim. The first church was lost to floods, and a replacement was built. This 17th or 18th-century church was also demolished, with its stones reused for the new construction at the end of the 19th century, which was completed in 1901.

In 1984, the tower had to be removed due to its dilapidated state, leaving only a truncated base. To the left of the church is a cemetery on higher ground. The building initially served as a theater and was even rented by a Satanic church from Amsterdam. It was later converted into a private residence and now also serves as a bed and breakfast.

name: Hervormde kerk
description: The Hervormde Kerk in Kwadijk is a national monument dating back to 1835. It is a hall church with pointed arched windows and a wooden tower on the west facade. The spire of the tower is covered with copper plates. Inside, the church features a pulpit from the 17th century, a baptismal font from the 18th century and a copper baptismal arch in Louis XIV style from 1741. The floor consists of tombstones from the former cruciform church. A Flaes organ from 1866 is also present. Nowadays, the church is also a popular wedding location.

name: Hervormde kerk
description:
The Hervormde Kerk in Schardam is a small, single-nave building with a five-sided closure, likely dating back to 1662. It was built to replace a late Gothic church. The west wall was renovated with machine-made bricks after the tower's demolition. Inside, the church features a pulpit from 1662, a communion rail with an arch from 1856, and a copper preacher's lectern from around 1700.

A square wooden tower was replaced around 1860 by a much smaller turret, also called a roof rider. In this roof rider, the bronze bell from 1497 originating from the previous church was placed. The church ceased to be used for services in 1968. In the 1970s, the current owners, the Mantje artist couple, restored the church, and it now serves as their home and studio.

name: Hervormde kerk
description:
The Hervormde Kerk in Warder is a former Reformed church built in 1847 in the Dutch village of Warder. It is the only national monument in the village, and was registered as such on May 18, 1967.

The church is a hall church featuring a wooden tower above its neoclassical facade, in which a bell is housed. The facade is designed as a framed facade with a central risalit topped by a fronton. Below the fronton is a double panel door with a white painted door frame, flanked by arched windows on either side.

name: Hervormde kerk
description: The Hervormde Kerk in Watergang, Netherlands, is a Dutch Reformed church built in 1642 in Gothic style. The year of construction is displayed on a stone above the entrance. The church has a wooden tower on the front facade, which was added in the 19th century. Inside, there's a sculpted pulpit with reliefs, a baptismal gate from the 18th century, and a single-keyboard organ made around 1860 by H. Knipscheer. The church also features a mechanical tower clock made by Petit & Fritsen around 1920, and a ship model from around 1725. The church is still active as a religious community.

name: Hervormde kerk
description: The Hervormde Kerk, also known as the Dorpskerk, is a Protestant church located in Sint Laurens, Zeeland. The current church was built in 1644, replacing an earlier church that was demolished in 1566 following the Beeldenstorm. It is a brick building with a rectangular floor plan. The portal features a basket arch. A roof turret and sandstone miniature castles on the gateposts were likely added in the 18th century. The current consistory dates from 1928, and the church was restored in 1952. The church community is part of the Protestant Church in the Netherlands and focuses on connection with each other and with God.

name: Hervormde kerk
description: The Hervormde Kerk is the Protestant church of Colijnsplaat, located in the Zeeland province of the Netherlands. The church is a simple hall church under a double gable roof, featuring an attached square tower covered by a tent roof. Originally built as a Reformed church, it was expanded in 1615 and renovated in 1769. Since January 1, 2006, the church community has been formed from the merger between the Reformed Municipality and the Reformed Church. The church also serves as a venue for exhibitions and performances since 2010.

name: Hervormde kerk
description:
The Hervormde Kerk (Reformed Church) in Geersdijk is a former church building located in Geersdijk. The current building was constructed in 1960, replacing an earlier church from 1927 that was destroyed in 1953 by the Watersnoodramp. The church is a modest reconstruction church without a tower.

The last service was held on January 3, 1960, after which demolition began. Construction of the new building by contractor R. Slotema started in February. The exterior was completed in September, but work continued inside. On January 18, 1961, the building was officially handed over by the Disaster Fund and put into use by minister W. Koole.

From the beginning of 1999, all services were held elsewhere, leaving the church empty again. In 2002, the building was rented to pianist Martine Davidian, who used it as a concert hall and opened it for musical activities, known as the 'Haydn Huis'. In January 2004, the lease was terminated, and the building was sold to be converted into a residential house.

name: Hervormde kerk
description:
The Reformed Church in Scherpenisse is a towering church located on a fenced churchyard. Originally dedicated to Maria, it features a three-aisled basilica with an unfinished tower, nearly as tall as the ship itself. The tower's construction halted after the first section, topped with a wooden structure for the bell chamber and a spire.

Constructed of brick covered in white natural stone, it reflects the village's wealth during its building period. Inside, a pulpit from 1616 stands alongside crowns dating from 1654 and 1787, plus some other brasswork. The church also houses some 17th and 18th-century pews with canopies.

name: Hervormde kerk
description: The Hervormde Kerk in Sint-Annaland is a significant church building located at Ring 1 in the municipality of Tholen. The current church replaced an older one. It was expanded in 1959 with two wings, providing seating for 950 people. The church has a rich history, with the first stone laid in 1476, and was built on the foundations of an older church. After the reformation, the church came into the hands of the protestants in 1586. The church has a pipe organ built in 1977 by Fa. Leeflang.

name: Hervormde kerk
description:
The Hervormde Kerk in Sint Philipsland is a Protestant church used by the Hervormde Gemeente St-Philipsland. The church was built in 1668 in a sober classicist style. Before its construction, religious services were held in houses and later in a barn with a turret.

In 1768, the church was restored due to its dilapidated state, followed by another major restoration in 1844. It suffered heavy damage during the 1953 flood. The consistory, likely renovated in 1896, was replaced after the flood by a community center. A significant restoration took place in 1968, and in 1985, new heating was installed and the interior was painted. The church features a pulpit from 1668 and an organ built by Willem van Leeuwen in 1957.

name: Hervormde kerk
description: The Hervormde Kerk in Stavenisse is a Protestant church belonging to the Dutch Reformed Church. The original church building dates back to 1617 but was renovated between 1910 and 1911. The church tower is still original, dating back to 1672. Inside the church, you can find the tomb of Hieronymus of Tuyll of Serooskerke, dating back to around 1670, made by Rombout Verhulst. The tomb features a reclining figure with a back wall decorated with coats of arms and putti. The pulpit features Ionic pilasters. There is also a readers desk and a board of regents from the same period and the coat of arms of the Van der Lek-de Clercq family hangs above the regents' bench.

name: Hervormde kerk
description: The Hervormde Kerk in Biggekerke is a church building located in the Dutch province of Zeeland. It is a single-nave brick church with a three-sided closed choir. The partially built-in tower has two sections and an octagonal spire. The lower space of this tower is vaulted by a ribbed vault. The nave is vaulted by a wooden barrel vault and tie beams. The church has a pulpit from around 1630 and a coat of arms that was placed in 1896. The church is centrally located in the village on a green area.

name: Hervormde kerk
description:
The Hervormde Kerk in Westkapelle was a church building located on Zuidstraat, opposite the old rectory. It was constructed in 1834 in a neoclassical style as a Waterstaatskerk.

The design for the new church was created by the Middelburg city architect Pieter Cornelis Bosdijk. Although the April specifications were slightly modified, the construction was contracted out to the Middelburg contractor C.J. van Uije on November 19 for 23,000 guilders. The 3,000 guilder deficit was covered by selling remnants of the old church for 1,000 guilders, and requesting a 2,000 guilder subsidy from the Provincial College. The College forwarded the request to the minister, who obtained another 1,000 guilders from King Willem I. The building was destroyed in 1944 during English bombings of Westkapelle and the Zeedijk.

name: Hervormde kerk
description: The Hervormde Kerk in Den Hoorn, located in the municipality of Texel, is a church building dating back to 1425. It is characterized by its white tower. The church is a national monument ("rijksmonument") and has a graveyard surrounding it. A restoration took place in 1956-57.

name: Hervormde kerk
description: The Hervormde Kerk in Nisse has its origins in the 14th century. The building consists of a single-aisled nave, a lower choir from the 15th century, and two transepts from the beginning of the 16th century. The oldest part of the church is the tower, dating back to the 14th century, the only remnant of the church's predecessor. It's a tall, slender tower and has a small corner tower which was added in 1922. Before the Reformation, the church was dedicated to Maria, mother of God. Inside, a vault dish shows the Coronation of Maria.

name: Hervormde kerk 't Zand
description:
The Hervormde Kerk 't Zand is a Protestant church building located on Vogelstraat in Middelburg. It was built in Neo-Romanesque style and used by the Reformed community from 1914 to 1963. Subsequently, it served as a warehouse for a period, but has been vacant for decades.

't Zand was a neighborhood on the border of Middelburg, part of the municipality of Koudekerke until 1941. Due to the growing neighborhood, the construction of a larger church began in 1914. The stones were imported from Belgium, but the supply stopped due to World War I and the German occupation. As a result, one of the two towers was only partially completed. The church was put into use on December 7, 1914. During World War II, the church roof was damaged by shelling. The last service was held on February 24, 1963.

name: Het Lichtpunt
description: Het Lichtpunt is a church building in Assen, located in the Dutch province of Drenthe. It belongs to the church community of Assen-Kloosterveen of the Dutch Reformed Churches. The church building was constructed between 2008 and 2009 and was inaugurated in September 2009. It is a modern hall church featuring a distinctive tensile structure that supports a composite wooden mast, which is illuminated at night. As of 2023, this church community has over 1450 members. The architect of the building is Klaas Klamer from Leeuwarden.

name: Het Lokaal
description: Het Lokaal is a small church in the Netherlands, built in 1912 for the conservative reformed community. Despite being constructed in the 20th century, the church features a Neo-Classical style, which was already uncommon during that period. The church served the conservative reformed community.

name: Het Octaaf
description: Based on the provided website, Het Octaaf is a Catholic primary school. The school strives to bring out the best in its children every day by offering a safe and trusted environment where each child feels cherished, accepted and comfortable. Besides focusing on subjects such as reading, arithmetic and language, it pays attention to creativity, talent development, critical thinking, problem solving, communication and teamwork. The school aims to teach children to be responsible for themselves, others and their environment, which contributes to a positive self-image and a good dose of self-confidence. The Catholic basis is reflected in celebrations and life lessons, but also in core values: Respect, Wonder, Care, Justice, Trust, Unity and Togetherness.

name: Het Witte Kerkje
description:
The Witte Kerkje (White Church) in Huis ter Heide, part of the Dutch Reformed Church in the municipality of Zeist, is located on Amersfoortseweg 47. The first service was held on January 31, 1860.

Around the church's 150th anniversary, the plasterwork on the exterior was replaced and a new hard stone floor was installed in the hall. The interior is simple. Concerts are regularly held there, and the church is open to visitors on Open Monument Day. The church is a simple hall church built in the Waterstaat style, with the pulpit at the end of the long, rectangular hall. Round-arched windows are among the classical details.

name: Heurnse kerk
description:
The Heurnse church, also known as the Reformed Church, is a Protestant church located in De Heurne, Netherlands. Before its construction, Protestant residents relied on the Sint-Liboriuskerk in Dinxperlo, using its northern side aisle, referred to as the Heurnse zolder.

In the early 20th century, the decision was made to build a church in De Heurne. The church was completed and inaugurated on November 8, 1908. In 1995, it was modernized and expanded with a consistory room. The church houses an organ made by L. van Dam & Zn., originally built for the Reformed Church in Hellendoorn and moved to the Heurnse church in 1963.

name: Hoefstraatkerk
description:
The Hoefstraat Church, officially the St. Anthony of Padua Church, is a Roman Catholic church located in the Hoefstraat in Tilburg. The church was designed by architect Albert Margry and built between 1898 and 1899. It is a remarkable example of neo-Gothic architecture.

The building features a basilica layout, and it is characterized by its pointed arches, ribbed vaults, and stained glass windows. The church has a tall, slender bell tower that dominates the surrounding neighborhood. The church is a notable landmark in Tilburg and is considered a significant example of religious architecture from the late 19th century.

name: Hof te Zande
description: The Hof te Zande church was originally a monastery chapel built around 1250. It is the only remaining example of brick Gothic architecture built by the Cistercians in Zeeland. In 1575, the Watergeuzen destroyed the chapel. It was rebuilt in 1609 using materials from the ruins of Hof te Zande. A thorough restoration of the church took place in 1922. Today, many activities are organized in and around the church, and it can be visited by appointment.

name: Hofkerk
description: The Hofkerk in Goor is a church built in 1934. A unique feature is that it was constructed without pillars, which was unusual for the time. The interior is decorated with handmade Limburg sandstone, and the brickwork itself is quite beautiful. The side windows are made of antique colored glass and lead. The large window at the rear is also a design by the same architect, representing the symbolic form of the earth encircled by a snake, bearing the tablets of the law, above which the cross rises. A bird symbolizes the resurrection, while a bundle of rays represents the light of divine truth. The church was built by the Groothengel company from Borne and is now used for multiple purposes. Besides Sunday services, performances are regularly held there due to its excellent acoustics.

name: Hofpleinkerk
description: The Hofpleinkerk is a former Reformed church in Middelburg, Netherlands, built in 1930. The last service was held in June 2019. It has been redeveloped, with efforts made to preserve and restore the monumental details of the building. The old rafters, mantelpieces, and ceilings are still visible in the apartments. The church is being transformed into a health center. This maintains a social function and keeps the building publicly accessible. A "box-in-box" concept was chosen as a spatial solution. The interior enhances the cubist design and plays with light and shadow.

name: Holy Trinity Church
description:
Holy Trinity Church is an Anglican parish church in Utrecht, located in the Oudwijk neighborhood at Van Limburg Stirumplein near Van Limburg Stirumstraat. The first stone was laid on November 9, 1911, by the Anglican Bishop for Northern Europe, Herbert Bury. A year later, the first church service was held, and the church was eventually consecrated on June 2, 1913.

The architect was Petrus Johannes Houtzagers, and the stained glass windows are by Henry Bosdet and were installed between 1913 and 1925.

name: Ichthuskerk
description:
The Ichthuskerk is a church building located at Grote Haag 154 in Amersfoort. It was put into use in 1967 as a Christian Reformed Church. The architects were G. Pothoven and H.A. Pothoven.

The church is a tall, brick building with small windows and a narrow, square, flat-topped brick tower equipped with clocks and topped with a spire showing a fish. This tower has decorative layers. The interior of this hall church is sober. Striking features include the black stone baptismal font and the organ.

name: Ichtuskerk
description:
The Ichthuskerk in Tholen is a church building located in the Zeeland city of Tholen, on Doelweg 7. It is used by the local Reformed Church within the Protestant Church in the Netherlands.

The church was originally built in 1889, but it was completely renovated in a modernist style in 1964, designed by G. Steen and G. Tuinhof. The building features a saddle roof and an open brick tower topped with a fish. A glass wall was installed in the facade, and the church hall was also renovated. The church contains a stained glass work depicting the burning bush. The organ was built by the Van Vulpen company. The church has about 225 seats.

name: Immanuelkerk
description: The Immanuel Church, designed by B.B. Westerhuis, is a relatively small church that stands out among the flats. Westerhuis designed it in a more traditional style compared to Eibink, showing influences of the Amsterdam School and New Building architectural movements. The church showcases a mix of brick and concrete, with the concrete having an olive-green color. The window sections are particularly striking. Originally built for the Free Evangelical Church, they vacated the premises in 2005. Subsequently, the Chinese Evangelical Christian Church took over the building, with this being the case as of 2018.

name: Immanuelkerk
description: The Immanuelkerk is a church building located in the Corpus den Hoorn neighborhood of Groningen, situated at Overwinningsplein near the Van Iddekingebrug over the Noord-Willemskanaal. The church was built in 1964 and designed by the Groningen architectural firm Haykens & Jansma. It is still in use as a church today. Originally built as a Reformed church, it is now used by the Protestant Church in the Netherlands (PKN) since the merger.

name: Immanuël
description: The Immanuelkerk in Amersfoort, located in the Liendert neighborhood, has been a church building since 1989. The building itself was originally constructed in 1960 as a gymnasium for schools and is considered to have no significant architectural value. It is owned by the Pentecostal Church Immanuel Amersfoort, which is affiliated with the United Pentecostal and Evangelical Churches. The congregation has been around since 1958. From 1972 to 1989, they held services in the former Remonstrant church on Herenstraat before moving to the space on Kraanvogelstraat.

name: Immanuëlkerk
description:
The Immanuëlkerk in Maastricht is a church building used by the Pentecostal community in the city. It is located on Brusselseweg 500 in Maastricht-Noordwest. The building is recognized as a municipal monument.

The Pentecostal community Immanuelkerk originated in 1959 in Hoensbroek and started in 1972 as an independent religious community. Initially, meetings were held in a home setting. In 1973, the community was officially registered as the Full Gospel Pentecostal Church Immanuel. They initially gathered in the former community center "Het Ruweel" in the Malberg district. Later, they moved to a former shop at Brusselsestraat 107 and in 1986, the former "Sint-Rafaël" school was purchased. In 1994, a new church hall for 400 people was put into use.

name: In alles de Liefde
description: Based on the provided website, the church, named after Saint Gudule, was originally built in the 12th century as a Roman Catholic church. It is dedicated to "In alles de Liefde", which translates to "In everything, Love". The church's history reflects its long-standing presence and significance.

name: Jachin Boazkerk
description:
The Jachin Boazkerk is a church building of the Old Reformed Congregations in the Netherlands, located on the Singel in Urk. It was built in 1959, designed by architect A.W. Helmink. The church has 1,650 seats, making it the second-largest church in terms of seating within this denomination, after the Mieraskerk in Krimpen aan den IJssel.

The brick hall church features a tower that is over 25 meters high. In 2005, the church building was expanded with a wing to accommodate the growing congregation. The new wing added 300 extra seats. In 2012, the church tower underwent significant restoration. In 2021, a new organ with 27 registers was installed, with a large portion of its pipework originating from an 1859 organ.

name: Jachin en Boazkerk
description:
The Jachin en Boazkerk in Genemuiden is a church of the Netherlands Reformed Congregations. It was built in 2003 and has a seating capacity of over 1800, making it one of the largest churches in the Netherlands regarding seating. The church was designed by architectural firm Valk te Soest.

Besides the large church hall, the building also includes a central meeting area, consistory room, five meeting rooms, a funeral room, and necessary facilities such as a kitchen. The church is named after the two pillars in Solomon's temple in Jerusalem. Jachin means "He will confirm," and Boaz means "in Him is strength."

name: Jacobikerk
description:
The Jacobikerk, or St. James' Church, is a prominent Protestant church in Utrecht, Netherlands, located on St Jacobsstraat. It's one of Utrecht's medieval parish churches and serves as the starting point for Dutch pilgrims on the Way of St. James to Santiago de Compostela.

Originally constructed in the 13th century, the Gothic church was expanded in the 14th and 15th centuries. In 1586, it was formally handed over to Protestants, leading to the whitewashing of wall decorations and the removal of altarpieces. The church still holds weekly Sunday services and is also rented out for weddings, concerts, and cultural events. The tower bell was made in 1479 and has a diameter of 182 cm.

name: Jacobskerk
description: The Jacobskerk is the medieval village church of Winterswijk, located in the center of the village on the Markt (market square). The Gothic-style building is a national monument. It is dedicated to James the Greater, the patron saint of pilgrims to Santiago de Compostella. James is depicted three times as a pilgrim in the church. The church tower is 57 meters high and bears a strong resemblance to the tower of the St. Walburgakerk in Ramsdorf, just across the border in Germany. The current Jacobskerk in Winterswijk was built in the second half of the 15th century.

name: Jacobus de Meerderekerk
description: The Jacobus de Meerderekerk is a Roman Catholic church in Bocholtz, Netherlands. It's a three-aisled, neo-Gothic basilica in the shape of a cross. The church was originally built between 1869 and 1873 by Pierre Cuypers. In 1953, Harry Koene expanded the church by adding a larger choir, a second transept, and a sacristy. The extension protrudes beyond the original transepts. The church has a black marble baptismal font from 1796 and a wooden crucifix from the 19th century. The parish was established in 1794 and legalized in 1803.

name: Jacobuskerk
description: The Jacobuskerk in Utrecht is a former Old Catholic church located on the Bemuurde Weerd. Initially, a hidden church stood on this site in the 16th century, serving the parish of the Jacobikerk outside the city walls. The current church building was consecrated on December 14, 1870. In 1986, the church was closed, and in 1989, it was sold to a furniture maker and antiquarian. Later, in 2009, it was sold again and transformed into a residential house. The church was designed by architect G. Gerritsen and consecrated by the Old Catholic Archbishop Henricus Loos.

name: Jacobuskerk
description:
The Jacobuskerk is a medieval church located in the center of Winterswijk on the Market Square. Roads from the four neighborhoods of Meddo, Ratum, Woold, and Miste converge at the square. The Gothic-style building is a national monument dedicated to Jacobus the Greater, the patron saint of pilgrims to Santiago de Compostella.

The church's history dates back to the 8th century. Around 1400, the Romanesque choir was replaced by an early Gothic choir. During a restoration between 1968 and 1972, remains of an earlier wooden church were not found, but foundations of a small stone church from around 1200 were discovered. The church features a large mural on the north wall of the choir and depictions of Jacobus as a pilgrim.

name: Jacobuskerk
description:
The Jacobuskerk in Zeerijp is a medieval cruciform church featuring a detached bell tower. It showcases Romanesque and early Gothic elements. Construction began around the end of the 13th century and was completed around 1350. The church was built in late Romano-Gothic style and has hardly been changed since its construction.

Inside, the walls have brick imitations, and the pointed arched vault fields also feature brick imitations in varying shades and patterns. An organ, pulpit, piscinas, and mourning boards complete the interior. The church also contains almost 40 tombstones, some dating back to the 16th century.

name: Janskerk
description:
The Janskerk, or St. John's Church, is a former church located in Haarlem. Completed in 1318, it was part of the Commandery of St. John, one of the largest monasteries of the Knights Hospitaller in the Netherlands. The complex included a monastery, hospital, and the church.

The Janskerk is the oldest church in Haarlem that has been preserved in its original form. In 1936, it became the location of the Haarlem Archives, and following restorations between 1975 and 1980, it now houses the North Holland Archives. Many items from the church that weren't removed have survived and are in the Frans Hals Museum or the Museum Catharijneconvent in Utrecht.

name: Janskerk
description:
The Janskerk is a Romanesque basilica located on the Janskerkhof in the center of Utrecht. It is dedicated to John the Baptist and once served as a church for the chapter of St. John. Founded shortly after 1040 by Bishop Bernold, it was one of the city's five collegiate churches that formed the Utrecht church cross during the Middle Ages.

In 1580, Catholic worship was prohibited, and the Janskerk lost its function as a collegiate church. It was later used as a city library and then a university library. The Reformed Church acquired the church in 1656. After years of disrepair, the church was thoroughly renovated in the 20th century. Today, the Janskerk hosts classical and choral concerts and holds services by the Ecumenical Student Community of Utrecht.

name: Jeruzalemkerk
description:
The Jeruzalemkerk is a Protestant church located in the Amsterdam West district, in the neighborhood of De Baarsjes, near Mercatorplein. It was built between 1928 and 1929, designed by architect Ferdinand Jantzen. The original idea was to name it the Nieuwe Westerkerk, however the name Jeruzalemkerk was eventually chosen. This name came from the fundraising campaign "City without a Temple" used to finance the construction.

The church's architecture is a good example of the Amsterdam School style. It is built connected to the adjoining housing block. The exterior and interior contain many symbols. The stained-glass windows were also designed by Jantzen. The church is oriented north-south, unlike most churches which are oriented east-west.

name: Jezuïetenkerk
description: The Jesuit monastery on Bredestraat, also known as the First or Old Jesuit Monastery, was the first establishment of the Society of Jesus in Maastricht. The cornerstone was laid in 1606, and in 1614 the church was dedicated to Saints Peter and Paul. Originally, the barrel vault was painted with depictions of saints, but around 1750 it was replaced by a baroque stucco ceiling. The sacristy was located on the east side of the church on Bredestraat, supposedly the birthplace of Saint Lambert. Between the sacristy and the old chapel was a small courtyard surrounded by columns, called the atrium. After the Jesuit order was abolished in 1773, the Jesuits resettled in Maastricht in 1853. Of the first monastery remains the heavily altered monastery church (the current Bonbonnière) and a monastery wing.

name: Johannes Vianneykerk
description:
The Johannes Vianneykerk is a church building in Deventer, built in 1929 and listed as a national monument in 1999. It was designed by the local architect Martin A. Roebbers in the basilica style. The church has three naves under a gable roof with a roof turret. The altar is relatively shallow.

The sober expressionist design in clean brickwork makes extensive use of the geometric figure of the parabola. Stained glass in the church was made by the Lou Asperslagh studio in The Hague. Until 2014, it was used by the Roman Catholic parish of the same name.

In 2016, the Vianneykerk became the property of Peter Vredeveld, a dealer in Buddha statues and Asian art. The zoning plan has been amended to allow an art gallery in the church. With respect for the monumental value of the building, a gallery for Asian art was established there.

name: Johannes de Doperkerk
description:
The Johannes de Doperkerk, also known as Sint-Jan Baptistkerk, is a church building in the Limmel district of Maastricht. It has traditionally served as the parish church for the Roman Catholic parish of Johannes de Doper. The Neo-Gothic church, designed by architect Carl Weber in 1864, is not a national monument but was placed on Maastricht's municipal monument list in 2002.

It is a spacious three-aisled cruciform basilica featuring a transept and a chancel. The church contains some notable grave monuments. The church has 26 stained glass windows made between 1913 and 1919. These windows depict episodes from the life of John the Baptist. The church also possesses valuable statues and artifacts.

name: Johannes de Doperkerk
description:
The Johannes de Doperkerk in Blerick is a Roman Catholic church located at Sint-Jansplein. The parish split from the Sint-Lambertus parish in 1963, and a temporary church was put into use in 1964. Plans for a permanent church were delayed due to the death of the original architect and declining church attendance. Architect J. Buschman ultimately designed a smaller church than initially planned, which was consecrated in 1973.

It is a modernist hall church with a high, overhanging gable roof. Steel roof trusses extend to the ground, and the facade features glass windows that bring light into the almost windowless interior. The entrance is a short concrete corridor. The church and its annex have a rural appearance, and it is located on a raised area surrounded by elderly housing.

name: Johannes de Doperkerk
description: The Johannes de Doperkerk in Utrecht is a Roman Catholic parish church dedicated to John the Baptist. It is located on the Kanaalstraat. The church was built between 1930 and 1931 and was designed by architect H.W. Valk. It is a three-aisled basilica with a striking tower. The building style can be described as expressionistic. The church replaced an earlier, smaller church that had become too small for the growing parish. The church is still in use by the Roman Catholic parish of the same name.

name: Johannes de Doperkerk
description: The Johannes de Doperkerk, also known as the Hervormde Kerk, is a Protestant church in Oud-Vossemeer. It dates back to 1516, but before that, in 1452, there was already a chapel dedicated to Saint John the Baptist, the patron saint of Oud-Vossemeer. The chapel had to be demolished in 1516 due to a shortage of seating. Services are held every Sunday at 10:00 and 18:30. In 1917, A. Standaart built a new pneumatic cone valve organ for the Johannes de Doperkerk.

name: Johannes de Doperkerk
description:
The Johannes de Doperkerk is a Roman Catholic church in Keijenborg, Netherlands, built in 1932 and dedicated to John the Baptist. Before its construction, Catholic services were held in a barn church from 1710, rebuilt in 1784, and later replaced by a waterstaatskerk in 1843 due to its small size.

Designed by Jan Stuyt, the current church is a pseudobasilica incorporating interior elements from the previous waterstaatskerk. It features stained glass windows depicting religious scenes and murals by Jos ten Horn. The broad tower is at the rear, with smaller side entrances used as the main entry. A mosaic of St. John the Baptist by Antoon Molkenboer is above the main entrance. The church combines Gothic and Romanesque influences and is a municipal monument.

name: Johannes de Doperkerk
description:
The Johannes de Doperkerk, also known as Sint-Jan or Jan de Doperkerk, is a Roman Catholic church located in Kilder, in the municipality of Montferland. The church was built in 1886 and dedicated to John the Baptist. Before its construction, the residents of Kilder attended the Sint-Oswalduskerk in Zeddam until 1854, and subsequently the Sint-Maartenskerk in Wehl for thirty years.

Designed by Alfred Tepe in Neo-Gothic style, the church features a large pointed arch window above the entrance, which is integrated into the tower. The tower is topped with a spire and flanked by a staircase tower. Inside, there are several stained glass windows. A Sacred Heart statue stands to the left of the church, and to the right of the adjacent rectory is a statue of Mary Queen of Peace, donated by parishioners in 1946. The church is a municipal monument.

name: Johannes de Doperkerk
description: The Johannes de Doperkerk in Meddo is a former Roman Catholic church in the Netherlands. Constructed between 1863 and 1864, it was consecrated in December 1864, with John the Baptist as its patron saint. After being decommissioned in September 2022, the church has been transformed into a multifunctional space for the village community. Most of the Roman Catholic elements, such as paintings, statues, and the altar, have been removed, but a cross, the baptismal font, and a statue of Mary remain. The entrance is incorporated into the church tower, which features large vertical windows and is topped with a spire. The church is a hall church and has been designated as a municipal monument.

name: Johannes de Doperkerk
description: The Johannes de Doperkerk is the parish church of Baexem, located at Monseigneur Kierkelsplein 19. The church's history dates back to 1485 when it was first mentioned as an independent parish church. In 1928, the church was expanded under the architecture of Caspar Franssen, which included lengthening the side aisles. However, on November 15, 1944, the tower was blown up by German soldiers. After the war, a new church was built more centrally in the village, starting in 1949 and consecrated in 1950. The tower was constructed in 1956, designed by Alphons Boosten. The church is a oriented brick cross-basilica in Romanesque style with a round closed choir and a clock tower on the southern transept arm.

name: Johannes de Doperkerk
description: The Johannes de Doperkerk is a church building in Eygelshoven, in the municipality of Kerkrade. It is a broad cruciform church in an expressionistic style. The church consists of a nave with three bays, two transepts, a semicircular choir, and a tower on the southern cross arm. The base is made of Nievelsteiner sandstone, with higher parts in Maastricht tuff, red brick, and concrete. The tower has a constricted spire with an overhang and sound holes at the corners. The church was built in 1922, designed by Alphons Boosten and Jos Ritzen. Since 2001, the church has been a national monument.

name: Johannes de Doperkerk
description:
The Johannes de Doperkerk in Ottersum is a Roman Catholic church centrally located in the village. Built in 1931, the church stands near the rectory, cemetery, and former town hall. The design, by architect J. Schoenmakers, reflects Traditionalism with Expressionist elements.

The church features a polygonal floor plan, with the nave nestled between the tower and apse. A steep gable roof with slate tiles covers the nave, accented by triangular dormers. Cross arms extend from the apse side and the tower. The tower has an extended stairwell and is topped with a tented roof of slate.

Inside, the church boasts stained glass windows by Daan Wildschut, an art-deco altar, and a Pels organ. The electro-pneumatic church organ with 31 registers was built in 1948. The church is a national monument.

name: Johannes de Doperkerk
description:
The Johannes de Doperkerk in Oud-Valkenburg is a church building in the Dutch South Limburg municipality of Valkenburg aan de Geul. It is one of the oldest churches in the area and has been a national monument since 1967. The Roman Catholic parish church is dedicated to John the Baptist.

The oldest part of the church is the nave, built around 1050. The tower dates from the 15th or 16th century. In 1851, the church was restored and a northern side aisle was added. The interior has flat plastered ceilings in the nave and cross vaults in the choir. The Rococo main altar is attributed to the Couven workshop. The churchyard contains several crosses and tombs from the 17th and 18th centuries.

name: Johannes de Doperkerk
description: The Sint-Johannes de Doperkerk is a Roman Catholic church in Kaatsheuvel. The architect is Cornelis van Hoof. Construction started in 1909 and the church was consecrated in 1912. It is a neo-Gothic cruciform basilica with a double-tower front and a double entrance portal with a wimperg. The towers are approximately 59 meters high and are crowned by spires. The church has a round closed choir, just like the transepts. The interior of the church is covered by a yellow star vault. The church also has stained glass windows. The church has a wooden triumphal crucifix dating from 1750. The Stations of the Cross in the side aisles are from 1890. The church was restored in 2009 and is still used by the Kaatsheuvel parish.

name: Johannes de Doperkerk
description: The Johannes de Doperkerk in 's-Heer Abtskerke is a Gothic brick cruciform church with a free-standing western tower. It is dedicated to John the Baptist. The church is a monumental building dating from around the beginning of the 14th century. The tower is a sturdy structure from around 1400, decorated with buttresses and panels. Inside the tower is a vault. The church also features a bell made by Gillis van de Gilde in 1710, along with two modern bells. The church is used by the Protestant Church in the Netherlands.

name: Johannes de Doperkerk, sinds 2018 brouwerij
description: The Johannes de Doperkerk in Sint Jansteen is a neo-Gothic hall church built between 1857 and 1860. The architect is unknown, but it is in the style of stucco Gothic. It features a tower with an octagon and a needle spire, and an extended west portal. The church has three naves with simple brick forms. Inside, the central nave has a stuccoed wooden barrel vault with cross ribs, while the side naves have cross-ribbed vaults, also made of stuccoed wood. In 1898, it was expanded with transept-like, double chapels on either side. The church is no longer used for religious services; since 2018, the building has housed a brewery/distillery and event space.

name: Johanneskerk
description:
The Johanneskerk is a church building located at Westsingel 30 in Amersfoort. It's a fairly tall, brick hall church with a gently sloping gable roof, accessible by an imposing staircase. Built in 1963 in a functionalist style, it was designed by S. van Woerden and H.J. Schneider for the Association of Liberal Protestants.

Currently, the Johanneskerk is used by a collaboration of Liberal Protestants, Mennonites, and Remonstrants. Cultural events, such as concerts, also take place in the building. The church houses an organ built in 1965 by the Van Vulpen company. For a short time, it was also rented to the Orthodox Parish of Amersfoort.

name: Johanneskerk
description:
The Johanneskerk, also known as the Johannescentrum, is a Protestant church building in the Overvecht district of Utrecht. The church is dedicated to the evangelist John. It was built in the 1960s, along with the construction of the Overvecht district. The architect, L.J. Linssen, designed the building according to Protestant guidelines established in 1954, which emphasized unity in the church space, avoiding features like communion rails or colonnades. The windows were designed to provide soft lighting without distracting from the outside world.

In 2004, the Reformed and Protestant churches merged to form the Protestant Church in the Netherlands. The neighboring Catholic Emmaus Church closed in 1984, after which they were able to use the Johanneskerk monthly, bringing objects such as the tabernacle, a crucifix and a baptismal font, which are still found in the church.

name: Johanneskerk
description: The Johanneskerk in Heerde, Gelderland, Netherlands, likely dates back to the 15th century. The church features a late-Gothic tower, while the nave was constructed in 1923. The brick tower, partly clad in tuff stone, has an octagonal spire. In 1869, detailing with arches and stucco was added to the tower. The nave, designed in 1923 by architect J. or W. Pothoven from Amersfoort, has a Greek cross floor plan and is covered with slate. The church also has an organ that was built between 1843 and 1845.

name: Johanneskerk
description:
The Johanneskerk is a Protestant church in Lichtenvoorde, Netherlands. It was built in 1648 on the site of a former chapel, which had fallen into disrepair in the early 17th century. The chapel became a protestant church in 1616. The church was constructed as a hall church with a pointed tower.

In 1904, the church and tower were plastered. During World War II, the church bells were confiscated by German troops, and new bells were cast in 1949. The interior was renovated in 1936, and the organ was renovated in 1986. The pulpit from 1682 remains intact. The organ incorporates parts from the 18th century. The church is a national monument, with specific mention of the pulpit and organ.

name: Johanneskerk
description: The Johanneskerk in Kruiningen is a monumental Protestant church dating back to the 15th century. Built in the Brabant Gothic style, it features a three-aisled pseudo-basilica design. Originally a cruciform church, the choir was demolished during the Reformation. The ship is partly built of brick with white Brabant sandstone. Inside, the church has pillars with cabbage leaf capitals. The north transept was added in the early 16th century. The church houses a pulpit from 1596 and a Van Vulpen organ installed in 1958, replacing an older Van Dam organ.

name: Johanneskerk
description:
The Johanneskerk in Nieuwerkerk is a Protestant church belonging to the Dutch Reformed Church. A church existed on the site, or slightly to the north, as early as the 12th or 13th century. Around 1200, construction of a new church began, and in 1233, there was mention of an old and new church, Ouwerkerk and Nieuwerkerk. In 1475, construction started on a new church dedicated to Saint John the Evangelist, which lasted until 1509.

The interior is austere, typical of Reformed churches, featuring gentlemen's pews along the walls and oak chairs in the center, which were formerly reserved for women. The pulpit dates from the 17th century, and the silver baptismal font is intricately engraved and dates back to 1857. The hexagonal church tower was blown up by the German occupying forces on February 3, 1945, near the end of World War II. The tower was reconstructed in 1975 and reopened on March 9, 1976.

name: Joriskerk
description:
The Joriskerk in Borculo, Netherlands, is a late-Gothic church built in the 16th century. Originally the church of the nearby Hof, it later became a Roman Catholic parish church dedicated to Saint George. In 1616, it transitioned to a Protestant church after the Reformation.

The church features a small archivolt at the entrance, above which is a large embedded pointed arch window in the church tower, topped with a tent roof. The nave has an aisle only on the north side. The windows are mostly pointed arches and have stained glass. In 1925, the building suffered significant damage during a storm and was subsequently restored. During the restoration, cross-ribbed vaults were added to the nave under the gable roof and stained glass windows designed by Femmy Schilt-Geesink were placed in the choir. The church has two organs.

name: Jozef Arbeiderkerk
description:
The Jozef Arbeiderkerk was a church building in Huls, in the South Limburg municipality of Simpelveld, Netherlands. It was located on the main road through Huls from Simpelveld to Ubachsberg/Imstenrade, at the highest point of the hamlet.

The building was constructed of brick and consisted of a hall church with a gable roof and an apse. The church was dedicated to Saint Jozef Arbeider. The community decided to build the church at their own expense within the parish of Simpelveld. The church was built in 1955-1956 and consecrated on September 20, 1956. The church was deconsecrated on January 1, 2012, and completely demolished in February 2018.

name: Jozefkerk
description:
The Jozefkerk, previously known as the Grote Kerk until 1964, is located on Kerkplein 1 in Assen. It's a listed building designed in a neoclassicist style by C.J. Spaan, chief engineer of Waterstaat and Public Works. The church is characterized by its symmetry, arched windows, plastered interior walls, and cross-vaulted ceiling.

Originally, the Hervormde Gemeente held services in the Kloosterkerk from the early 17th century. As the population grew, a new building was needed. Construction started in 1845, and the church was inaugurated in 1848. In 1910, lightning struck the church, causing a fire that largely destroyed the tower, which was rebuilt a year later. The church was thoroughly restored between 1979 and 1982, and in 2021, renovations began.

name: Julianakerk
description:
The Julianakerk was a Dutch Reformed church located on the Rijnlaan in the city of Utrecht. It was commissioned in 1931 to serve the growing population of the Rivierenwijk neighborhood. The church was named after Princess Juliana.

The building was a simple hall church constructed in an expressionistic style, common during the Interbellum period. It featured a roof turret. The church housed a Witte organ, originally built in 1874 for the Geertekerk. When the Geertekerk closed, the organ was moved to the Julianakerk.

The Julianakerk was closed and demolished in 1983. After its closure, the organ was moved to the Hervormde church in Geervliet, where it remains today.

name: Juvenaatskapel Broeders van Maastricht
description: The Juvenaatskapel of the Broeders van Maastricht, is part of a former school, juvenate and monastery complex. The chapel is a single-nave structure featuring three window bays, each containing a triple window with stained glass and a round stained glass window above. The windows are framed by a round-arched brick surround. Buttresses covered with hard stone support the structure. Inside, the former monastery chapel retains much of its original character, including cross-ribbed vaults, stained glass windows, and murals. The murals are made by F.H. Bach.

name: Kandelaarkerk
description: The Kandelaarkerk is a former church located on Hamburgerstraat in the city of Groningen, Netherlands. It was built for the Reformed Churches Liberated, designed by architects Pit van Loo and Sikke van der Mei. In 1999, the congregation moved to the Oosterkerk. After a short period of use by an Antillean denomination, the building was sold in 2000. Since then, it has been used as a daycare center. The building is recognized as a municipal monument.

name: Kapel Capucijnenhof
description: The Capucijnenhof chapel, built in 1885, is a neo-classical structure. Its plastered and white-painted facade features four stucco pilasters, the central two supporting a fronton. The entrance, located centrally, has a profiled frame with volute shapes. There are three niches in the facade, which contain statues of saints. While the facade was largely preserved during a 1994 renovation, the side facades were significantly altered with modern windows. The building is part of a larger complex that was once a monastery and now functions as an apartment complex.

name: Kapel Hof van Sint-Monica
description: The Hof van Sint-Monica, formerly a Roman Catholic orphanage and Augustinian monastery, is now an apartment complex in the center of Maastricht. The building complex in the Jekerkwartier is partially classified as a national monument and partly as a municipal monument. The chapel is a neogothic monastery chapel with a staircase tower, and is characteristic of the neogothic style of J. Kayser. The chapel is sometimes used for exhibitions. The historical complex is a national monument, but the chapel itself is not.

name: Kapel Onze-Lieve-Vrouw ter Eecken
description:
The Kapel Onze-Lieve-Vrouw ter Eecken is a chapel located in the village of Kapellebrug, in the municipality of Hulst. Initially, the chapel may have been dedicated to Saint George, but the veneration of Mary later became more prominent.

A previous chapel stood on the site in 1578, which was a place of pilgrimage where people sought healing from fevers and illnesses. That chapel was demolished in 1686. In 1933, the foundations of the old chapel were discovered and it was decided to rebuild it. The current chapel was rebuilt in 1935 and is also known as the Mariakapel (Mary's Chapel). In 1990, the chapel and its garden were restored. Today, many people still visit the Ter Eecken chapel to light a candle or pray.

name: Kapel Pniël
description:
Kapel Pniël is a church building located in the Dutch city of Leeuwarden. The former church belonged to the protestant community. In 1925, the chapel replaced an older chapel. In 1936, the church was re-opened.

The pulpit was placed in the center. The organ was replaced with a theater organ from the Metropooltheater in Schiedam. It was made in 1933 by the Rotterdam organ builder Standaart. In August 2011, the Protestant Church took leave of the chapel. Later, the chapel was rented out to the Pentecostal church Elim for a few years. In 2015-2016, the church was converted into an annex of the Johan Willem Frisoschool, while the exterior remained unchanged.

name: Kapel Sint-Servaasgasthuis
description:
The chapel of the Sint-Servaasgasthuis was situated on the northwest side of the complex. Due to its forward position, both the north and east facades of the chapel were exposed to the Vrijthof. The choir faced east and was connected to a wing of the guesthouse, as was the south facade.

Initially Romanesque in appearance, the chapel was later rebuilt in the Gothic style at an unknown time. The north and west wings, which faced the Vrijthof, were renovated in 1571 in the Maasland Renaissance style, adorned with portrait medallions and cartouches.

name: Kapel Vincentiusvereniging
description:
The Kapel van de Vincentiusvereniging, also known as Vincentiuskapel and formerly Heilige Geestkapel, is a neo-Gothic chapel located in the center of Maastricht, Netherlands. It is hidden behind buildings on Jodenstraat and Kesselskade, making it not visible from the street.

The chapel was built around 1850 by priest Louis Hubert Rutten, who aimed to provide education for young workers in Maastricht's industries. He commissioned the chapel and a school in the garden behind his house for the Ursuline Sisters of Tildonk. In 1864, the sisters moved to their own monastery, and the chapel was then used by the Sint-Vincentiusvereniging, a Roman Catholic organization focused on poverty relief.

Today, the chapel is part of the Drukkunstmuseum (Printing Museum). The ground floor features a reconstruction of a pottery printing workshop from the Petrus Regout & Co factories. The upper floor exhibits the work of graphic artist René Glaser. Some original elements, such as windows, capitals, and furniture, remain, reflecting its original purpose. The chapel is recognized as a municipal monument.

name: Kapel in 't Zand
description:
The Kapel in 't Zand is a parish church and pilgrimage site located in Roermond. It is built in a predominantly neo-Gothic style, designed by architect Johannes Kayser. For a long time, it served as the monastery church of the adjacent Redemptorist monastery.

Legend says that a statue of the Virgin Mary was found at this location in 1435. The current chapel replaced an earlier chapel whose tradition dates back to the 15th century. The chapel is known throughout the Netherlands and beyond as a place where people come to pray to Our Lady in 't Zand. The procession corridor on the south side of the chapel is a later addition.

name: Kapel van Coelhorst
description:
The Kapel van Coelhorst, also known as Koelhorst or Keulhorst, is a chapel located on the Coelhorsterweg in Hoogland, in the municipality of Amersfoort. The Coelhorst Cemetery of the local Protestant community surrounds the chapel. It was built in the 14th century for the Koelhorst neighborhood.

The chapel is built on an artificial hill and oriented towards the east. It is a plastered, single-nave chapel, constructed from various types of stone. It features an 18th-century old Dutch roof structure consisting of a gable roof between pointed gables, with glazed roof tiles, and a small wooden bell tower. A bell from 1708 hangs in the tower. Inside the chapel are three tombs of the owners of the Coelhorst estate.

name: Kapel van Hoogelande
description:
The Kapel van Hoogelande is located in the hamlet of Hoogelande. In 1189, a chapel dedicated to Saint Martin was founded in Hoogelande. In the 15th century, the chapel was expanded into a small church, but it was largely destroyed during the Siege of Middelburg (1572-1574), with only a few wall remains of the choir remaining. In 1912, the chapel and its surroundings were purchased for hunting purposes.

The current building is built of brick in Gothic style. It has a three-sided closed choir, and the facade is decorated with a small bell gable, which does not contain any bells. The choir was restored in 1965, and planting was established around the chapel. Today, the building is used as a chapel, wedding and baptism location, and for cultural events. There is a cemetery for the residents of Hoogelande near the church.

name: Kapel van Onze-Lieve-Vrouw van Genooi
description:
The Chapel of Our Lady of Genooi is a small Roman Catholic chapel located in the north of Venlo. It was originally built in 1423, modeled after the chapel of Loreto in Italy. However, the current structure dates back to 1631. Over the years, it became a place of pilgrimage.

In 1916, the chapel was restored by Pierre Cuypers, who added a trefoil-shaped chancel extension. Inside, it features a wooden altar retable in the Louis XV style, crucifixes from around 1500 and the 17th century, and a Madonna statue. The chapel is dedicated to Our Lady, Help of Christians, and is considered the patroness of the city of Venlo.

name: Kapelkerk
description:
The Kapelkerk is a medieval church located in the old city center of Alkmaar. Originally, the Catholic Sint-Janskapel stood on this site. The church is used for weekly services by the Dutch Reformed Churches in Alkmaar.

The current Kapelkerk combines different styles, partly due to restorations. The southern part has a Gothic style, seen in the pointed arch windows. The northern part has a Dutch classicist style with a simple appearance, including a small tower with a dome. The interior has a unified style from after a fire. The pipe organ from 1762 was built by Christian Müller. The church was restored after the fire, and a new pulpit was installed.

name: Kathedrale basiliek Sint Bavo
description:
