The Kathedrale Basiliek Sint Bavo, also known as KoepelKathedraal Haarlem, is a significant church, ranking among the top five most important churches built between 1850 and 1950 worldwide. Joseph Cuypers designed the impressive cathedral, featuring twelve towers and a 65-meter-high dome. Its architectural styles include Neo-Gothic, Neo-Romanesque, Jugendstil, and elements of the Amsterdam School and Berlage.

Construction occurred in three phases between 1895 and 1930. The interior is renowned for its stained glass windows and mosaics. The church was elevated to a basilica in 1948.

name: Keizersgrachtkerk
description: The Keizersgrachtkerk, originally a Reformed Church, was built in 1888 on the Keizersgracht in Amsterdam. Designed by architects Gerlof Bartholomeus Salm and Abraham Salm, it's located at number 566, between Leidsestraat and Nieuwe Spiegelstraat. The church community is known for its accessible liturgy, with a focus on music and children. The design of this church is in a neo-Gothic style which is quite rare. The facade is very striking between the canal houses on Keizersgracht.

name: Kerk aan de Fok
description: The Kerk aan de Fok is a church building in Heerenveen, in the province of Friesland. This neoclassical church was built in 1867 for the Reformed Church in the former municipality of Aengwirden. Later, a portal was added to the hall church. The organ, built in 1872 by L. van Dam and Zn., was restored in 1961 by Bakker & Timmenga. In the hall, there is a mural by Frits Klein. The church belonged to the Protestant Parish of Heerenveen, which also included the Kruiskerk and the Europalaankerk. The church was closed in 2012 and the building was sold in 2018. In 2020, seven rental apartments were realized in the building.

name: Kerk of kapel behorende bij kasteel De Haar
description: The church, or chapel, at Kasteel De Haar has been rebuilt almost from the ground up in neo-Gothic style. During construction, remains of ancestors of the baron were found. The walls are adorned with statues of saints, some dating back to the 14th century. Beneath the sacristy, a crypt was built in the 1950s, serving as the final resting place for members of the Van Zuylen family, with tombs inlaid with multicolored marble. The chapel is characterized by serenity and simplicity, with stained glass windows and colorful paintings. Today, the chapel is a wedding venue and can seat 120 guests.

name: Kerk van Beets
description:
The Church of Beets is a late Gothic, single-nave cruciform church located in the North Holland village of Beets. It was built in the first half of the 15th century. After the Reformation, the church was partially rebuilt for use as a town hall and as a school. In 1982, the Reformed Municipality of Zeevang transferred the church to the Old Dutch Churches Foundation. The municipality of Zeevang did the same with the upper council chamber in 2009. The church is recognized as a national monument.

The ceilings of the church are decorated with flower paintings instead of religious representations. The vaults in the church are decorated with wildflowers, and the council chamber contains a painting of the Tree of Life. These paintings were added in the 17th century. After the Reformation, the choir was separated from the rest of the church. A floor was installed in the choir, creating space for the town hall of the municipality of Beets-Oudendijk and the local village school.

name: Kerk van Durgerdam
description:
The Dorpskerk Durgerdam, originally the Reformed church of Durgerdam, is a Protestant church located in Durgerdam in Amsterdam-Noord. It is not directly on the Durgerdammerdijk, but slightly behind it. The building has side walls structured by lesenes and a roof turret.

The chapel of Durgerdam started as a Roman Catholic church, with the first mention in 1499. In 1572, the Roman Catholic service was prohibited. In 1623, services were held again but then Reformed/Protestant. In 1642, when the church became too small, another church was built, and the Chapel continued to function as a town hall and the school was given more space.

name: Kerk van Holysloot
description:
The Kerk van Holysloot, also known as the Holyslootkerk or Het Witte Kerkje (The Little White Church), is a Dutch Reformed church located on Dorpsstraat 30 in Holysloot, in the rural area of Amsterdam-Noord. Since 2006, the church has been used by the Protestant Municipality of Ransdorp-Holysloot.

The first stone was laid on September 9, 1846. The single-nave church is entirely plastered white and stands on a gray cemented plinth. The church is covered with a gable roof. The tower, located on the west side, is partially built into the church. The tower is crowned with a slate-covered spire, featuring a cross and a weather vane in the shape of a rooster. The Gothic character is accentuated by pointed arch windows, with three on both the north and south facades. The consistory is located on the east side of the church.

name: Kerk van Janum
description:
The church of Janum is a religious building in the village of Janum, in the municipality of Noardeast-Fryslân. The single-nave church made of red brick dates back to the 13th century and is located on a terp. The slightly narrower chevet, from the early 13th century, has a seven-sided exterior and a semi-circular interior with colonnettes. The nave, with its round-arched windows with Romanesque-Gothic bead profiles, dates from the late 13th century.

In the 16th century, the roof was renewed, and the original domed vaults were demolished. The church received a hanging bell cage on the west facade, similar to the Sint-Vituskerk in Wetsens. The bell dates from 1489. The church may have belonged to the Klaarkamp monastery in Rinsumageest. Since 1947, the church has been an outpost of the Frisian Museum.

name: Kerk van Jezus Christus van de Heiligen der Laatste Dagen
description: The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints in Groningen is a church building of the religious community of the same name, also known as the Mormons, in the southwestern district of Corpus den Hoorn. The building, located on the northwestern corner of Paterswoldseweg and Laan Corpus Den Hoorn, was designed by the Rotterdam architect M.C.A. Meischke and was put into use in 1969. The construction costs amounted to approximately 400,000 guilders, of which approximately 80% was paid by the American mother church. The church is a characteristic modern church with a tower.

name: Kerk van Laren
description:
The Kerk van Laren, also known as the Hervormde Kerk, is a Protestant church in Laren, Gelderland, Netherlands. It was built between 1834 and 1835, designed by architect B. van Zalingen. The church replaced an older church that had become dilapidated by 1835.

Initially known as the waterstaatskerk, because Rijkswaterstaat managed the construction, the church suffered heavy damage in 1945 when occupying forces detonated the adjacent rectory. The reconstruction significantly altered the church's appearance. Neo-Gothic steel windows were replaced with round, wooden arched windows, and the interior was transformed into a hall church with a beamed ceiling replacing the stuccoed one. The entrances were also relocated and modified. The church reopened in 1949, and the interior has been renovated in recent years, featuring liturgical furniture designed and crafted by local cabinetmaker René Bruns.

name: Kerk van Menaldum
description: The church of Menaldum is located in the town of Menaldum in the Dutch province of Friesland. Originally dedicated to Lambertus, a new church was built on the foundations of an older church. The five-sided closed choir dates from 1855 and the nave from 1874. The hall church with round-arched windows, a transept, and a consistory was built in eclectic forms to plans by M. and J.P. Boonstra. The three-section tower with a constricted spire was built in 1866 to a design by architect J.I. Douma. Inside the tower hangs a clock (1473) by clock founder Johannes van Deventer and a clock (1619) by Hans Falck. The interior is covered by a barrel vault. The walls have pilasters with Corinthian capitals. The pulpit (1672) was made by Gerryt Nijhoff.

name: Kerk van O.L. Vrouw Onbevlekt Ontvangen
description:
The Church of Our Lady of the Immaculate Conception in Amstenrade is a Roman Catholic parish church dedicated to the Immaculate Conception of Mary. The church was constructed between 1852 and 1856, designed in an early neo-Gothic style by Carl Weber. Later, from 1932 to 1933, J. Cuypers and P. Cuypers Jr. expanded the church, adding a double transept and rebuilding the choir with an ambulatory.

The church features a hall church design with three naves, a three-sided closed choir, and two west towers with constricted spires. Inside, the church has plastered wooden ribbed vaults. The green copper spires are a striking feature. A notable organ, made by Pereboom and Leyser in 1865, is positioned on either side of a large window. The church also contains a Romanesque baptismal font, a lords box, and mourning shields.

name: Kerk van Ransdorp
description:
The Church of Ransdorp has a striking tower dating back to the early sixteenth century. The location's history goes back to the Middle Ages. The tower is a reminder of the flourishing shipping, trade and industry that the village experienced, especially in the fifteenth century.

The church is located in rural North Amsterdam, close to the city center. It can be hired for dinners, receptions, presentations, workshops, weddings and concerts. The church is located on the village square and has a large, beautiful garden. Around 1650, Rembrandt van Rijn made several sketches and drawings of the tower.

name: Kerk van Ruigoord
description:
The Kerk van Ruigoord, also known as the Sint-Gertrudiskerk, is a former Roman Catholic church located in the village of Ruigoord in the province of Noord-Holland, Netherlands. Designed by C.P.W. Dessing, it was dedicated to Saint Gertrude of Nivelles and features a statue of her holding a staff with mice.

In 1973, the church was decommissioned due to planned demolition of the entire village. However, in July 1973, Amsterdam artists took over the building and rectory. Since then, the church has served as a cultural center, hosting exhibitions, concerts, and various events. It is considered the spiritual heart and a meeting place of Ruigoord, playing a central role in the village's cultural activities. The building dates back to around 1880 and underwent restoration work starting in 2021 to preserve it for the future.

name: Kerk van Terwolde
description: The Kerk van Terwolde is a Protestant church located in the village of Terwolde in the Gelderland province of the Netherlands. The church's choir and tower date back to the late Middle Ages. The nave was raised and enlarged with a side aisle in 1540. Inside the church, a large painting of the giant Christopher carrying Jesus on his back, dating from the late fifteenth century, can be found in the choir. The medieval village church has 16th-century murals and a medieval baptismal font. The church was likely built in the 13th century and dedicated to Saints Cosmas and Damianus, and rebuilt around 1400 and 1540 into its current form.

name: Kerk van West-Souburg, gesloopt in 1833
description:
The Kerk van West-Souburg was a church building in the Zeeland village of West-Souburg. It was possibly dedicated to Saint Martin. The church was largely destroyed by war between 1572 and 1574.

It was an own church of the Bishop of Utrecht, who therefore also had the tithe rights. The West-Souburg parish church was built in the first half of the 11th century and is first mentioned in written sources in the year 1167. The church of West-Souburg was one of the five mother churches on Walcheren. Daughter churches were the churches of Oud- and Nieuw-Vlissingen, Ritthem, Oost-Souburg and Nieuwerve.

name: Kerk van Zunderdorp
description:
The Kerk van Zunderdorp is a Dutch Reformed church located in Zunderdorp, Amsterdam-Noord. It's a plastered hall church with buttresses, built in 1711 against the late Gothic tower of the previous church, which lacks buttresses.

In the 11th century, the first residents settled here and built their first church. Little is known about that church. The tower was built in the late Middle Ages. The church contains a single-manual organ, delivered by the Goldschmeding company in 1907. The church is characterized by its traditional Dutch design, featuring a charming bell tower. Inside, soft light filters through stained glass windows, illuminating the church's interior.

name: Kerk van de Evangelische Gemeente Maastricht
description:
The Church of the Evangelical Community of Maastricht is a house of worship of the independent evangelical community in the Dutch city of Maastricht. The building is located near the Brusselse Poort shopping center, on the corner of Aesculaapstraat and Eenhoornsingel. It's a relatively inconspicuous gray brick building with a flat roof, designed by architect Frits Corten.

A striking red brick section with a brick pattern of crosses and two metal crosses that rise above the facade is central to the front facade. To the left is the entrance under a brown painted awning with the name "Evangelische Gemeente". The building is surrounded by lawns on two sides. The interior has an informal layout with chairs and a lectern.

name: Kerk van het Apostolisch Genootschap
description:
The Kerk van het Apostolisch Genootschap in Groningen is located on the Vestdijklaan in the De Wijert-Zuid neighborhood. The building, which the Apostolisch Genootschap calls a "Plaats van Samenkomst" (Place of Assembly), was originally built in 1973.

In 2003, the building underwent a large-scale renovation and expansion designed by the Rotterdam architectural firm MK Architecten. The renovation retained three outer walls and the roof, with the rest being new construction. The renovation and expansion were designed to be inspiring during services and in meetings with each other. The hall where the services take place has chairs placed towards each other, the stage is lowered and a canvas ceiling provides special lighting. Where the building was previously closed and inward-looking, the renovation has broken open the building both inward and outward, creating more transparency and openness with contemporary materials and techniques. It can accommodate 278 churchgoers.

name: Kerkelijk Centrum Emmaüs
description: The Kerkelijk Centrum Emmaüs in Ede is a modern church building located in the heart of the Rietkampen district. It is situated at Laan der Verenigde Naties 94. The Emmaüs Church was built for the Emmaüs Ede congregation, which still manages the building. The Kleopasgemeente uses the building for Sunday services and other activities during the week. Although the church center does not have stained glass windows, artist Henk Heidenvel from Zwolle created the windows as part of the ART IN THE CHURCH project, giving that impression. The Emmaüs church is an ecumenical community and a collaboration of churches in Ede.

name: Kerkelijk Centrum Emmaüs
description: The Kerkelijk Centrum Emmaüs in Ede is an ecumenical center resulting from a collaboration of churches in Ede. It is described as a place that is connected, open, free, and searching. Weekly services are held every Sunday at 10:30 AM, featuring varied leaders and musical accompaniment. The center functions as a multipurpose building, offering spaces for training sessions, meetings, cultural events, and church activities. It provides the amenities of a modern meeting center and is utilized by schools and various organizations.

name: Kerkje "De Rietstap"
description:
Kerkje "De Rietstap" is a small church building located in the former neighborhood of Het Beggelder near Dinxperlo, in the municipality of Aalten. It is known as the smallest church in the Netherlands.

The church belongs to the 'De Rietstap' estate. Originally owned by the Counts of Culemborg, the estate was later purchased by the Te Rietstap family. In 1874, Gerhard Hendrik A.N. te Rietstap from The Hague, a relative of the Te Rietstaps from Dinxperlo, bought the estate. He stipulated that a chapel be built on the property with a painting depicting the crucifixion of Jesus.

Today, the church, a listed national monument included in the Guinness Book of Records, functions as a free exhibition space. It can accommodate 12 to 15 people and is open on Sunday afternoons, and also on Wednesdays during the summer. A new art collection is displayed every month, featuring works by artists from Dinxperlo and beyond.

name: Kerkje aan de Zee
description:
The Kerkje aan de Zee is the oldest church building in Urk, built in 1786 on the site of an older church. The church is owned by the Church Council of the Reformed Church of Urk, and the church tower is owned by the municipality of Urk. The church has the status of a national monument.

The church does not hold regular Sunday services, but wedding services are still held there. Special services are sometimes organized in the Urk dialect during the winter, known as Urk Vespers. Inside the church, there are two ship models: a merchant ship and a botter.

Above the main entrance, a memorial stone displays four coats of arms, including those of West Friesland and Holland, the high lordship of Urk and Emmeloord, Amsterdam, and the family coat of arms of Henrick Hooft, mayor of Amsterdam and lord of Urk. The stone also features symbols like an anchor, a bible, and a burial lamp, the latter referring to the church's additional function as a burial site.

name: Kerkje van Harkema
description: The Kerkje van Harkema, located in the Groningen countryside, is a unique church built in the late 20th century by farmer Albert Harkema and volunteers between 1985 and 1998. Inspired by a former monastery farm on the site, Harkema first spent 30 years digging and expanding a moat around his farm. He then created a miniature of a traditional farmhouse before embarking on his life's work: the church. The church includes an organ, a pulpit, pews, and Marian figures. Harkema initially planned only a tower but expanded the project to include a chapel and then the entire church. He later added a teahouse in the style of the Aduard monastery church.

name: Keurhorsterkerk
description:
The Keurhorsterkerk is a Protestant church located in Sinderen, Netherlands, north of the town center on the road to Varsseveld. Its location stems from its origins as a Reformed church, facing resistance when trying to purchase land near Sinderen.

Built in 1887, this hall church features a neo-Gothic style. A square stone church tower with three sections adorns the street side, topped with a constricted spire. Lancet windows decorate the facades. The church is designated as a municipal monument. The construction of the new church was partially funded by donations from residents who had emigrated to North America.

name: Kloosterkapel Opveld
description:
The Kloosterkapel Opveld, located in the Heer district of Maastricht, is the former monastery church of Klooster Opveld. Situated behind the monastery in a beautiful monastery garden, it's considered a gem designed by Maastricht architect Theophile van Kan. Built in the early twentieth century, it features a triumphal arch and a nave with round-arched windows.

Inside, the chapel is notable for its large blocks of marl that define the atmosphere, as well as the beautiful stained glass windows by Jean den Rooijen from Roermond. The building has an intimate feel and good acoustics, making it well-suited for concerts. The chapel has a cross-shaped floor plan, short transepts, an apse, and an ambulatory.

name: Kloosterkapel Zusters van het Arme Kind Jezus
description: The Refugie van Hocht, also known as Poort van Hocht or Hochterpoort, is a building complex located on Boschstraat in Maastricht. The largest building of the complex is at Boschstraat 69-71, the actual Refugie van Hocht. The white plastered facade has an impressive height and width, which is emphasized by a continuous balcony on the first floor with a cast iron balustrade. The window shutters on the first three floors provide a vertical element. In the northern side facade on the Hochterpoort street, a fragment of a late Gothic cross window with an accolade arch has been preserved. There are also some stones built into the rear facade of Boschstraat 71.

name: Kloosterkerk
description:
The Kloosterkerk, also known as the abbey church, originally belonged to the Mariënkamp Cistercian nunnery in Assen. A charter mentions the presence of the monastery in 1276, but it was probably already established in Assen in 1260.

The Reformed community of Assen held its services in the Kloosterkerk for over two centuries. In 1810, a gallery was built in the church, and in 1817, the building was extended on the east side with a choir closure, making the building approximately 12 meters longer. After the Reformation, the Kloosterkerk could not be used for Reformed church services because the tower collapsed in 1601, severely damaging the church and rendering it unsuitable for use.

name: Kloosterkerk
description: The church in Aduard is the only remaining building of the former St. Bernard Abbey, one of the largest monasteries in Europe during the Middle Ages. This Romano-Gothic building was constructed in the early 14th century and originally served as the monastery's infirmary. Later, it was repurposed as a church. Today, it stands as part of the adjacent Monastery Museum. Inside the church, a large screen divides the space, depicting the building's original use as an infirmary. The furnishings are Protestant, but the walls and ceiling have been returned to their original state.

name: Kloosterkerk
description: The church at Klooster Ter Apel is split into two sections. One side was where the monks worshipped, featuring choir stalls lining the walls where they could sit or lean on misericords during long services. These misericords were carved with faces meant to inspire contemplation. The other half of the church was for local villagers and passing traders, who attended Sunday services there. The church is part of the original monastery buildings which were carefully preserved and restored in the 1930s. Vaults in the church were demolished in 1837. Today, the former lay church of the monastery still functions as a reformed church.

name: Kloosterkerk Commanderij Nieuwen Biesen
description: The website mentions a kloosterkapel (monastery chapel) associated with the Commanderij Nieuwen Biesen. The oldest depiction of the Maastricht commandery and its associated monastery chapel is a quick sketch related to legal documents concerning a conflict between Borgharen and Valkenburg around 1500. This sketch shows the Maas river, the Schonenvaardersbolwerk, and an unclear complex representing the Nieuwen Biesen. A more detailed depiction of the rebuilt commandery after 1411 can be found on Simon de Bellomonte's city panorama from around 1570. The buildings were rebuilt after 1586.

name: Kloosterkerk Zusters Onder de Bogen
description: The Kloosterkerk of the Zusters Onder de Bogen is a three-aisled, neo-Gothic church, built in 1899-1900 by contractor J. Reggers, designed by architect Johannes Kayser. The church has a cruciform floor plan with a pentagonal apse, transept arms with flat ends, and extended chapels on the west side. The whole building is made of brick, laid in a cross bond. The nave has four bays separated by tapering buttresses with hard stone covering. Inside, the ten black marble columns, partition walls with triforia, and stained glass windows are remarkable features. The pointed arches and windows are framed alternately with red and yellow brick.

name: Kluizenarij Onze Lieve Vrouwe van de Besloten Tuin
description: The Kluizenarij Onze Lieve Vrouwe van de Besloten Tuin, located in Warfhuizen, is a Roman Catholic hermitage. It was established in 2001 in the former Reformed church, which was built in 1858. The church building has a five-bay structure with a three-sided closure, and its walls are articulated by pilasters. The tower contains an old bell originating from the tower in Oldenzijl. The church now serves as a place of pilgrimage dedicated to Our Lady of the Enclosed Garden. Since 2015, the Eucharist is celebrated daily in Latin according to the traditional missal.

name: Koepelkerk
description:
The Koepelkerk in Leeuwarden, designed by Tj. Kuipers and built from 1921 to 1923, is a national monument notable for its Byzantine appearance. Initially a church, it exemplifies a mix of architectural styles, primarily rationalism, with Jugendstil details and Expressionist influences in the windows.

The church features a hexagonal central space under a ten-sided dome, complemented by three arms with rose windows, arranged in an arrow shape. Following its closure as a church in 2011, it was sold and transformed into a theater in 2015, now known as the Koepeltheater, hosting conferences and cultural events.

name: Koepelkerk
description:
The Koepelkerk in Amsterdam, originally built between 1668 and 1671 by Adriaan Dortsman, served as a Lutheran church. Its unique dome design was a result of religious restrictions on building towers. In 1822, the church was nearly destroyed by fire, but it was rebuilt with a raised dome. The famous Johann Bätz organ was installed in 1830, which remains one of the largest organs in the Netherlands.

Until 1935, it functioned as a house of worship before becoming a concert hall and event venue. Following a thorough renovation in 1975, the church was transformed into a unique conference and event location. Today, the Koepelkerk is part of the Renaissance Amsterdam Hotel and hosts various events, including weddings, congresses, and fashion shows.
